<FIRST>r a AM-Cameras-Court     03-14 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cameras-Court,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Lawyer: Courtroom Cameras Helped My Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Live television coverage of the Joel
Steinberg murder trial helped turn a ``lynch mob'' atmosphere into a
serious deliberative process, the convicted child killer's lawyer
said Monday.
   Ira London told state legislators that he and Steinberg initially
objected to the cameras, but he changed his mind.
   ``A television camera has a chemical effect on people,'' London
said. ``It makes people more serious.''
   Cameras have been allowed in New York state courtrooms on an
experimental basis since Dec. 1, 1987. The Legislature is
considering whether to extend the experiment or make it permanent.
   Both chairmen of the Legislature's judiciary committees have
predicted the Senate and Assembly would extend the experiment beyond
its May 31 expiration date.
   London, whose client was convicted in January of first-degree
manslaughter in the death of his illegally adopted 6-year-old
daughter when the jury declined to convict Steinberg of murder, said
he'd like to see a permanent law passed using the regulations
currently in place.
   There was a ``lynch mob mentality'' against Steinberg in New York
City as the case began, but jurors worked hard to be fair, said
London. ``I think the television cameras had a lot to do with
that,'' he said.
   London dismissed as ``misguided'' critics who argue the presence
of cameras would trivialize trials and alter the behavior of
participants. He said the public received an education in the
criminal justice process.
   Several full days of testimony in the Steinberg trial were
broadcast on New York City television stations, and lengthy excerpts
were broadcast nationwide on Cable News Network.
</TEXT>
