<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     03-14 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lean on Me'' Edges Out `Police Academy 6' at Box Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Lean on Me,'' the story of crusading New
Jersey high school principal Joe Clark, was first in box office
revenue for the second-consecutive weekend.
   ``Lean on Me,'' which grossed $4.5 million last weekend, was
followed by the cop farce ``Police Academy 6,'' which earned $4
million in its debut.
   It was considered a poor opening for a ``Police Academy'' sequel.
Last year, the fifth installment had opening weekend receipts of
$6.1 million.
   Taking third was John Ritter's ``Skin Deep'' with $3.9 million.
The debut of the romantic comedy ``Chances Are,'' featuring
``Moonlighting'' TV star Cybill Shepherd, took in $3.7 million to
place fourth.
   In fifth was the teen comedy ``Bill and Ted's Excellent
Adventure,'' with $3.4 million.
   Oscar contender ``Rain Man,'' in its 13th week of release, got
$3.1 million worth of business on 1,571 screens to take sixth. ``The
'burbs'' was seventh, ``New York Stories'' was eighth, ``Dangerous
Liaisons'' was ninth and ``Cousins'' was 10th.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Lean on Me'' Warner Bros., $4.5 million, 991 screens, $4,621
per screen, $11 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Police Academy 6,'' Warner Bros., $4 million, 1,627 screens,
$2,478 per screen, $4 million, one week.
   3. ``Skin Deep,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.9 million, 1,062 screens,
$3,688 per screen, $7.2 million, two weeks.
   4. ``Chances Are,'' Tri-Star, $3.7 million, 837 screens, $4,378
per screen, $3.7 million, one week.
   5. ``Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure,'' Orion, $3.4 million,
1,314 screens, $2,551 per screen, $21.8 million, four weeks.
   6. ``Rain Man,'' MGM-UA, $3.1 million, 1,571 screens, $1,999 per
screen, $126 million, 13 weeks.
   7. ``The 'burbs,'' Universal, $2.6 million, 1,710 screens, $1,525
per screen, $28.1 million, four weeks.
   8. ``New York Stories,'' Disney, $2.4 million, 511 screens,
$4,716 per screen, $3 million, two weeks.
   9. ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' Warner Bros., $1.7 million, 718
screens, $2,333 per screen, $21.2 million, 12 weeks.
   10. ``Cousins,'' Paramount, $1.6 million, 708 screens, $2,225 per
screen, $15.8 million, five weeks.
</TEXT>
