<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Chile-Whales     03-14 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Chile-Whales,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dozens Of Whales Stranded at Strait Of Magellan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUNTA ARENAS, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 whales grounded on a beach in
the Strait of Magellan in the third similar incident in a week, the
navy reported.
   It said the black-skinned whales, measuring about 10 feet to 25
feet long, were spotted stranded about 20 miles north of this port
city. A rescue party was sent to try to help the whales return to
the sea, the navy said.
   Last week, around 140 whales grounded on the strait's coast. Most
were helped back to the sea by navy personnel and fishermen, but
many died, according to the navy.
   Some experts speculated that an unusual warming of the normally
frigid waters in the area may have caused the whales' directional
system to go awry.
</TEXT>
