<FIRST>r a PM-People-Rivera     03-14 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Rivera,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Geraldo to the Rescue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENDWELL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talk show host Geraldo Rivera helped two
nuns and a businesswoman change a flat tire on their car after it
broke down in his posh New York City neighborhood, one of the women
says.
   ``What a nice man,'' said Janet Schiavone, a hair salon owner of
who lives in this town near Binghamton.
   Schiavone said she and two friends, both nuns from New York City,
were driving near Central Park on the evening of March 5 when their
car got a flat tire.
   Schiavone said she was struggling to change the tire when a man
walking his dog offered to help.
   ``I was having a hard time, so I said `sure,''' she recalled.
``(Then) one of the sisters recognized him.''
   Rivera, whose reputation for sensationalism took off last year
when his nose was broken during an on-air brawl with white
supremacists, changed the tire. When the women's car wouldn't start,
he brought his car to try to jump-start it and then tried pushing
the vehicle with his own, Schiavone said.
   ``He pushed us for 10 blocks. We were going to stop him after
five, but we were having so much fun.''
   Rivera left the women in his car to keep warm while they waited
for help and gave them his address so they could return the key,
Schiavone said. He walked home with his dog, Spike, a black Labrador
retriever.
   A spokesman for Rivera, Lynn Lazaroff, confirmed Schiavone's
account. She said Rivera is ``that kind of guy.''
</TEXT>
