<FIRST>r a AM-RighttoDie     03-14 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Right to Die,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-to-Die Case Appealed to U.S. Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of comatose 31-year-old
woman asked the U.S. Supreme Court on Monday to overturn a decision
by the state's highest court preventing them from removing their
daughter's feeding tube so she can die.
   In November, the Missouri Supreme Court ruled 4-3 that Joe and
Joyce Cruzan could not order the removal of the surgically-implanted
tube providing food and water for their daughter Nancy, a 1983
car-wreck victim.
   ``This will give Nancy another chance to have her wishes carried
out through her parents,'' attorney Bill Colby said in a telephone
interview from his Kansas City law office. He represents Ms. Cruzan
and her parents, who are their daughter's court-appointed guardians.
   Attorney General William Webster's office said it would file a
response to the Cruzans' appeal but did not think the Supreme Court
would find a constitutional issue in the case.
   ``The U.S. Supreme Court has never extended the right of privacy
to permit a patient or guardian to direct the withdrawal of food or
water, which are the basic necessities of life,'' Webster said in a
statement.
   Doctors say Ms. Cruzan of Carthage has been in a persistent
vegetative state since the accident and could live another 30 or 40
years with daily feedings through the tube implanted in her stomach.
   ``We know Nancy would not want the treatment she is receiving,''
Cruzan said in a statement from Colby's office. ``What right does
the state of Missouri have to tell us that ... her wishes and our
wishes do not matter at all?''
   The appeal argues that Ms. Cruzan's federal constitutional rights
to liberty, privacy and equal protection were ignored by the
Missouri Supreme Court when it refused to side with her parents,
Colby said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
