<FIRST>r a AM-Navajos-MacDonald     03-14 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navajos-MacDonald,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Withholds Navaho Trust Funds; Cites Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs
notified Navajo officials Monday that the agency will not release
any tribal trust funds until there is a resolution of a power
struggle involving Chairman Peter MacDonald.
   James Stevens, Navajo Area director for the BIA, said his letter
to tribal officials does not involve such basic governmental
services as welfare and law enforcement and is expected to have
little immediate impact.
   Rather, Stevens said, he intended to ``put the tribe on notice''
and encourage the factions in tribal government to resolve the
dispute.
   The Tribal Council voted last month to place MacDonald on paid
administrative leave in the wake of corruption allegations aired
during U.S. Senate hearings. MacDonald has contested the legality of
that move and others by the council, insisting that he is still in
charge.
   Last week, MacDonald ordered two tribal officials fired and had
tribal police change the locks on the Navajo council and legislative
buildings.
   Tazbah McCullah, a spokeswoman for MacDonald, said officials in
the chairman's office Monday were studying Stevens' letter to
determine its impact on tribal operations.
   Stevens said the restriction applies to release of trust funds
from such sources as timber, coal and oil leases. He said the
Navajos periodically draw on the funds, mostly for tribal
administrative costs.
   He said the BIA acted because it is unable to determine who is in
charge of the tribe, the nation's largest.
   Stevens declined to say how much money was involved.
</TEXT>
