<FIRST>r w PM-USBishops-Vatican     03-14 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US Bishops-Vatican,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Bishops Deny Being Taken to Vatican Woodshed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's Roman Catholic bishops deny they were
summoned to Rome to be chided for waywardness and say their four-day
meeting at The Vatican won't affect the document they are preparing
on women and the church.
   At a news conference Monday after their return, the bishops said
their meeting showed that Pope John Paul II is aware of the
particular problems the church faces in the United States.
   ``We have a heightened sense that Pope John Paul and the members
of the Curia understand our situation and support us in our work _
that they recognize that it is no easy job to be a bishop,
especially in America,'' Archbishop John May of St. Louis said.
   May, president of the U.S. Conference of Bishops, said,
``Clearly, there were some differences of perspective ... as might
be expected in any gathering of five dozen such people, but these
differences have to do with approach and not with doctrine.''
   Asked about reports that the bishops had been invited to Rome to
be chastised for taking too independent a course, Archbishop John
Quinn of San Francisco said: ``We never went to Rome with the
thought that we were to be chastised; we never said were going there
to be chastised; Rome never said we were going there to be chastised.
   ``That thought developed in areas completely apart from Rome or
the American bishops. I think we thought we were going there to sit
down as brothers and talk about the things that had surfaced during
the past several years.''
   May said the Vatican meeting would not result in any modification
of a document on women and the church which the U.S. Conference of
Bishops is preparing.
   ``There was no question about our document and its development,''
he said. ``We weren't advised and certainly never directed to modify
it.''
   Several questions touched on a statement by Cardinal Edouard
Gagnon, president of the Pontifical Council for the Family, that in
allowing women to help decide annulment cases ``we have to be
careful that their tender hearts do not play tricks on them.''
   ``I would agree with the women of the United States in their
consternation and their irritation about certain things that were
said,'' May told reporters.
   He said that in replying to Cardinal Gagnon's statement during
the meeting, ``We said that we believed the women on our tribunals
had served in a most remarkably effective way and some of the best
officers of our tribunals were women.''
</TEXT>
