<FIRST>r w PM-FarmCredit     03-14 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Credit,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Regional Banks Absorb Bulk of Bailout Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A total of $690 million has been spent by a new
federal board created to help bail out financially distressed banks
of the Farm Credit System, according to the board's first annual
report to Congress.
   The Farm Credit System Assistance Board's report said $629
million of that went to help regional banks in Jackson, Miss.;
Louisville, Ky.; Omaha, Neb.; and St. Paul, Minn.
   Eric P. Thor, president and the board's chief executive officer,
said the 1987 Farm Credit Act authorized the board ``to provide
financial assistance to eligible Farm Credit System lending
institutions and by so doing to help assure continuing credit
services to the nation's farmers and ranchers.''
   The law authorized up to $4 billion in aid to the beleaguered
system that was hit hard by declining land values, rising farm debt
and the inability of farm borrowers to pay their loan installments.
   From 1985 to 1987, the cooperatively owned Farm Credit System
alone had losses of more than $4.5 billion. Currently, the system
has about $55 billion in loans outstanding.
   The board is comprised of Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter,
Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Will Erwin, an Indiana farmer.
   ``System institutions, including those receiving financial
assistance from the (board), are making progress toward financial
viability but are not yet there,'' the report said.
   Funds are raised at the request of the board by the sale of
15-year Treasury guaranteed bonds. Interest on the bonds is paid by
the Treasury for the first five years, half by Treasury and half by
the system for the second five years, and entirely by the system in
the final five years.
   The system's institutions pay the principal upon maturity, plus
all interest initially funded by the Treasury.
   About $370.6 million in the first year of operation went to the
four banks to help them recover. In return, they had to carry out
reforms to put the institutions on sound footing.
   The four banks and their aid packages included: Federal Land Bank
of Jackson, $37.6 million; Farm Credit Bank of Louisville, $90
million; Farm Credit Bank of Omaha, $110 million; and Farm Credit
Bank of St. Paul, $133 million.
   In addition, the board assumed more than $258.4 million in
previous debt owed by those four as IOUs to financially healthy
other banks in the system under an earlier bailout arrangement.
There was no breakdown for that amount.
   The balance of the $690 million in expenditures included: board
expenses, $2 million; retirement of frozen borrower stock, $21
million; interest on promissory notes payable, $563,000; discount of
first bond sale, $2.25 million; and prefunding, $35.2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
