<DOCNO> AP890314-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     03-14 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Modern-day pilgrims who worry more
about flooded basements than fur trade with the Indians are upset
with the comeback the beaver population has made in Massachusetts.
   Wildlife biologists have stopped a beaver relocation program
because there is no corner of the state where the toothy rodents are
not entrenched.
   ``There's nowhere to put them,'' said Tom Decker, a biologist
with the state Division of Fisheries and Wildlife. ``You'd just be
moving your problem into somebody else's backyard.''
   The industrious animals, whose dams have resulted in flooded
basements, helped the state's first settlers survive, state
biologist James Cardoza said Monday. ``The beavers were the reason
they were able to sustain the colony because their sponsors wanted
to bargain with the Indians for furs,'' he said.
   By the Revolutionary War, however, beavers had disappeared from
Massachusetts and most of New England because of year-round trapping
and the drainage of wetlands for farming.
   After an absence of two centuries, two beaver colonies took hold
in Berkshire County in the 1920s.
   Among some of the biggest beaver headaches in Massachusetts in
recent years was a colony in the town of Montgomery that drew
spectators until the beavers set their sights in 1986 on a brook
flowing under Main Street.
   The animals built dams faster than work crews could demolish
them, threatening the main thoroughfare of the town of 500 people
and inspiring one resident to hang a sign bearing a score: ``Beavers
33, Waterworks 10, Highway Department 0.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SILT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Silt, a little town of about 1,200 people
along the Colorado River, is fighting off years of slurs and jokes
about its name with a new bumper sticker.
   ``Silt Happens.''
   The promotion is the brainchild of Silt resident Jim Bailey and
Steve Anderson, an advertising salesman for the Valley West Dispatch
in the nearby town of Parachute.
   Silt town administrator Jim Yale said the idea is ``to get
something to talk about and get something going in town.''
   Several years ago, the town board considered changing the name
because of the hard time the community gets about the name Silt.
   The new name of Pistol was proposed to capitalize on Rifle, a
larger community of about 5,000 people seven miles west of Silt.
   But a town councilor observed at the time that living in a town
called Silt ``is like being a boy named Sue _ it makes you tough.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The issue was food and the debate was non-existent
in the Georgia House as lawmakers worked past the supper hour on a
state spending plan.
   During a lull near suppertime Monday, House Speaker Tom Murphy
announced that a run would be made to the Varsity restaurant
downtown and had clerks program the electronic voting board for hot
dogs and hamburgers.
   The first vote came out for 93 hot dogs and 44 hamburgers.
   Murphy conducted another vote to see how many House members
wanted seconds. Seventy-eight wanted a second hot dog, and 50 wanted
another hamburger.
</TEXT>
