<FIRST>r w PM-LeagueofCities     03-14 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-League of Cities,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Officials Give Bush, Congress $14 Billion Shopping List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Municipal officials are pointing with
frustration to the proposed savings and loan bailout as they ask
Congress and the Bush administration to consider tax increases to
pay for urban aid.
   Members of the National League of Cities, the organization of
municipal leaders from cities of all sizes, were lobbying Congress
today armed with a list of suggestions for tax increases.
   At the same time they were voicing anger over proposed rescue
plans for the beleaguered S&amp;L industry, where estimates for the cure
range as high as $150 billion over years.
   ``The plan for helping banks with bad loans that they have
already written off and never should have made is moving ahead,
while funding for the war on drugs is a billion dollars short,''
said Mayor Terry Goddard of Phoenix, Ariz.
   ``Tell the Congress we can see through the scam,'' Goddard said.
``The deficit can no longer be used as an excuse to avoid setting
legitimate spending priorities.''
   The nearly 3,000 members conclude their annual winter meeting
today by spreading across Capitol Hill to meet with their
congressional delegations.
   The league's board of directors, meeting over the weekend, came
up with the list of 16 federal tax increases its members would
accept ``if our priorities are funded'' for urban needs.
   Goddard said the municipal leaders identified $14 billion in
requests for additional federal spending that they want from
Congress and the Bush administration.
   They include urban enterprise zones, which use tax incentives to
attract businesses to ghettos; full funding of the emergency
homeless legislation; a new housing initiative; full funding for
anti-drug legislation; and $7 billion for the Head Start program
providing early education for disadvantaged children.
   On the tax list were higher federal income taxes, an oil import
fee and broad-based energy taxes, greater taxation of Social
Security, and limiting the interest deduction for home mortgages.
   Not on the list was a gasoline tax, which some city officials say
should remain dedicated to transportation needs.
   ``In the past, we have been accused of coming to Capitol Hill
with a tin cup seeking a handout,'' said Goddard, president of the
league. ``It was painful, but this time we come with a balanced
program.''
   The League of Cities has backed higher federal taxes previously,
but the list of taxes was the organization's first attempt to
propose specific revenue alternatives to go along with their request
for restoration of some federal urban aid.
   Mayor Richard Berkley of Kansas City, Mo., a Republican and
former president of the league, said there was some sentiment for
higher federal taxes to cover urban needs among Republican municipal
office holders.
   ``I think ... there's generally a high degree of similiarity in
what the priorities of the Democratic and Republican mayors are _
maybe some differences in degree,'' Berkley said.
   ``In the whole scheme of things, we're not talking about huge
amounts of money,'' he said.
   The list was drafted because of congressional leaders' statements
that any new intitatives should be accompanied by proposals for
where the money will come from.
   Goddard said that President Bush's budget proposal for fiscal
1990, while including modest increases in Head Start, anti-drug and
homeless programs, would also impose major cuts on some of the
group's favorite programs and eliminate 82 domestic grant programs.
</TEXT>
