<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-14 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Shares Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
after a marginal retreat Tuesday, while share prices rose on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 129.92 yen, up 0.35 yen from Monday's
129.57-point finish. The currency opened at 130.23 yen and
fluctuated between 129.90 yen and 130.40 yen during the day's
dealings.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
148.82 points the previous day, regained 171.39 points, or 0.54
percent, to finish trading at 31,724.35.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's high opening in Tokyo to
indications by Karl Otto Poehl, president of the West German central
bank, that the bank has no intention of raising its interest rates.
   Speaking after a bankers meeting, Poehl said he thinks West
German interest rates are sufficient to contain inflation.
   The dollar moved higher in New York overnight on the strength of
Poehl's comments, said Tokyo dealers, adding that the upward
movement caused the dollar to also rise in Tokyo.
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama suggested at a press
conference Tuesday that the dollar's recent strength was not of
serious concern and indirectly discouraged the possibility of
intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   A central bank dealer said the market was in a wait-and-see mood
because of concerns over U.S. trade figures to be released Wednesday
in Washington.
   In stock trading, the Nikkei strengthened as individual investors
bought shares, traders said.
   Participants were interested in cheap, small issues, added one
trader with a major securities firm in Tokyo, speaking on condition
of anonymity. But trading was inactive ahead of the U.S. trade
report, he said.
</TEXT>
