<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ContraAid     03-14 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contra Aid,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Seek More Aid for Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is preparing to ask
Congress for more humanitarian aid for the Nicaraguan Contras at a
time when the rebels also are enjoying greater diplomatic acceptance
in the region than they had previously.
   Although no final decision has been made, U.S. officials said
Monday they expect the request probably will exceed $50 million.
Contra leader Adolfo Calero said after a meeting with State
Department officials the request will be ``40 some odd million
dollars.''
   The current $27 million humanitarian aid package expires at the
end of March and the administration request is likely to be sent to
Capitol Hill before the lawmakers open a two-week spring recess this
weekend, the officials said. Congress suspended military aid to the
rebels more than a year ago.
   More than 10,000 Contra fighters are clustered at camps in
Honduras along the Nicaraguan border. The administration wants to
see the rebels survive as a unified force at least until there are
assurances that the leftist Sandinista government will carry out
their promises to hold a fair national election early next year.
   The New York Times reported in today's editions that the United
States formally made such a request Monday, asking Honduras to let
the guerrillas stay for another year.
   The Sandinistas, meanwhile, have maintained all along their
interest in creating a pluralistic system but that this process was
systematically thwarted by the Reagan administration's funding of
the Contras.
   There also is evidence of a softening in the Honduran attitude
toward the presence of the rebels on Honduran territory.
   After years of refusing to hold official talks publicly with the
rebels and even to acknowledge the existence of rebel camps on
national territory, Honduras broke the diplomatic ice Monday when a
delegation of Honduran officials, led by Ambassador Jorge Ramon
Hernandez Alcerro, met with Calero and other rebel leaders at a
Washington hotel.
   Hernandez spoke in unusually conciliatory terms about the
Contras, declining to repeat previous Honduran demands that the
rebels be expelled from Honduran territory.
   Asked whether the Contras should be forced out of Honduras before
the 1990 elections in Nicaragua, Hernandez said the answer depends
on negotiations that are to be carried out in Costa Rica at the end
of March by the five Central American foreign ministers.
   ``I really want you to understand that we have to proceed very
cautiously on this,'' he said. ``We don't want to take any positions
at the present moment that could impede us from achieving a
consensus among the Central American countries.''
   The policy of the five Central American countries is based
largely on a joint resolution approved by their respective
presidents last month in El Salvador. It calls for a plan to be
drawn up by this spring for the demobilization of the rebels in
exchange for Sandinista promises of democratic reform.
   Calero said there were no demands by the Hondurans during the
meeting for the evacuation of the rebels and added he was struck by
how friendly the Hondurans were. For his part, Hernandez called the
meeting ``positive.''
   Calero said the rebel cause also received a boost on March 4 when
he and other Contra leaders met with President Carlos Andres Perez.
</TEXT>
