<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WhiteHouse-Finances     03-14 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-White House-Finances,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scowcroft Removes Himself from Decisions Affecting 70 Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft has
removed himself from decisions affecting 70 companies, including a
major defense contractor, because of stock he owns worth at least $1
million and up to $3.3 million.
   But at the same time, Scowcroft has notified the White House
legal counsel's office that he will seek waivers allowing him to
take part in government dealings with some of the companies on the
list in which his interest is insubstantial.
   Financial disclosure reports released Monday by the White House
also showed that chief of staff John Sununu had assets and income
together last year of between $530,000 and $1.1 million. This
included his interest in a ski condominium, a residential lot next
to his New Hampshire home and a stake in an insurance agency.
   The document also said Sununu, a former New Hampshire governor,
has decided to give up tuition benefits from Tufts University for
his children. Sununu has been on leave from the school since 1982,
and last year received $5,500 in assistance.
   The Ethics in Government Act of 1978 requires senior government
officials to reveal their assets, liabilities and sources of income.
It does not require them to list exact amounts but rather to report
values within a range of money, such as $15,000 to $50,000 and
$100,000 to $250,000.
   Scowcroft's form revealed that the retired Air Force general was
unable to specify for whom he provided services as a hired
consultant for Kissinger Associates.
   In a letter about his financial reporting form, Scowcroft told
White House counsel C. Boyden Gray that former Secretary of State
Henry A. Kissinger, who heads Kissinger Associates, ``denied my
request for a list of the clients for whom I worked.'' Scowcroft
reported receiving $293,300 for his services to Kissinger.
   Scowcroft said that ``under my contractual relationship with
Kissinger Associates, I worked for the company, not directly for its
clients.''
   Scowcroft has at least temporarily removed himself from decisions
involving dozens of companies, including Lockheed Corp., a major
defense contractor, along with IBM, the RAND Corp., and Aerospace
Corp.
   Scowcroft received over $16,000 in consulting fees from Lockheed,
for example. And he got $50,000 to perform as a consultant to the
National Council for Peace and Security.
   The disclosure form showed Scowcroft has extensive bank and stock
holdings. Because officials are required under the law only to list
the valuations of assets in monetary ranges, the form indicated that
Scowcroft's holdings in 1988 were worth between $1,079,000 and
$3,265,000.
   Scowcroft reported liabilities ranging from $200,002 to $500,000.
   Because a part of his income came from interest and dividends,
which also needed only to be listed in value ranges, Scowcroft's
report showed he earned between $527,894 and $649,994.
   The disclosure form also showed that Scowcroft, formally national
security adviser to President Gerald R. Ford and later a member of
the presidential commission that investigated the Iran-Contra
affair, earned $53,751 in speaking honoraria.
   Scowcroft, whose national security post pays about $89,000 a
year, also received $49,452 last year for his membership on various
corporate boards.
   Sununu's holdings are largely in real estate.
   He owns a condominium in Cambridge, Vt., and a residential lot
adjacent to his home in Salem, N.H., and each is valued at $100,000
to $250,000. He earned from $15,000 to $50,000 in condominium rental
fees last year.
   Other major assets include a 40 percent ownership, valued at
between $100,000 and $250,000 in Lakeside Insurance Agency Inc. It
is listed under the name of his wife, Nancy.
   Other White House disclosure forms showed:
   _Charles ``Chase'' G. Untermeyer, White House personnel director,
listed assets including investments, partnerships and oil and gas
holdings totaling between $155,000 and $420,000.
   _Andrew Card, deputy chief of staff, listed a two-family
apartment in Holbrook, Mass., as his major asset, checking the
category between $100,000 and $250,000. He said he earned between
$5,000 and $15,000 in rental income from the apartment last year.
   _Robert M. Gates, deputy national security adviser, showed few
assets _ a savings account worth between $1,000 and $5,000 and two
Individual Retirement Accounts worth from $15,000 to $50,000 apiece,
one for himself and one for his wife.
   _David Q. Bates, secretary to the Cabinet, listed assets of
$29,000 to $100,000.
   _Frederick McClure, assistant to the president for legislative
affairs, listed $30,000 to $100,000 in assets and reported that he
was paid a salary of $132,770 in 1988 as an executive with Texas Air
Corp.
   _Jane E. Newman, assistant to the president for operations,
reported salaries from 1988 of $105,000 from the New England
Council, a non-profit regional business association of which she was
president, and $47,359 from the Business and Industry Association of
New Hampshire, a trade group that she headed.
</TEXT>
