<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     03-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Maneuvers Begin in Korea Amid Heightened Tension</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today accused communist
North Korea of preparing for war and stirring up anti-Americanism as
U.S. forces began joint maneuvers with South Korean troops.
   About 200,000 South Korean and U.S. troops, along with naval and
air units, began 10 days of major annual military exercises.
   A Defense Ministry statement rejected North Korean charges that
the ``Team Spirit'' exercises were preparations for a nuclear attack
on the North. The exercises have been held every spring since 1976.
   ``The North should immediately stop its continuous military
buildup and war preparations and clearly show that it is giving up
its strategy of communizing the South by force,'' the statement said.
   North Korea put its armed forces on combat alert and mobilized
reserves in response to the exercises. The North said Monday that
the exercises could trigger war.
   ``The tension between the north and the south has been screwed up
to the highest pitch, and a dangerous situation has been created on
the Korean peninsula in which a war may break out any moment,'' said
Pyongyang's official Korean Central News Agency.
   The Korean peninsula was divided at the end of World War II when
U.S. and Soviet troops ended Japan's colonial rule over the region.
   The two Koreas became bitter enemies and fought a war from
1950-1953. The two sides are still technically at war because no
truce was ever signed.
   South Korean officials said in today's statement that the North
is trying to foment anti-American sentiment among South Koreans to
try to force removal of the 42,000 U.S. troops based in the South
under a mutual defense treaty.
   ``We are compelled to point out ... the north's scheme to
heighten anti-Americanism and get American troops out and ...
eventually realize revolution to communize the south,'' the ministry
statement said.
   Radical students, other dissidents, farmers and other groups in
the south are increasingly anti-American because of U.S. trade
pressure and perceptions that Washington has supported authoritarian
regimes.
   A U.S. military spokesman in Seoul said this year's ``Team
Spirit'' maneuvers involve about 70,000 U.S. troops, including the
42,000 stationed in South Korea and others from Hawaii, Okinawa, and
the U.S. mainland.
   North Korea routinely charges the exercises are preparations for
an attack on the north and puts its armed forces on alert.
   The north said earlier this year that talks with South Korea on
easing tension could not progress unless the exercises were called
off. Seoul refused to do so, and the peace talks have stalled.
   South Korean defense officials said again today that the
exercises are defensive and pose no threat to the north. They
criticized North Korea for rejecting the south's invitation to send
military observers to the exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
