<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     03-14 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adult Bookstores Near FBI Building Shut Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that operates adult bookstores across
the street from FBI headquarters has pleaded guilty to federal
racketeering charges, ending a two-year investigation, the Justice
Department said.
   FBI agents entered the stores and found videotapes with titles
such as ``Traci's Big Trick,'' ``His to Command,'' and ``Bound and
Punished,'' according to court documents.
   The plea agreement was outlined in U.S. District Court on Monday.
   The agreement provides that the two stores directly across the
street from the J. Edgar Hoover building will be closed immediately,
while two others located just down the street will be shut down
later.
   The case is the first obscenity prosecution in the federal court
in the district in 26 years and is only the second time the federal
racketeering law was used in an obscenity case since Congress placed
obscenity violations under that law in 1984, according to Assistant
Attorney General S.G. Dennis Jr.
   Automatic Enterprises Inc., the owner of the bookstores, was
fined $150,000 as part of the settlement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>$10 Million in Drug Paraphernalia Seized</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs Commissioner William von Raab
stood behind a sparkling array of bongs, pipes and scales as he
announced seizures of up to $10 million in drug paraphernalia.
   ``We're going to take away from the drug abuser the tools of his
trade,'' von Raab said Monday. Those who manufacture and distribute
such products ``are putting yourself at risk to lose millions of
dollars of your inventory,'' he said.
   The 306,000 items seized March 1 from the Contempo Products Inc.
warehouse in Nashville filled eight 48-foot containers and was the
largest such seizure in U.S. history, he said. On March 4, Customs
officials seized enough items from the Award Distributing Co. in
Philadelphia to fill four such containers, the second largest
seizure in history, he said.
   But von Raab acknowledged that the amount confiscated would
``probably not have a measurable impact'' on the drug paraphernalia
industry. He estimated that hundreds of millions of dollars worth of
drug paraphernalia is sold annually.
   So far, there have been no arrests in any of the recent cases,
but he said U.S. attorneys around the country ``are identifying
people who might be indicted.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Private Eye Misrepresented Himself, Panel Told</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private investigator hired by Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. misrepresented himself as working for a House
subcommittee while Drexel was assisting in a corporate takeover, the
subcommittee was told.
   The allegation before the House Energy and Commerce Committee's
oversight and investigations subcommittee was made by William G.
Bertain, a Eureka, Calif., lawyer involved in a pending suit over
the 1985 Drexel-assisted takeover of Pacific Lumber Co. by Maxxam
Corp. of Houston.
   Bertain told the subcommittee that John Gibbons, a former
assistant U.S. attorney in California and now a private investigator
for Kroll Associates, had told him on five occasions last year that
he was seeking information about Maxxam's chairman, Charles Hurwitz,
on behalf of a congressional subcommittee.
   In one of the conversations, which was taped by Bertain, Gibbons
said he was working for the oversight and investigations panel,
which is chaired by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., Bertain testified.
   But Gibbons' boss, John Kroll, the principal owner of the
detective agency, told reporters it is ``totally inconceivable''
that Gibbons had misrepresented himself and predicted that he would
be vindicated when the hearing continues next week.
   Drexel agreed in principle in December to plead guilty to six
charges of securities law violations and pay a record $650 million
fine. The Securities and Exchange Commission also has alleged that
Drexel violated securities laws in Maxxam's takeover of Pacific
Lumber, the largest private holder of redwood timberland in
California.
</TEXT>
