<DOCNO> AP890314-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0511EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhonyFrontPages     03-14 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phony Front Pages,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extra! Extra! Anti-War Group Puts Out Fake Papers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Spelling of ``Chornicle'' in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mock versions of three daily newspapers may
have briefly fooled readers in two states, but officials were not
amused, and at least two papers planned to take legal action against
the imitators.
   Thousands of look-alike front pages attacking U.S. policy in El
Salvador were wrapped around vending machine copies of the San
Francisco Chronicle, Chicago Tribune and The State Journal-Register
in Springfield, Ill., on Monday.
   In a news release delivered to The Associated Press in San
Francisco, a group called Citizens Against the U.S. War in El
Salvador claimed responsibility for the phony front page _ with a
``San Francisco Chornicle'' masthead.
   ``Over 100 activists put over 10,000 copies'' of the special
edition into Chronicle newsboxes in San Francisco, the eastern San
Francisco Bay area and Sonoma County, the statement claimed.
   The real paper planned to pursue charges of product tampering and
copyright infringement against the copycats, said Jessie Knight,
vice president of marketing for the San Francisco Newspaper Agency,
which distributes the Chronicle.
   The bogus page, whose typefaces and makeup resembled those of the
real Chronicle, carried headlines such as ``El Salvador On Verge of
Revolution'' and ``United States Waging War on El Salvador.''
   ``This kind of hoax is not the way to exercise free speech,''
said William German, the Chronicle's executive editor. ``Our readers
will certainly see through it as a fraud upon them as well as the
Chronicle.''
   The Baltimore Sun and The Arizona Daily Star were the targets of
similar stunts in January.
   In Chicago, the Tribune released a statement saying it will
``take every legal step possible to prosecute the people responsible
and prevent any recurrence.''
   ``While the right of free speech and political protest is
understood and appreciated, tampering with the front page of the
Tribune interferes with and distorts our mission as a newspaper and
our right to do business,'' the statement said.
   Several thousand newspapers were covered with the bogus front
page, which had a Chicago Tribune masthead, a spokeswoman said.
   Beneath the masthead, headlines proclaimed ``U.S. at War in El
Salvador'' and ``Death Squad Activities,'' Tribune officials said. A
group calling itself the ``People for a Free El Salvador'' said it
made the switch.
   In Springfield, Ill., Steve Fagan, editor of The State
Journal-Register, said about 30 of their 200 street boxes were
targeted. Those papers said the lampoon was the work of ``People for
a Free El Salvador.''
   ``We view this as a childish prank as well as an incident of
vandalism and criminal trespass,'' Fagan said. ``The worse part of
it is this is an unwarranted intrusion on our readers.''
   Leslie Schuld of the Committee in Solidarity with the People of
El Salvador approved of the effort but did not take credit.
   ``There has been little in the press about what is happening down
there,'' Schuld said in Chicago. ``The Tribune in particular hasn't
been covering the death squad activities adequately.''
   The San Francisco activists' statement said the prank was an
attempt to ``get out the truth about the situation in El Salvador.''
   ``We believe that actions like this can contribute to building a
political movement in the U.S. that can stop the war in El Salvador
and support self-determination for the Salvadoran people,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
