<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     03-14 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average finished trading at 31,724.35,
regaining 171.39 points, or 0.54 percent. The market's main index
was a 148.82-point loser on Monday.
   The dollar finished trading at 129.92 yen, up 0.35 yen from
Monday's 129.57-yen close. The dollar opened at 130.15 yen, the
first time it opened beyond the 130-yen level since Feb. 2. It
traded between 129.90-130.40 yen.
   Opening higher following comments by Karl Otto Poehl, president
of the West German central bank, the dollar fluctuated as
speculative investors adjusted their positions and took profits,
said Ichiro Takeda of Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   Speaking after a bankers meeting Monday, Poehl said he thought
current West German interest rates could contain inflation and that
the bank had no intention of raising them.
   ``But after Japan's trade surplus was released, investors started
selling some of the dollars they bought earlier, which helped the
yen recover a bit,'' Ikeda said.
   Japan's trade surplus widened for the sixth consecutive month
from year-earlier levels in February, to $7.2 billion dollars from
$5.2 billion dollars, the Finance Ministry announced today.
   ``The market is waiting for the wholesale price index report to
come out later today, which is expected to be higher than last
year's,'' Ikeda said. ``Investors are also concerned about the U.S.
January trade figures due out tomorrow.''
   On the stock market, overnight gains on overseas markets inspired
the Nikkei's rise today, an analyst with Nomura Securities said.
   He said market players stepped to the sidelines before a series
of releases of economic indicators including Japanese trade figures,
the wholesale price index and the U.S. trade figures.
   ``If the wholesale price index growth marks more than 0.3
percentage points, it wouldn't be too good for the stock market,''
the dealer said, adding that it would discourage investors because
price increases can lead to tighter economic policy including
discount rate hikes.
   Increases in the discount rate generally discourage stock trading.
   Trading was moderate, with the first section volume estimated at
800 million shares.
</TEXT>
