<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Anti-US     03-14 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Anti-US,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Hurl Rocks, Firebombs at U.S. Military Range</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Korea</UNK>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers protesting practice bombing
by U.S. jet fighters threw rocks and firebombs onto a military range
on the west coast today, forcing it to close for a second day, a
U.S. military spokesman said.
   Three guardhouses along the range's edge were hit by firebombs,
one sustaining minor fire damage, the spokesman said. No injuries
were reported.
   Police arrested nine villagers during the nightlong protest in
front of Koon-ni military range about 70 miles southwest of Seoul,
said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The protesters from the nearby village want the range closed.
   The trouble began early Monday when about 400 villagers tried to
enter the range, protesting ``deafening'' noise made by U.S.
military jets, the U.S. spokesman said.
   About 1,500 policemen surrounded the range and kept protesters
back, the spokesman said. Some villagers fought police with rocks
and sticks, he said.
   About 300 villagers gathered again Monday night and tried to
enter the range through the fence, but police again held them back,
the spokesman said.
   However, the disturbance continued, and several demonstrators
hurled firebombs and rocks into the range, he said.
   The spokesman quoted Maj. John Anderson, the range commander, as
saying the range will be reopened after the repair of 70 feet of
fence also damaged in the protest.
   The U.S. planes that practice at the range are stationed at Osan
and Kunsan air bases.
   Villagers have complained in past weeks that the noise from the
practice bombing runs is unbearable. They have formed a committee to
demand that they be compensated for living with the noise or that
the range be moved.
</TEXT>
