<FIRST>r a PM-KittyGenoveseKiller     03-14 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kitty Genovese Killer,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer Seeks Retrial After 25 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years after Kitty Genovese was killed
while neighbors ignored her screams for help, the man convicted of
her murder is seeking a retrial, a newspaper reported today.
   The Genovese case became a nationwide symbol of how fear and
apathy can override compassion.
   Catherine ``Kitty'' Genovese, a 28-year-old bar manager, was
stalked and stabbed to death on a street in Queens on March 13, 1964.
   Thirty-eight people reportedly either saw the attack or heard her
cry ``Help me! Help me! Oh God, he's stabbed me.'' But no one went
to her aid.
   Winston Moseley confessed to the killing and was sentenced to
death, later commuted to life in jail.
   Now Moseley, 54, has filed for a new trial, charging that his
court-appointed lawyer never told him he had been representing
Genovese in a gambling case when she died, the Daily News said.
   The Queens district attorney's office is opposing Moseley's
petition.
   ``There's no possibility at all of any conflict of interest,''
said Richard Piperno, a spokesman for the district attorney. ``There
was no harm accrued to the defendant. He confessed the murder to the
police and at his trial.''
   In papers filed at the trial-level state Supreme Court in Queens,
Moseley claimed that lawyer Sidney Sparrow's silence deprived him of
the right to choose an attorney ``solely interested in my defense,
without any possibility of divided loyalties.
   ``At no time was I informed of this conflicting representation,''
Moseley said. ``The failure of counsel to inform the accused and the
court of a conflict of interest cannot be deemed harmless error.''
   Sparrow, who at 76 still practices law, said he is certain he
told Moseley and the trial judge, J. Irwin Shapiro, that he had
represented Genovese on an appeal of a bookmaking conviction.
   ``I'm sure that in the course of my conversations (with Moseley),
I mentioned I knew her and that I had represented her,'' Sparrow
said.
   ``My representation of Kitty Genovese ended when she died.''
   A hearing on the petition is scheduled for April 6.
</TEXT>
