<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0617EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NorthernLights     03-14 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Lights,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northern Lights Stage Rare Show In Southern States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Police 911 emergency lines lit up as unusually explosive activity
on the sun touched off ``once-in-a-lifetime'' sightings of the
``northern lights,'' causing jitters as far south as Texas and
Florida.
   Worried sky watchers thought they spotted wildfires or falling
debris from the space shuttle Discovery, but scientists advised
people to sit back and marvel at the unusual occurrence.
   ``Wow! Enjoy the show!'' said a special advisory issued Monday by
the National Weather Service in Fort Worth, Texas. ``It is an
extremely rare event for the southern latitudes of the U.S. In fact,
it would be a quintessential once-in-a-lifetime event.''
   Jack Horkheimer, director of the Miami Space Transit Planetarium
and a astronomy expert for the Public Broadcasting System, said he
had not seen the northern lights in his 25 years in southern Florida.
   ``For you to see them down here is rarer than snow,'' he said.
   Chris Balch, a forecaster for the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration in Boulder, Colo., said that multicolored
lights in the nighttime sky, usually visible only in or near the
Arctic Circle, were reported late Sunday and early Monday in
Pennsylvania, New York, Detroit and Colorado. Sightings also were
reported in Delaware, Indiana and Georgia. But in much of the
nation, clouds or haze obscured the show.
   Northern lights, also called aurora borealis, and their
counterpart in the Southern Hemisphere are believed to result as
tiny charged particles that pour out by the sun during solar flares
strike the Earth's upper atmosphere hours or days later.
   The geomagnetic storms, caused as the charged particles smash
into the Earth's magnetic field, can also disrupt satellites and
communications on Earth, but Balch said he had heard no reports of
significant problems.
   Experts differed on whether the continuing disturbance on the sun
is likely to mean more northern lights this week.
   Joe Allen, a NOAA solar-terrestrial expert in Boulder, said he
thought there was a good chance of further northern lights displays
this week across the northern third of the country.
   But Balch said that although the forecast could change if another
huge solar flare bursts out, ``We're not really looking for the
northern lights to continue.''
   In Utah, the northern lights early Monday covered about 40
percent of the sky at one point. Those who rose early enough to
witness them reported seeing a shifting curtain of red or purple
light with occasional vertical white streaks, moving from the
northeast to the northwest and back again.
   ``It was the most brilliant display of northern lights any of our
people can remember in the last 30 years,'' said Bill Alder, chief
meteorologist at the weather service's Salt Lake City office.
   In Florida and Texas, the northern lights caused mass confusion.
   ``I've been having a lot of calls,'' said Ignacio Casanova, a
dispatcher with the Cameron County Sheriff's Department in
Brownsville near the Mexico border. ``They're just callings to find
out what it is. On 911, I've had about 10 calls. They're worried
about what's going on.''
   In Anchorage, Alaska, where the northern lights are far more
common than in the lower 48 states, the color display seemed to last
longer than usual, with viewers reporting sightings over 6{ hours
Sunday evening to early Monday.
   Clear skies provided a clear view for watching the ever-changing
lights dance around a quarter moon. But the lights Sunday night were
not as brilliant as they have been on some sightings in Anchorage,
when greens, blues and reds bounce off snow-covered mountains under
a full moon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
