<FIRST>u i PM-Romania 1stLd-Writethru a0472 03-14 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Arrests Diplomat Linked to Letter Critical of President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with senior diplomat charged with spying, diplomats
linking charge to letter critical of Ceausescu. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania today said it has charged with
spying a senior diplomat whose father and five other veteran
Communists reportedly petitioned President Nicolae Ceausescu to stop
repressing his people.
   In a bold challenge to the autocratic Romanian leader, the six
demanded in a January letter that he improve human rights and stop
exporting food from his shortage-plagued country, emigre sources say.
   The official Romanian news agency Agerpres said Mircea Raceanu,
who was arrested Jan. 31 in Bucharest, had been charged with spying
for a foreign power and engaged in ``steady treasonable action''
since 1974.
   Agerpress did not name the power.
   Raceanu had served for several years in Romania's embassy in
Washington in the 1970s and as deputy head of the Foreign Ministry's
U.S. desk in Bucharest _ and emigre sources said he was arrested en
route to the U.S. ambassador's residence.
   The official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug quoted unidentified
diplomatic sources in the Romanian capital as linking the arrest to
the letter to Ceausescu.
   Raceanu's father, Ion Raceanu, had joined the other veteran
officials in criticizing Ceausescu's plans to destroy up to 7,000 of
the country's 13,000 villages in a resettlement campaign, according
to a text of the letter made available to The Associated Press.
   The letter's six signatories are all retired senior leaders, two
of them former Politburo members. Their initiative marks the first
time senior Communists have banded together to protest Ceausescu's
stern policies, suggesting dissatisfaction in party ranks.
   The letter condemns a late 1970s decree that forbids Romanians to
speak to foreigners.
   It also criticizes the use of secret police against ``workers
demanding their rights, against old members of the party, and honest
intellectuals exercising their right to petition ....''
   And it decries forced Sunday labor and alleged systematic
violations of private mail and phone communication.
   The letter accuses Ceausescu of damaging Romania's economy and
reputation.
   ``You started changing the geography of the countryside, but you
cannot remove Romania to Africa,'' the text says, alluding to
Romania's increasing international isolation.
   ``How are you going to improve Romania's external relations when
all the leaders of the non-communist nations of Europe refuse to
meet with you?''
   The letter demands that Ceausescu immediately renounce plans to
destroy the villages, restore constitutional guarantees to meet
European human rights agreements, and halt food exports.
   In announcing the arrest, Agerpres made no mention of the letter,
saying only that the state security bodies had ``uncovered a grave
action of betrayal of the interests of the Romanian people and
state'' by Raceanu.
   It said he managed to supply unspecified ``secret data and
intelligence'' to the unidentified power for which he allegedly
worked.
   Agerpres did not say what sentence Raceanu faces if convicted.
The maximum penalty for treason is death.
   The emigre sources said both Raceanu and his wife were initially
detained while en route to the U.S. ambassador's residence but that
she was later freed. A Western diplomat in Bucharest confirmed by
telephone that Raceanu was invited but didn't appear.
   After that, Raceanu was said to have been transferred from his
post at the Foreign Ministry, the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
