<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia     03-14 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Resistance Leaders Take First Step Toward Unified Command</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's often-fractious resistance forces took
a first step today toward unifying their armies by forming a defense
council headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   In their joint statement, the leaders also announced a ``common
political program'' calling for a multiparty parliamentary
government with ``Western democracy'' and free enterprise in
Cambodia after the Vietnamese withdraw.
   ``All of them (the rebel forces) now are practically under my
command,'' said Sihanouk, the president of a three-party Cambodian
government-in-exile that is fighting the Vietnamese, who invaded in
1978.
   Sihanouk, who lives part of the year in Beijing, announced the
new High Council for National Defense together with his two partners
in the resistance government, communist Khmer Rouge leader Khieu
Samphan; and Son Sann, who heads a smaller nationalist party.
   The three have been holding closed-door meetings in Beijing since
Sunday to discuss Cambodia's future in view of Vietnam's rejection
of Sihanouk's peace proposals and a planned Chinese-Soviet summit in
May.
   Sihanouk said he was confident that China, a main backer of the
Cambodian resistance, will not drop its support to reach agreement
with the Soviets on a speedy Vietnamese withdrawal. Moscow is
Vietnam's main ally.
   ``I am 100 percent sure (China) will continue to support my plan
and support us,'' Sihanouk said. A Vietnamese withdrawal that leaves
the Vietnamese client government of Hun Sen to confront the
resistance ``a la Afghanistan'' is not acceptable, the prince said.
   In Afghanistan, Soviets troops have withdrawn and left Afghan
forces to fight rebels.
   Sihanouk predicted that Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and
senior Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping will agree at their May 15
summit to pressure Hun Sen and Vietnam into accepting his plan. It
calls for U.N. supervision of a Vietnamese pullout and free
elections under a provisional government representing all parties.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw by September if a political
agreement can be reached on Cambodia's future, but it promised to
leave in 1990 whatever the case.
   The main snag in advancing that plan has been the refusal of
Vietnam and Hun Sen to accept Khmer Rouge participation in a future
government and U.N. supervision. The United States, which helps the
resistance, has also been wary of a return of the Khmer Rouge to
power.
   The Khmer Rouge seized power and killed at least 1 million people
in a reign of terror from 1975 to 1978 under Pol Pot, who is said to
have retired.
   Sihanouk said Khieu Samphan has agreed Pol Pot will remain out of
the picture.
   ``If they break their promise,'' Sihanouk said, turning to Khieu
Samphan, ``my army will fight them indefinitely.''
   Khieu Samphan, smiling broadly, said his party was willing to
``accept realities'' in order to end Vietnam's occupation.
   The possible role of the Khmer Rouge has been one of the main
sources of conflict within the three-party resistance. Sihanouk has
accused its forces of repeated attacks on his army.
   However, he told the news conference no new attacks have occurred
in several months and that one role for the new defense council will
be to resolve such conflicts.
   The joint statement said the council will ensure ``solidarity,
cooperation and mutual respect and assistance'' among the three
resistance armies. It did not say in detail how that would be
achieved.
   Sihanouk said the council is a first step toward uniting the
three armies in a national Cambodian army in the near future. For
now, the three armies will keep their own commanders.
</TEXT>
