<DOCNO> AP890314-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0637EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Stolar     03-14 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stolar,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chicagoan Ends Nearly Six Decades In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon, Abe Stolar will be able to claim the
luggage that left Moscow more than a dozen years before he did.
   Stolar, a Chicago-born Jew who spent 58 years in the Soviet
Union, arrived in Vienna on Monday with his wife, son,
daughter-in-law and two grandchildren.
   ``Even in the plane, I still felt paranoic, I still felt we
weren't safe,'' said the 77-year-old Stolar.
   Stolar, who was taken to the Soviet Union in 1931 by his
communist parents, had tried to leave in 1975. He got as far as the
entrance ramp of his plane at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport, only to
have the authorities drag him and his family back.
   Their luggage went on Israel, their destination. It's been
waiting for them since, throughout the long battle to emigrate that
took two superpower summits and heavy lobbying by U.S. congressmen
to finally win.
   The whole family was subdued and tired after their 2{-hour flight
from Moscow to Vienna.
   ``At last I got free, that's all I feel,'' said Stolar's wife,
Zita.
   ``It did feel great to get off the plane,'' Stolar said. ``Just
walking into this building, you could feel right away that it wasn't
Russia.''
   ``It's really wonderful to be here, great, even though I haven't
seen anything yet, I haven't felt anything yet,'' he said as he
received a hug from Linda Opper, a member of a Chicago Jewish action
group that kept Stolar's case alive.
   He waved an ``I Love Chicago'' button he said he'd been saving
for the arrival. ``And Chicago loves you,'' Ms. Opper said.
   Stolar's parents, Russian emigres, fled the Depression and
arrived in a Soviet Union where Josef Stalin was just starting the
wave of mass collectivization and purges.
   Stolar's father was among the millions who perished in the
purges. Stolar remained in Moscow, and worked for 20 years until his
retirement in the mid-1970s as an English-language translator at
Radio Moscow.
   But he was disenchanted with Soviet life and decided to join the
wave of Soviet Jews emigrating to Israel.
   In 1975, Stolar, his wife and son, Michael, got almost to the
plane when officials pulled them back, saying his wife was privy to
state secrets and could not leave for at least another two years.
   In some ways, the Stolars were better off than other
``refuseniks'' _ those denied permission to leave the Soviet Union.
Stolar had a U.S. passport, as did his son. In 1977, Israel granted
a passport to Stolar's wife.
   Although foreigners, they couldn't leave. And since they had
given up Soviet citizenship _ a Soviet requirement for emigration to
Israel _ they found themselves in a bureaucratic limbo.
   They had given up their apartment and couldn't officially
register to live in another. When Michael married in 1983, he
couldn't go through with official ceremonies because he was not
registered to live in Moscow.
   In 1985, then-President Reagan held his first meeting with Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Geneva, and the Stolars were on the
list Reagan handed Gorbachev of emigration cases he wanted solved.
   The Soviets granted the wish, but refused to let Michael's wife
and their newborn daughter go.
   Stolar said he thinks the case was finally solved through the
summit meeting Gorbachev and Reagan held in Moscow, although it took
several more months to pry loose exit visas.
   Stolar said in Moscow earlier Monday that he did not consider
himself a ``refusenik'' because he always has been a U.S. citizen.
   `I was an American, pure and simple, and so I considered myself a
hostage all these 13 years,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
