<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     03-14 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in thin, early European
trading today as the market waited for American economic indicators
to lift it out of its week-long doldrums. Gold prices rose.
   U.S. retail sales figures for February were to be released later
today and trade figures for January are to be released on Wednesday.
   Foreign currency dealers said the potential for the dollar to
rise on better-than-expected trade figures is larger than the
potential to fall on a disappointing trade deficit.
   ``Underlying sentiment is still bullish (for the dollar),'' said
one trader in Rome, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``For me
there's more room on the upside than on the downside.''
   Economists expect the deficit to be lower than December's $10.2
billion.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 129.92. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 130.08 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8665 West German marks, down from 1.8669
   _1.5965 Swiss francs, unchanged
   _6.3260 French francs, up from 6.3230
   _2.1060 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1040
   _1,368.90 Italian lire, up from 1,367.40
   _1.1973 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1981
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7128, marginally more
expensive for buyers than $1.7125 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $394 a troy ounce, up
from $392.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $394.30.
   The bid price was also $394.30 in Zurich, up from $392.75 bid
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 52 cents to close at a bid
$395.37.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.07 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $6.02.
</TEXT>
