<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-14 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wintry Weather In Northern States, Showers on Coasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front packing high winds and blowing snow chilled several
northern states early today while showers were scattered over parts
of both coasts.
   Snow advisories were in effect this morning for much of central
and northwest Montana. In Billings, Mont., three inches fell in six
hours late Monday.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow were posted for Colorado's
mountains, northern Wyoming and parts of the Dakotas. In Montana, up
to 10 inches of snow was expected in the mountains.
   Winter storm watches have been posted for later today for
southeastern North Dakota, northern South Dakota, most of Minnesota,
Wisconsin and Upper Michigan.
   High wind warnings were in effect this morning for southeastern
Wyoming and northeastern Colorado, where gusts to 80 mph were
possible.
   Clouds covered much of the nation this morning. Showers were
scattered over the northern Pacific Coast and a cold front was
bringing rain and drizzle to the Middle Atlantic coast and the
Carolina coast.
   Fog was developing in the middle Mississippi Valley, the lower
Ohio Valley, southern Appalachia and the Gulf Coast this morning.
Dense fog was reported in northern Kentucky.
   On Monday, high temperature records were broken in several cities
in the South and in Colorado including: Colorado Springs, Colo., 70
degrees; Columbus, Ga., 85; El Paso, Texas, 86; Midland, Texas, 89;
Pueblo, Colo., 80; Roswell, N.M., 88; Tucson, Ariz., 88.
   It was Tucson's seventh consecutive day of record heat.
   But that still was cool compared to Laredo, Texas, the nation's
hot spot at 98 degrees.
   Today's forecast: showers widespread over the Pacific Northwest;
snow widespread from Idaho across the northern Rockies, the Dakotas
and Minnesota to the northern Great Lakes; showers and thunderstorms
developing over the middle Mississippi, Ohio and Tennessee valleys
and the southern Great Lakes; and gusty winds over the central
Plains.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 20s and 30s from the
northern Rockies across the Dakotas to northern Michigan; in the 70s
and 80s from Southern California across the Desert Southwest, the
southern Plains, the lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys and the
Gulf Coast states to the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 90s
over some southwest Texas towns. Elsewhere in the continental
states, highs were forecast to be in the 40s, 50s and 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 15
degrees at Great Falls, Mont., to 70 degrees at Glendale, Ariz., and
Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 48 cloudy; Boston 29 partly cloudy; Buffalo 37
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 46 hazy; Cincinnati 44 foggy; Cleveland 37
fair; Detroit 30 fair; Miami 58 foggy; New York 36 cloudy;
Philadelphia 36 cloudy; Pittsburgh 39 partly cloudy; Portland,
Maine, 28 cloudy; Washington 37 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 22 snow; Chicago 38 hazy; Dallas-Fort Worth 64
windy; Denver 44 windy; Des Moines 34 foggy; Indianapolis 40 foggy;
Kansas City 39 foggy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 33 foggy; Nashville 60
cloudy; New Orleans 62 foggy; St. Louis 47 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 53 fair; Anchorage 20 fair; Las Vegas 61 fair;
Los Angeles 54 fair; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 38 cloudy; San
Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 40 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Toronto 28 fair.
</TEXT>
