<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0652EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola     03-14 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savimbi Offers Concessions, Denies Reports of Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMBA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the rebel army fighting
Angola's Marxist government says he's called a four-month halt to
attacks in an effort to produce peace talks, and denies reports he
has tortured and killed critics.
   Rebel chief Jonas Savimbi, who spoke at a news conference Monday
on the 23rd anniversary of the founding of his UNITA movement, even
brought forward an alleged victim of abuses to personally refute the
claims.
   The New York Times, in a dispatch Saturday from London, quoted
former UNITA supporters as saying Savimbi ordered the torture and
killing of rebel dissidents.
   It said Tito Chingunji, former UNITA representative in
Washington, was being held against his will in Jamba, the rebels'
southern Angolan stronghold.
   Asked at a news conference about the allegations in the Times,
Savimbi referred reporters to Chingunji, now deputy
secretary-general of UNITA, who appeared along with Savimbi.
   Chingunji said the reports were ``lies attempting to split the
UNITA leadership.''
   Other leaders of UNITA, the National Union of the Total
Independence of Angola, described recent reports by the British
Broadcasting Corp. and The New York Times alleging UNITA human
rights abuses as ``propaganda.''
   In an interview at his headquarters in southeastern Angola,
Savimbi said his U.S.-backed movement would refrain from launching
any military offensive against the government until July 15 to allow
for a possible diplomatic breakthrough in the stalemated war.
   ``We are optimistic that there will be progress,'' Savimbi said.
``If there is no production of goods by then we resume offensive
operations.''
   The government has refused to negotiate with the rebels, even
though there is little prospect for a military victory by either
side in the 14-year civil war. Savimbi acknowledges he cannot win a
conventional war against the Cuban-backed government forces, but his
rebels have for years controlled about a third of this sparsely
populated country of 9 million people.
   Savimbi said officials from several African states _ including
Zaire, Congo and the Ivory Coast _ met with Angolan officials
earlier this month in an attempt to launch peace talks.
   He also said UNITA leaders would be meeting with Cuban military
officials in the Ivory Coast in about two weeks to discuss the
withdrawal of Cuba's 50,000 troops from Angola.
   Savimbi has pledged not to attack withdrawing Cuban forces.
   Cuba has agreed to a phased withdrawal as part of a regional
peace pact also signed by Angola and South Africa. The South
Africans have agreed to grant independence to neighboring Namibia
and to end assistance to UNITA, which still receives aid from the
United States.
   At his news conference, Savimbi also offered to bow out of peace
talks and instead send other rebel leaders. The Angolan government
has been adamant in refusing any contact with Savimbi.
   He further said the rebels would not interfere with
reconstruction of the strategic east-west Benguela railway,
destroyed by rebel attacks, and he said he would be willing to
release 100 captured government troops.
</TEXT>
