<FIRST>r a PM-Jenco-Hostages     03-14 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jenco-Hostages,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Hostage Says `Satanic Verses' Hurts Prospects for Anderson's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publication of ``The Satanic Verses'' has
reduced the likelihood that Terry Anderson will be released soon
from Lebanon, said the Rev. Lawrence M. Jenco, a former hostage in
Lebanon.
   ``The doors have been slammed shut again,'' said Jenco, who was
here Monday for a prayer service for Anderson, the longest held of
15 foreign hostages in Lebanon.
   Meanwhile, six organizations are asking news media around the
world to publicize the fourth anniversary of Terry Anderson's
kidnapping on Thursday.
   ``Today, March 16, 1989, the American journalist Terry Anderson,
41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press in
Beirut, entered his fifth year of captivity as a hostage in
Lebanon,'' said a statement that the groups asked broadcasters to
air and newspapers to use on their front pages.
   The ``statement of solidarity with Anderson'' is from ``the
leading freedom of expression organizations in the Western world,''
Anne Nelson, executive director of the New York-based Committee to
Protect Journalists, said Monday.
   In Buffalo, Jenco said Americans should show some support toward
Moslems who have been offended by ``The Satanic Verses'' by British
author Salman Rushdie.
   ``We don't need books that degrade. It was a stupid thing,'' he
said.
   The Rev. Jenco's comments came a day after Peggy Say, Anderson's
sister, said the book had increased tensions between the West and
Moslem extremists and was an impediment to the release of the
hostages.
   Jenco, campus minister at the University of Southern California,
shared a cell with Anderson in 1986.
   He told an audience of about 100 at St. Paul's Episcopal Church
that Anderson's life in captivity was filled with suffering.
   ``Terry's only refuge was prayer and the hope that his countrymen
will not forget him,'' he said.
   Mrs. Say and Jenco and other hostage families will gather in
Washington Thursday to mark the anniversary of Anderson's abduction.
   Ms. Nelson said she will read the statement of solidarity with
Anderson at the National Press Club in Washington Thursday.
   Other organizations urging publication of the anniversary
statement are: Article 19 of London; International Federation of
Publishers in Paris; the International Federation of Journalists in
Brussels; Index on Censorship in London; and Observatoire de
L'Information in France.
   The International Federation of Journalists also asked its
150,000 members in 37 nations to draw attention to the plight of
British journalist John McCarthy, who marked his 1,000th day of
captivity on Jan. 10.
   Elsewhere, Charles Dale, the president of the Newspaper Guild of
the United States and Canada, will lead a delegation to the U.S.
State Department in Washington on Thursday.
   In Strasbourg, France, French journalist and former hostage
Jean-Paul Kauffmann will meet with European Parliament leaders to
press for the hostages' release.
</TEXT>
