<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0711EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-IslamicConference     03-14 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Islamic Conference,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Ministers Discuss Iran-Iraq Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic foreign ministers met today
to arrange a swap of prisoners between Iran and Iraq and discuss
ways to revive peace talks between the longtime foes, sources said.
   The ministers, meeting under the auspices of the 46-member
Organization of Islamic Conference, also planned to discuss post-war
reconstruction projects in the Persian Gulf nations.
   Conference sources said the meetings were also expected to try
and heal the rift between Iran and Saudi Arabia and hopefully talk
the two Islamic powers into resuming diplomatic relations.
   Saudi Arabia severed ties with Iran last year to protest alleged
Iranian attempts to instigate Shiite Moslem supporters to sabotage
oil and public utility installations in the kingdom.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
ministers hope to convince Iran and Iraq to accept a simultaneous
release of all prisoners of war. A U.N.-brokered cease-fire halted
eight years of hostilities between Iran and Iraq on Aug. 20 but
peace talks launched five days later have been deadlocked over the
issue of troop withdrawals.
   Both countries are members of the Islamic Conference. Tehran sent
a low-ranking delegation to the meeting.
   Conference members, mainly Arab countries, were expected to
criticize Iran's efforts to export its fundamentalist revolution to
neighboring nations, the sources said.
   The Iranian delegation was expected to appeal to the conference's
foreign ministers to support Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's edict
urging Moslems to kill British writer Salman Rushdie for allegedly
blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Saudi Arabia has criticized Rushdie and banned his book, but
would not support Khomeini's death threat.
   Arab diplomatic sources have said the Saudis will resist Iran's
attempts to project Khomeini as defender of Islam. They said
Khomeini was bent on using the Rushdie affair to arouse public
sentiment, hoping to improve unfavorable political conditions at
home.
   Moslems were offended by a scene in Rushdie's book where
prostitutes take their names after prophet Mohammed's four wives. In
the novel, Rushdie also suggests that Mohammed wrote the Koran, the
holy book of Islam, rather than receiving it directly from God.
   The conference sessions were held behind closed doors, and the
Saudis were understood to have argued that Khomeini's order only
portrays Moslems as bloodthirsty and precipitates unnecessary rifts
with the West.
   Conference sources said the Saudis were to offer a compromise
proposal based on sending conference delegations to Western
countries to request that Rushdie's book be denounced and banned.
   Meanwhile, the Saudi newspaper Okaz reported that the conference
was to discuss collective action to regain the Arab sector of
Jerusalem. Okaz said that Islamic Conference member nations want the
sector of Jerusalem occupied by Israel in 1967 to become capital of
a Palestinian state.
   The foreign ministers, it said, plan to discuss ways to bolster
the Palestinian uprising against Israel in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0718EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Botha     03-14 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Botha,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Leaders Vote To Replace Botha</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederik W. de Klerk, chosen by
the governing party as South Africa's next head of state, says party
leaders will meet with President P.W. Botha but will not press him
to resign immediately.
   The National Party's Parliament members voted unanimously Monday
to back de Klerk as head of state.
   But Botha, who is 73 and suffered a stroke in January, has said
he plans to return to work Wednesday and wants to stay in office at
least until next year.
   ``There will be discussions with him with regard to his position
and there is nothing in the decision that says he must now step
down,'' de Klerk told reporters after the National Party vote.
   ``I am the leader-in-chief of the National Party and the decision
was, in principle, that the leader-in-chief of the National Party
should be state president.''
   Botha made no immediate response to the announcement by the
governing party's parliamentary caucus. The president has been
active in National Party politics since 1935 and has led the
government since 1978.
   A power struggle between Botha and de Klerk, 52, has intensified
since Botha resigned as party leader Feb. 2, two weeks after the
stroke. It worsened Sunday, when Botha said de Klerk ``had been
misused by some people'' and said he would not call early elections
this year.
   The party leader has no policy-making powers, and there has been
widespread support in the parliamentary caucus for de Klerk to share
that power with Botha or replace him altogether.
   De Klerk, who has been education minister, is widely viewed as
more open-minded than Botha and more likely to end the black-white
political stalemate.
   Under the constitution adopted in 1984, South Africa's president
is chosen by an electoral college controlled by members of the party
with a majority in Parliament. The electoral college convenes after
a general election.
   Party leaders met for more than three hours Monday before the
caucus passed the resolution, which said it was in the national
interest for the same person to be president and party leader.
   It said the Cabinet should discuss the position with Botha, but
did not say when. De Klerk said the resolution did not imply the
president should resign immediately.
   Until Botha quit the job six weeks ago, the man serving as party
chief had led the government throughout the National Party's 40
years in power.
   In a report after the caucus announcement, the independent South
African Press Association said: ``The statement after the caucus
meeting is an unequivocal demand that Mr. Botha step down and get
out of Mr. de Klerk's way. It is now expected to be merely a matter
of time and procedure to arrange for the departure of Mr. Botha.''
   News reports said many National Party officials were angered by
Botha's refusal to call elections early. The latest election date
mentioned is March 1990.
   A party official was quoted in The Star as saying the ``situation
is intolerable and will have to be settled this week.'' The official
was not identified.
   Botha said in a television interview Sunday, after describing de
Klerk as ``misused,'' that the new party leader was ``one of my good
advisers'' and there was no personal conflict. He appeared healthy
and said he wanted to remain in office because it was his duty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
