<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonSuit     03-14 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Suit,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor's Ex-lover Files Second Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock Hudson's former homosexual companion has
filed a new lawsuit against representatives of the late actor's
estate charging they made false claims against him.
   The new $7.1 million suit was filed Monday in Superior Court on
behalf of Marc Christian, who was awarded $21.7 million from the
estate in an emotional distress suit last month. In that civil case,
a jury found that Hudson and his personal secretary, Mark Miller,
conspired to keep Christian from learning Hudson had AIDS.
   Attorneys for Hudson's estate and Miller have said they will seek
a new trial.
   The new lawsuit alleged that estate representatives knowingly
made false claims in a cross-complaint to force Christian to abandon
his earlier legal action or settle it.
   The cross-complaint, filed in February 1986 but dismissed before
the trial, alleged that Christian had sex with men and women for
money, had threatened to publish Hudson's love letters to him, had
forced the actor to let Christian live in his house and took about
$60,000 worth of the actor's property.
   Miller was named in the new complaint along with three attorneys
and Wallace Sheft, the estate's executor. The suit seeks $1 million
in general damages and $6.1 million in punitive damages.
   Harold Rhoden, Christian's attorney, could not be reached for
comment Monday night.
   Christian has tested negative for acquired immune deficiency
syndrome, but contended he suffered emotional distress after
learning that Hudson had AIDS. The actor died from AIDS-related
complications on Oct. 2, 1985.
</TEXT>
