<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     03-14 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Bureau Freezes Trust Funds in Navajo Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has frozen funds
belonging to the Navajos to prod the tribe into resolving a dispute
over the status of embattled chairman Peter MacDonald.
   James Stevens, Navajo Area director for the U.S. Bureau of Indian
Affairs, said the freeze, announced Monday, does not involve such
basic services as welfare and law enforcement and is expected to
have little immediate impact.
   Rather, Stevens said, he intended to ``put the tribe on notice''
that it must settle the dispute over MacDonald.
   He declined to say how much money was involved.
   The Tribal Council voted Feb. 17 to place MacDonald on paid leave
in the wake of corruption allegations aired during U.S. Senate
hearings. MacDonald has denied an wrongdoing and has contested the
legality of that move.
   Stevens said the freeze applies to funds in trust from such
sources as timber, coal and oil leases. The Navajos periodically
draw on the funds, mostly for tribal administrative costs, he said.
   ``We're of the position that legally we cannot say that one has
the authority to sign or the other group. And we can't make that
determination,'' he said.
   ``I agree that the BIA should stay out of politics,'' MacDonald
said in a statement.
   The Navajos are the nation's largest Indian tribe. About 150,000
of its 200,000 members live on the reservation, which is in Arizona,
New Mexico and Utah.
</TEXT>
