<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Fasts,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Wave of Hunger Strikes Reported in South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 40 detainees held
without charge have resumed or started hunger strikes at prisons in
two cities, lawyers said today.
   All but four are being held at Westville Prison in the port city
of Durban. They had suspended a hunger strike last week but resumed
the fast Sunday because they believed the government had broken a
promise to either free them or charge them, lawyer Ebrahim Goga said.
   The National Association of Democratic Lawyers said four
detainees at Pretoria Central Prison began their hunger strike last
week. They also demand that they be freed or charged.
   There have been a series of hunger strikes since January,
involving about half the estimated 1,000 detainees held at the
beginning of the year.
   The government says about 280 detainees have been released as a
result of negotiations to end the strikes, but anti-apartheid
leaders question the figure and say all detainees should be freed.
   Severe restrictions have been imposed on many detainees released
in the past few weeks.
   Leon Mellet, a spokesman for the Law and Order Ministry, said
activists ``are trying to rekindle the hunger strike for political
and propaganda purposes.''
   ``They do not have the interests of the detainees at heart,'' he
said.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying periods under the 3-year-old state of emergency.
