<FIRST>r i PM-China     03-14 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Official Defends Action in Tibet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief government spokesman today defended
China's crackdown on protesters in Tibet and said authorities will
never allow the region to be independent.
   In a wide-ranging news conference, Yuan Mu also denounced dissent
within China. He said a battle to improve the economy is showing
results.
   Asked about recent campaigns by Chinese intellectuals calling for
democratic reforms and the release of political prisoners, Yuan
said, ``We are not happy with this situation.''
   China's constitution, Yuan said, guarantees freedom of speech,
``but no one is allowed to infringe upon the interests of the state,
society and other citizens.''
   He said some critics of the government, whom he did not name,
were denying the basic tenets of Marxism and rule of the Communist
Party and ``relying on foreign forces'' to spread their message.
   ``This is something we are not in favor of,'' he said. ``China
has no intention to import from Western political systems things
which are not in keeping with reality in China.''
   Yuan denied China has any political prisoners.
   China showed its displeasure with political activism by
preventing astrophysicist Fang Lizhi, the nation's best known
dissident, from attending a banquet held by President Bush during
Bush's visit last month.
   Asked about Tibet, where dozens of people have died in
anti-Chinese riots since 1987 _ including 16 people killed last week
_ Yuan said ``conflicts arise'' there because ``some separatists
want to split Tibet from the motherland, and we won't allow that.''
   ``The channel for dialogue is always open'' with Tibet's exiled
spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, Yuan said.
   The Dalai Lama has agreed to talk to the Chinese, but China
rejects his proposals to give Tibet greater regional autonomy.
   Yuan said China's six-month effort to reduce an inflation rate
officially set at 26 percent has had some success, although
``further efforts will be faced with great difficulties.''
   He also said government reassertion of controls over many aspects
of the economy is not a setback for the 10-year-old policies of
market-oriented reforms.
   ``While enlivening the economy, chaos can't appear,'' he said.
``Good order must be maintained while invigorating enterprises.''
   Saving deposits are on the rise, the momentum of price rises has
leveled off since the beginning of the year and industrial growth
through February has been held to a manageable 8 percent, less than
half the overheated rate of the past year, he said.
   Yuan said further reforms in the nation's heavily subsidized
price system, deemed crucial to increased productivity and economic
efficiency, will slow this year because of the inflation problem.
   Asked if the government would meet its goal of substantially
lowering inflation this year, Yuan said it will be ``very
difficult.... That remains to be seen.''
</TEXT>
