<FIRST>r a PM-MedicaidFraud     03-14 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicaid Fraud,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Pleads Guilty in $3.6 Million Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor pleaded guilty to charges he bought
blood from junkies and the poor and then billed Medicaid for $3.6
million worth of unnecessary lab tests.
   Prosecutor Edward J. Kuriansky of the attorney general's office
called the scam ``the largest and most nefarious fraud ever
perpetrated on this country's health care system.''
   Dr. Surinder Singh Panshi, 40, pleaded guilty Monday to all 127
counts against him.
   Panshi recruited junkies and the poor to sell a pint of blood for
$10. Investigators raiding apartments where the blood was given
often found lines of poor people waiting to get in, said Sonya
Hoover, a spokeswoman for Kuriansky.
   Tests on the blood then were performed in Panshi's laboratories,
where one pint could yield $2,000 in billings to Medicaid, the
federal health-care program for the poor, said Kuriansky.
   In 2{ years, the labs billed Medicaid more than $31.6 million.
Officials do not know how much of the total was legitimate.
   ``The $3.6 million is what we felt we could prove in a court of
law,'' Hoover said.
   State Supreme Court Justice Herbert A. Posner ordered the labs to
repay the $3.6 million. The judge indicated he would give Panshi a
five- to 10-year prison term at sentencing April 6 and order him to
repay $300,000.
   Officials began looking into the scam after emergency room
doctors reported that junkies were showing up with ``half their
blood supply gone,'' said Hoover.
   Panshi pleaded guilty to grand larceny, conspiracy, offering a
false instrument for filing and falsifying business records.
   His father, Gurdial Singh Panshi, is also charged in the case and
is the subject of an international manhunt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
