<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     03-14 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Says Cambodia Still Holds Hundreds of Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International today urged Cambodia to
furnish information about hundreds of political prisoners the human
rights group says remain jailed despite an amnesty proclaimed last
May.
   Amnesty said it has names of more than 400 people, including some
prisoners arrested as long ago as 1979 who have yet to be charged or
tried, and others who may have died in jail.
   ``Amnesty International asks for an independent and impartial
investigation into the deaths of these prisoners,'' the London-based
organization said in a statement issued by its French section.
   It said the Cambodian Council of State declared an amnesty for
political prisoners in May 1988, but ``it is difficult to see who
benefited from it. What's more, sentences have been prolonged for
prisoners refusing to `repent.'''
   Amnesty said 412 people were arrested in the first nine months of
1988, all considered ``hidden enemy elements.''
   ``In the course of recent years, Amnesty International has made
known on numerous occasions its preoccupation with the allegations
of torture and the detention of numerous political prisoners (in
Cambodia),'' Amnesty said. ``In June 1987, the organization
published a report on this subject. The Cambodia government has
never reacted to requests for information and to proposals for
sending a delegation to the country.''
</TEXT>
