<FIRST>r a PM-Ex-WifeSlain     03-14 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ex-Wife Slain,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Officials Face Disciplinary Hearings In Prison Furlough Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven state corrections officials face
disciplinary hearings for their roles in approving an eight-hour
pass for an inmate who allagedly murdered his ex-wife while he was
out of prison.
   Gov. Evan Bayh announced the proceedings Monday as he received an
internal report that showed officials knew that Alan L. Matheney
harbored ill will toward his ex-wife and that she had expressed fear
over any plan to release him.
   Matheney, 38, is charged in the March 3 beating death of Lisa
Marie Bianco, 29, outside her home in Mishawaka.
   Among those facing hearings, which could begin this week, are the
superintendent of the Correctional Industrial Complex at Pendleton,
where Matheney was serving an eight-year sentence for beating Ms.
Bianco and confining their children in 1987.
   ``He had no business being part of the (furlough) program,'' said
Bayh, who has suspended the program pending review by new correction
Commissioner James E. Aiken.
   The report by Board of Correction Chairwoman Virginia Dill
McCarty said officials had denied Matheney's requests for passes six
times. Bayh and McCarty also said officials should have notified the
prosecutor's office or Bianco of the pass.
   A prison counselor, replying to a letter from Bianco, had written
the woman in January to say she would be notified before Matheney's
release, the report said.
   ``We have a questionable program, implemented poorly, compounded
by human error,'' Bayh said.
   Aiken, serving his first day on the job Monday, said it is
impossible to say that the slaying could have been prevented even if
the program had been administered more strictly.
   Bayh said the seven correction officials, two of whom were
suspended last week, could receive punishments ranging from verbal
reprimands to dismissal.
   Those scheduled for hearings also include the director of the
division of adult institutions and two assistant superintendents.
   McCarty said prison officials first behaved well in response to
Matheney's requests for passes but ``as time passed, the combination
of lack of clear lines of authority, lack of procedures, perhaps CIC
personnel's lack of training in special assignment procedures and
human error caused the system to fail.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
