<FIRST>u i PM-India-Blasts     03-14 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Blasts,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>17 Killed In Bomb Blasts By Tribal Militants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY SABITA GOSWAMI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUWAHATI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded simultaneously today
in a northeastern Indian town, killing at least 17 people, and state
officials said separatist tribal militants were responsible for the
attacks.
   Police said at least 48 people were injured by the blasts in the
town of Bongaigaon in Assam state.
   Police said two bombs went off in a crowded marketplace and a
third occurred near a railroad crossing.
   Unofficial sources said the death toll could be at least 20.
   A government official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the bombs were planted by Bodo tribespeople who are demanding a
separate homeland on the northern bank of the Brahmaputra River in
Assam, a remote and hilly state bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   The bombings were the most serious attacks attributed to the
Bodos since they began their separatist campaign in 1987, claiming
discrimination by other settlers of the area.
   Today's deaths raise to 99 the number of people reported killed
by Bodo militants. At least 44 of the victims have been killed since
Feb. 8.
   Many people have fled Bodo-dominated regions, fearing more
violence, police said.
   The Bodo Students Union has called for a 15-day statewide general
strike starting Wednesday in support of its demand for a separate
state, which would cover about one-third of Assam, mostly prime
forest and cultivable land.
   The Bodos claim migration to their traditional homeland by
non-tribals has caused economic and social repression. The problem
has been simmering for more than 20 years, but there were few
reports of violence until about two years ago.
   The Bodos were animists before they converted earlier this
century to Hinduism and Christianity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
