<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovak-Havel     03-14 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovak-Havel,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel Appeal Set; Other Dissidents Face Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czech playwright and activist Vaclav
Havel, imprisoned after being convicted of taking part in a protest,
will get an appeal hearing on March 21, his brother said today.
   Ivan Havel, speaking by telephone from Prague, said the
prosecution also has appealed for a longer sentence and a fine for
his brother.
   The playwright filed an appeal seeking to overturn the conviction
immediately after a Prague court sentenced him Feb. 21 to nine
months in jail on charges of incitement and obstructing a police
officer.
   The charges arose from an unprecedented week of public protest in
Prague in January. The protests marked the 20th anniversary of the
death of Czech student Jan Palach, who set himself on fire in 1969
to protest the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Havel's jailing provoked strong protests from several Western
nations and even from the East bloc, where Polish Premier Mieczyslaw
Rakowski attended a Warsaw premiere of two Havel plays _ both banned
in Czechoslovakia _ the weekend after the Prague trial.
   The sentencing was part of a communist crackdown on dissent that
resulted in the jailing of two more activists last week and led to
fines, jail terms or suspended sentences for seven other dissidents.
   The London-based emigre publishing house Palach Press said Monday
that two leaders of the Independent Peace Association who were
arrested in October will be tried in Prague on Thursday on charges
of incitement. If convicted, they could be jailed for up to five
years.
   Hana Marvanova and Tomas Dvorak have been charged with incitement
on grounds of addressing a crowd at an Aug. 21 rally in Prague that
turned into a demonstration by about 10,000 people protesting the
Soviet-led invasion of 1968 that crushed communist reforms.
   The two face an additional charge of preparing to incite in
connection with an Oct. 28 demonstration to mark the 70th
anniversary of Czechoslovakia's pre-World War II independence,
Palach Press said.
   Also, it said, a Brno cultural activist, Eva Vidlarova, will be
tried March 23 on charges she organized a petition for another
jailed cultural activist.
</TEXT>
