<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0525 03-14 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Blaze in a Year Damages Cairo Landmark</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with one death. Pick up 4th pvs,
``Official Radio ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man died today as fire gutted the top two
floors of a 27-story building housing the government's radio and
television services. It was the second blaze in less than a year to
hit the Cairo landmark on the banks of the Nile.
   Officials in the building and witnesses said the fire started at
7:15 a.m. and was under control two hours later. It was restricted
to the top floors and roof, which holds a transmitting tower.
   Immediately after the blaze was extinguished, Cairo governor
Youssef Sabry Abu-Taleb said it caused no casualties. But police
sources reported later that firefighters searching the ruins found a
man's charred body on the 27th floor. They identified it as that of
Wasfi Zaki Abdel-Malaak, a night watchman.
   Two firefighters and five employees in the building were treated
for smoke inhalation, the sources said on condition of anonymity.
   Official Radio Cairo broadcast a government statement saying ``a
malfunction in a subsidiary electric connection, far away from the
main cables powering radio transmissions'' caused the fire.
   Interior Minister Zaki Badr, who was at the scene, said the fire
was being investigated. He ruled out sabotage.
   The two top floors of the 29-year-old building contain
administrative offices and were believed to have been unoccupied
when the fire began. The work day for radio and television
administrative employees normally begins after 8 a.m.
   About two dozen fire engines rushed to the scene, where flames
poured out of the two floors and licked at the bottom of the roof.
But the first ladders only went up the side of the building an hour
after the fire began.
   Two military helicopters circled above, and river police provided
special boats to supply additional water for firefighters.
   An electrical short circuit caused a smoky fire on the eighth
floor of the building last April, and 40 people were treated for
smoke inhalation.
   The building houses about 6,000 people at peak working hours _
employees of state radio and television, broadcast artists and the
staff of the Information Ministry that controls them. Several
hundred people probably were in the building at the time of the
fire, most of them in the first nine floors, officials said.
</TEXT>
