<HEAD>Man Dies After Getting Caught in Rock Crusher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with man's death.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 61-year-old quarry worker who was trapped
for four hours in a rock crusher died today, hours after doctors
amputated his legs to free him from the machine, hospital officials
said.
   After his legs were severed at mid-thigh, Clinton Tyler, an
employee at the Boutwell Limerock Co. quarry, was taken by
helicopter to Shands Teaching Hospital in Gainesville, where he
underwent four hours of surgery, said Sgt. Ken Ergle of the Marion
County Sheriff's Department.
   Tyler died at 4:40 a.m., said hospital spokesman Chris Smith.
   Tyler, of Zuber, was extracting flintrock from the crusher Monday
evening when the accident occurred, Ergle said.
   Tyler told his rescuers he switched the gears to neutral and
climbed inside to correct a malfunction when the machine kicked into
gear, Ergle said. A co-worker quickly turned off the machine but
Tyler's legs were crushed.
