<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DeathPlot     03-14 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Plot,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoner Planned Murder-For-Hire `Bloodbath,' Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate hatched at least a dozen
murder-for-hire plots from his cell, and the intended victims
included a federal judge, a state appeals court justice, witnesses
and a reporter, a newspaper reported today.
   Kevin James Veschi, serving a life term in a maximum-security
prison, planned a ``bloodbath of maniacal proportions,'' said Bexar
County First Assistant District Attorney Jamie Boyd.
   The district attorney's office named the 12 intended victims and
six possible conspirators in an affidavit submitted to obtain a
warrant to search Veschi's cell Monday, Boyd said.
   The San Antonio Express-News reported that the intended victims
included Boyd, another prosecutor and a reporter for the newspaper,
John Moulder, who broke the story about Veschi's criminal activities
in 1987.
   Veschi later was convicted of attempted capital murder,
aggravated robbery and burglary. Prosecutors said he operated a
criminal organization that was involved in daylight burglaries, auto
thefts and threats.
   The newspaper reported that it delayed by two days its account of
the death plots to avoid interfering with an undercover part of the
investigation.
   In New Jersey, an agent, posing as a hit man and a friend of
Veschi's, met on Monday with a woman who wanted her husband killed,
said the affidavit. The woman offered to pay $5,000 to Veschi and
$5,000 to the killer, it said.
   The newspaper said officials in New Jersey were preparing charges
against the woman, whose identity was not disclosed.
   Other intended victims, according to the newspaper, were U.S.
District Judge H.F. ``Hippo'' Garcia; an appellate judge, three
lawyers who represented Veschi; a former prosecutor; a burglar who
testified against Veschi, and a woman who was to be killed in a life
insurance scheme.
   Boyd said the targets were notified, and federal marshals, the
FBI and the Texas Rangers were called to help provide protection.
   Authorities said that when officers at the state prison at
Rosharon went to search his cell, Veschi had to be dragged out,
cursing and screaming. Letters, photos and other papers were taken
from Veschi's cell, Boyd said.
   The affidavit said that a prison neighbor of Veschi's, murderer
John Marco Civella, 33, was a prospective hit man in the scheme.
   Civella, due to be released later this year, said Veschi promised
him guns, rental cars, ``safe houses,'' cocaine and an immediate
$10,000, the newspaper reported.
   Civella, discussing Veschi, told the San Antonio reporter: ``He's
got that kingpin mentality where he thinks he's a (obscenity) Al
Capone.''
</TEXT>
