<FIRST>r i PM-Chile-Fruit 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Fruit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0461,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile Promises Fruit Safeguards After Cyanide Found In Grapes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New grafs 4-5 to UPDATE with Japanese reports that fruit imports
from Chile will be halted, edit for transition. Picks up 5th graf pvs:
``Chile has...'' ^By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has promised to protect
Chilean fruit from further contamination and is blaming terrorists
and communists for a cyanide scare that threatens one of the
country's most lucrative exports.
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration on Monday warned consumers
not to eat any fruit imported from Chile after traces of cyanide
were found in Chilean seedless red grapes in Philadelphia.
   The cyanide was discovered after an anonymous threat to poison
Chilean fruit was telephoned to the U.S. Embassy in Santiago on
March 2.
   News reports in Japan said today the Japanese Embassy in Santiago
had received a similar call warning of cyanide poisoning. The
reports said Japan will halt Chilean fruit imports.
   Chile's interior minister, Carlos Caceres, went on national radio
and television Monday night and blamed ``terrorism supported by
international communism which does not hesitate in damaging not only
our economic interests but also our social and moral interests.''
   Chile has been under right-wing military rule since September
1973, when the armed forced ousted the elected government of Marxist
President Salvador Allende. The coup was led by Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, the current president.
   Despite the cyanide scare, Caceres said Chile ``will continue to
be a dependable supplier'' to the international fruit market.
   Security has been reinforced throughout the fruit-exporting
process ``from the crop to the port of destiny,'' he said.
   Caceres said an investigation conducted after the anonymous
caller said some export fruits would be laced with poison had
uncovered no problem.
   ``We have now come from the anonymous threat to the concrete
damage,'' he added.
   Four days after the poisoning threat was made, the FDA said the
call was ``almost certainly a hoax,'' but that it would continue to
examine samples of Chilean fruit.
   After later confirming cyanide in the Philadelphia samples, the
FDA urged that all Chilean fruit be removed from U.S. markets and
that shipments of Chilean fruits which had not yet been distributed
should be held for testing.
   ``This may be an isolated incident, but we can hardly take that
chance,'' FDA Commissioner Frank Young said Monday.
   Hours later, Canadian officials urged stores in Canada to remove
all Chilean produce.
   Health Minister Perrin Beatty asked stores to remove Chilean
produce from their shelves and advised Canadians to throw away any
fruit and vegetables they know came from Chile or think may have
come from there.
   Joe Pusateri, owner of Pusateri's supermarket in downtown
Toronto, said if he takes Chilean produce off his shelves, he won't
have anything left to sell.
   ``All my grapes, peaches, nectarines and apples come from
Chile,'' Pusateri said. ``If they're no good, what am I going to do
_ throw them in the garbage?''
   All Chilean fruit imported into Canada passes through the United
States.
   Caceres said government supervisors have been placed at every
stage of Chile's fruit-exporting process and the government is
working in cooperation with private exporters.
   He also said technicians from the Agriculture Ministry and other
agencies conducted tests Monday on a variety of fruits ready for
export and found nothing wrong.
   Caceres said the government is doing ``everything possible to
limit this unprecedented damage to the nation'' that has affected
thousands of Chilean families.
   Chile's fruit exports have been booming in recent years and it
has now become the leading importer of fresh fruit to North America
during the Northern Hemisphere's winter.
   Central Bank figures showed in 1988 that those exports reached
$584.1 million _ more than 25 percent of country's trade surpus for
last year.
   Chile's main fruit exports are grapes, melons, apples and
peaches. Imports of Chilean apples to the United States went from
16,258 tons in 1983 to 47,322 tons in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PriestProtest     03-14 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Priest Protest,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priests Demonstrate for Higher Pay, Better Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish clergymen marched through the
city today demanding higher wages and shorter working hours in what
was believed to be the first such protest in the 400-year history of
the state church.
   ``I think God is smiling in heaven,'' said the Rev. Kerstin
Propper, an assistant vicar and official of the clergymen's union.
   ``This is good for the church. The church needs it,'' she told a
radio reporter who asked what God might think of the demonstration.
   Police said there were about 150 demonstrators, some carrying
banners. One said: ``Salary according to performance.''
   ``This is a big step. Priests have never raised their voices
before. We have suffered in silence, now we have reached the
threshold of pain,'' said Ms. Propper.
   The Lutheran priests, wearing traditional black vestments and
clerical collars, marched through central Stockholm to the Office of
State Employment. Priests of the Swedish Lutheran Church are civil
servants paid by the goverment.
   The clergymen's union says real wages have dropped 40 percent
since 1970 because of inflation and that many clergymen are burdened
by debts following extensive studies of theology. They also have
complained about working overtime without compensation.
   The starting monthly salary for a priest is about $1,325. Ms.
Propper said her salary was $2,040 a month after working 18 years as
a priest. The average Swedish blue-collar worker earns about $1,412
a month.
   Our employer ``says that we should be idealistic. That is old
fashioned thinking,'' Ms. Propper said.
</TEXT>
