<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0464 03-14 0966</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Israel Share Sense of Urgency but Disagree on PLO</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 11 grafs new with Arens quotes; Editing throughout to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, accusing
the Palestine Liberation Organization of ``the worst atrocities
we've ever seen since World War II,'' said today his government
shares the U.S. desire for peace in the Middle East but must cope
with dangerous radicalism.
   Arens, who is to meet today with members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said on ``CBS This Morning'' that the PLO is
trying to impose itself in the area and is scaring King Hussein of
Jordan away from the peace table.
   But he said on NBC's ``Today'' show that a suggestion by
Secretary of State James A. Baker III that Israel and the PLO
consider reciprocal gestures to reduce tensions on the West Bank and
in Gaza ``is something that needs to be investigated.''
   Arens said Israel was in the midst of selecting areas in the
occupied territories where troops could be reduced. ``I think we
will see, and I can report back to you, as to whether the results
are positive or not.'' he said.
   On Monday, Arens told President Bush and Baker that U.S. talks
with the PLO would not contribute to peace-making efforts in the
Middle East.
   He said on the CBS show today that the PLO was an umbrella
organization for 10 to 12 different terrorist groups. ``They've
carried out the worst atrocities we've ever seen since World War
II,'' Arens said. ``They are trying to impose themselves on the
area. They are scaring Hussein away from the peace table. They tried
to overthrow his regime...in September of 1970. They're carrying out
terrorist activities.''
   Arens added, ``This kind of violence will not be conducive to the
peace process at all.''
   Arens called attention to the bombing last week in San Diego of
the car driven by the wife of Capt. Will Rogers, who commands the
guided missile frigate Vincennes which accidentally shot down an
Iranian jetliner in the Persian Gulf.
   ``You've seen the gutted car of the skipper of the Vincennes,''
Arens said on NBC. ``We see that on Israeli television every day.
We've had 1,500 cases like that this past year, people burned alive.
Dealing with that kind of terrorism is not an easy thing, and I
don't know that anybody really has a prescription on how to do it.
   ``I think the important thing is to demonstrate that this kind of
violence is not going to pay off,'' Arens said.
   But the Bush administration intends to push ahead in dealing with
the PLO, and is making plans for a sixth session with a PLO
representative next week in Tunisia.
   The talks were opened in December over Israel's objections. Since
then Palestinian guerrillas have clashed several times with Israeli
soldiers in southern Lebanon. While criticizing the PLO, Secretary
of State James A. Baker III has concluded the attacks do not
constitute terrorism.
   Arens found himself in basic agreement with President Bush and
Baker that there is an urgent need for peace-making in the Middle
East.
   Arens said they had also concluded that King Hussein of Jordan
was the ``key element'' in the process and a way must be found to
get him involved.
   But Arens told Israeli reporters after the talks on Monday that
he made the point the PLO was still engaged in terrorism on three
levels.
   He said Yasser Arafat's organization had sent guerrillas on
several infiltration raids, called for violence on the Israeli-held
West Bank and in Gaza, and threatened Palestinian Arabs who
disagreed with the PLO.
   ``There is a sense of urgency here, and even more so in Israel,''
Arens said of the need for a Mideast settlement. ``I told the
secretary and the president that since we are confronted with this
difficulty in promoting peace because so many elements are not
interested in peace it is very important we work together.''
   A senior U.S. official said, meanwhile, that Baker told Arens he
considered the situation in the territories ``untenable'' and wanted
Israel to suggest ways to reduce tensions with the predominantly
Palestinian Arab population.
   ``The object is to calm the environment, not as an end in itself
but to create conditions that will allow direct talks,'' said the
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in Gaza have been in
rebellion against Israeli control for 15 months. Amid the violence
396 Arabs and 17 Israelis have died.
   ``We certainly want to reduce tension,'' Arens told reporters at
the State Department. He added: ``It's not easy to do that
considering the violence in the area at the present time.''
   However, Arens also said: ``I think we will find common ground on
how to do this.''
   ``We didn't arrive at any finalized or defined positions,'' Arens
said. ``I think it is probably premature to expect that at this
point.''
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said the
administration was seeking ``new ideas'' to advance the peace
process.
   ``President Bush emphasized that the United States does not want
to miss an opportunity for peace in the Middle East and still
believes in direct talks as the best path to peace,'' Fitzwater said
in a statement.
   Baker said he was seeking ``various reinforcing and reciprocal
steps which might be taken to defuse the tension there'' on the West
Bank and Gaza. He was not specific. But even before Arens' arrival
on Sunday, published reports said they included release of
Palestinian prisoners and a general easing of Israeli control.
   Next week, Robert Pelletreau Jr., the U.S. ambassador to Tunisia,
is expected to ask the Palestine Liberation Organization to block
guerrillas from trying to infiltrate Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
