<FIRST>r a PM-TexasFires     03-14 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Fires,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blazes Blacken Thousands Of Acres Throughout Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wind whipped grassfires for miles from Big Bend
National Park in southwestern Texas to the Louisiana border,
prompting a statewide fire alert.
   The fires have burned 44,000 acres since Saturday, killing a
dozen cattle and destroying or damaging nearly a dozen homes but
causing no deaths, authorities said. A fire chief was hospitalized
briefly after being overcome by smoke.
   Officials declared the fire alert on Monday, meaning that
conditions are dry and windy, with plentiful dry grass, timber and
dead vegetation that could fuel wildfires. Officials were
considering a ban on outdoor burning.
   Authorities blamed open burning for at least one fire and said a
cigarette started another.
   The alert remains in effect until rain lessens the fire threat.
But forecasters said no rain is expected for days.
   ``March, with its traditional high winds and low humidities and
cured fuels, is always our potentially most hazardous fire period of
the year,'' said Bruce Miles, director of the Texas Forest Service.
   Fires blackened 38,000 acres in Dickens County in the lower
Panhandle before being put out Monday around daybreak and burned
1,000 acres on the Camp Swift military reservation, 40 miles from
Austin. The fire was under control by midday Monday.
   Flames also scorched 615 acres of the High Chisos Mountains in
the worst fire in Big Bend National Park's history, and drained
firefighters in Odessa and Ector counties, who battled 36 blazes,
including one that covered 640 acres.
   A total of 151 other wildfires burned more than 3,500 acres in
the Southeastern Piney Woods through Sunday, the forest service said.
</TEXT>
