<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Vincennes-Bomb     03-14 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vincennes-Bomb,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator: Bombing Investigators Don't Expect International Link</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI seems to be backing off the theory
that the bombing of a Navy captain's van was internationally
directed terrorism because the device was a crude pipe bomb, U.S.
Sen. Pete Wilson says.
   No one has claimed responsibility for the bombing Friday of the
van driven by Sharon Rogers, the wife of USS Vincennes Capt. Will
Rogers III.
   But because Rogers ordered the mistaken downing of an Iranian
passenger jet in July, FBI officials said he is receiving protection
as a potential target of terrorists.
   ``It is their belief a sophisticated terrorist, one who is
trained in the use of explosives for car bombings, would have done a
better job and that (Mrs. Rogers) would not have escaped,'' Wilson
said Monday.
   ``It is either someone acting independently, on their own, which
I suspect to be the case, or it was conceivable that it was an act
of state-sponsored terrorism. But most of the indications point to
the former.''
   However, New York Newsday reported today that federal sources in
Washington said the CIA is providing the FBI with intelligence in
the case. Because the CIA is forbidden by law from gathering
intelligence within the United States, the report indicated
continuing suspicion of foreign involvement.
   Wilson, a California Republican, said his information was based
primarily on news reports and a conversation with the Rogerses. The
couple remain in hiding under the protection of Naval Investigative
Service agents.
   Pentagon sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, noted
Monday that Buck Revell, a top FBI official, warned of the potential
terrorist threat posed by Iranian students in the United States
while testifying to Congress recently.
   Revell cited the San Diego region as one area with a high number
of Iranian students, but the sources cautioned against drawing the
inference that students were behind the incident.
   While the FBI began examining debris from the explosion, the
agency would not comment publicly on the investigation, but
newspapers quoted federal sources they did not identify regarding
theories investigators are discussing.
   Although investigators are still treating the bombing as possible
terrorism, it may have been carried out by disgruntled sailors from
Rogers' ship or one or more Iranians acting on their own, an FBI
official told the Los Angeles Times.
   ``Not any of this is being ruled out,'' he said.
   The bomb detonated as Mrs. Rogers drove to work alone. She
escaped uninjured moments before the van caught fire and burned.
   Both the Los Angeles Times and The New York Times quoted sources
as saying the bomb may have been a heat-sensitive device.
   A small piece of light wood such as balsa could have been placed
between the bomb and the van's undercarriage so that when the engine
got hot, it would ignite the wood and detonate the device, the Los
Angeles Times said.
   No sign of a detonating device was found among pipe bomb
fragments recovered; the newspaper's source said that contributes to
the theory.
   He and others also noted that the bomb detonated while Mrs.
Rogers was stopped at a traffic light.
   ``Most heat comes from an automobile transmission, when the car
is stopped and waiting in traffic, so this theory makes sense,''
another official said.
</TEXT>
