<FIRST>r a PM-LATeachers     03-14 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Teachers,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Teachers Vote to Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers from the nation's second-largest
school district have authorized a summer strike that could stall the
release of final grades and prevent some students from graduating,
union leaders say.
   The vote by the United Teachers of Los Angeles, taken last week
and hand-counted, was 16,264 in favor to 1,909 against, UTLA
President Wayne Johnson said Monday. Th union represents 22,000 of
the district's 32,000 teachers.
   The teachers will continue negotiations, but ``the odds are very
high ... there will be a nasty, bitter strike'' as early as June,
Johnson said.
   The teachers, working without a contract since June, have
demanded a two-year wage increase of 21 percent. Board president
Roberta Weintraub said the district had made its final offer, a 20
percent raise over three years.
   The teachers' average salary is $36,600.
   A walkout near the end of the school year could tie up grades for
the district's 594,000 students, prevent some seniors from
graduating and affect students applying to colleges, said
Superintendent Leonard Britton.
   The teachers are barred by law from striking without a previous
fact-finding period in which a neutral panel reviews the disputed
issues.
   The union's last strike, in 1970, lasted 23 days.
</TEXT>
