<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Azores-Crash     03-14 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Azores-Crash,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overlapping Radio Messages May Have Caused Azores Jet Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overlapping radio messages between a
pilot and air traffic controllers probably led to a jet crash in the
Azores that killed 144 people, government investigators said today.
   The Ministry of Public Works, Transport and Communications said
that because of the overlapping conversations, the pilot apparently
descended to 2,000 feet when he should have remained at 3,000 feet.
   The American-chartered Boeing 707, filled with Italian tourists
on their way to the Caribbean, slammed into a fog-covered mountain
on the Azores island of Santa Maria on Feb. 8. All on board died.
   According to the ministry statement, the control tower authorized
the pilot to descend to 3,000 feet. It then informed the pilot which
runway to use and asked him to renew contact when the plane was at
3,000 feet.
   At the same time the control tower was relaying its second
message, the pilot was announcing plans to drop to 2,000 feet.
   Neither side heard the other's message, the ministry concluded.
   ``The plane hit ... in a zone where flying is not permitted below
an altitude of 3,000 feet,'' the report said.
   The commission also said controllers gave the jet's crew an
atmospheric pressure reading of 1,027 millibars instead of the
correct 1,108.7 millibars. The difference in pressure readings would
mean the jet's altimeters told the pilot he was 240 feet above his
actual position.
   The plane, owned by Independent Air Corp., of Smyrna, Tenn.,
crashed into 1,936 foot Pico Alto.
   According to the statement, the commission found no evidence of
mechanical or technical failure of the plane or its equipment. The
commission's report also ruled out sabotage or other criminal
action, the statement said.
</TEXT>
