<FIRST>u i PM-Brazil 3rdLd-Writethru   03-14 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0560,0769</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Strands Commuters, But Many Workers Show Up At Jobs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with additional violence. Pickup
22nd pvs, `The general...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of commuters were stranded
nationwide today as public transportation shut down at the start of
a 48-hour general strike called by leftist labor groups.
   However, many Brazilians ignored the strike call and went to work.
   The subway in Sao Paulo, the nation's largest city with 10
million people, operated normally, as did a small number of
privately owned buses. But the city's public bus fleet was idled.
   In greater Sao Paulo, with a population of 15 million, more than
70 percent of the 2 million factory workers showed up at their jobs,
according to the Federation of Industries of Sao Paulo State.
   The city's suburbs are home to Brazil's foreign-owned auto plants
_ including General Motors, Ford and Volkswagen _ and a center of
strike organization.
   International and domestic airlines flew on normal schedules, and
supermarkets, gas stations, small shops and corner cafes opened.
   Brazil's two largest labor movements _ the radical left Central
Workers Union and the more moderate General Workers Central _ called
the strike to protest President Jose Sarney's anti-inflation policy,
which has frozen workers' pay since January.
   ``I would say we can consider the strike a success. I am sure
that as the day progresses the strike will grow,'' Sergio dos Santos
said in a telephone interview early today from strike headquarters
in Sao Paulo.
   Some violence was reported. In Sao Paulo, rock-throwers damaged
about 30 buses and one person was arrested, police said.
   In Rio de Janeiro, the nation's second-largest city, strikers
threw stones and punctured tires of some privately owned buses that
attempted to operate. City-owned buses did not run.
   Police with billy clubs beat and detained several people accused
of trying to loot stores in Caxias, on the northern outskirts of Rio
de Janeiro.
   A photographer of the Jornal do Brasil newspaper who was taking
pictures of the beatings was shot in the hand by a policeman,
according to the Jornal do Brasil radio station, which is owned by
the newspaper.
   Sarney's centrist government warned it would not allow violence
and accused the labor groups of trying to seize control of Latin
America's largest country.
   ``We have reliable information that violence against the freedom
to work is planned,'' Justice Minister Oscar Dias Correa told the
nation of 144 million people in a radio and television broadcast.
   Army troops were posted in Rio outside the main downtown station
of the government-run commuter railroad, which was shut down. The
trains normally carry about 1 million commuters a day.
   Rio's subway was shut down, as was the government-run commuter
ferry service across world-famous Guanabara Bay.
   In Brasilia, the capital, Labor Minister Dorothea Werneck kept in
telephone contact with authorities in Brazil's 26 states to assess
the degree of participation in the strike.
   The unions that called the strike together claim to represent 35
million of the nation's 60 million workers.
   The general strike was Brazil's third since the nation returned
to civilian rule in 1985. The first, in December 1986, was partly
successful. The second, in August 1987, was a failure.
   ``This year, the two labor movements have put aside their
rivalries and we are much better prepared,'' said Jair Meneguelli,
president of the Central Workers Union.
   At issue is a wage freeze that is part of the government's Jan.
15 ``Summer Plan,'' an austerity package that also includes a price
freeze and other measures aimed at bringing down 1,000 percent
annual inflation.
   The plan brought inflation down from a rate of 28.7 percent a
month in December to 3.6 percent for the first 11 days of February,
the latest period for which government figures are available.
   But Meneguelli said the wage freeze slashed workers' purchasing
power by up to 49 percent ``and we want it back.'' More than half of
Brazilian workers earn less than $50 a week.
   The government concedes that purchasing power dropped, but has
not given figures.
   The Sao Paulo State Federation of Industries said in a statement
that the general strike was aimed exclusively at ``the destruction
of the Summer Plan, which despite its errors was the only viable way
to stop a process of hyperinflation, which threatened to lead Brazil
to chaos.''
   The country is saddled with a $115 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
