<DOCNO> AP890314-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchProtest     03-14 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Protest,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Vote to Reopen Church Divided by Transfer of Popular Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warnings against disruptions will be
posted when a church that closed a month ago because of protests by
parishioners reopens.
   Three weeks after police were summoned to St. Michael the
Archangle Roman Catholic Church to oust dissidents protesting the
transfer of a Polish priest, the parish corporation voted Friday to
reopen the church, Edward Tulinski said Monday.
   The church will probably resume Masses by Sunday, which is Palm
Sunday, said Tulinski, one of two lay members of the five-member
board.
   ``They were eager to reopen the church for the Easter holidays,''
he said.
   On the advice of the corporation's lawyer, signs will be posted
threatening the arrest of anyone who attempts to occupy the church
or undertake any activity not authorized by the Rev. John Bambol,
the pastor, Tulinski said.
   The predominantly Polish church has been closed since Feb. 18,
when church officials called police to end a weeklong sit-in by
about 200 parishioners upset by the transfer of the Rev. Roman
Palaszewski.
   The dissidents charged that Bambol engineered Palaszewski's
ouster because he was too active in the Polish community, and they
questioned Bambol's commitment to maintaining the church's Polish
character.
   Bambol and his supporters have blamed much of the unrest on
recent immigrants from Poland and say they have the backing of 95
percent of the 1,400 families belonging to the parish.
   One dissident leader vowed to defy the order against unauthorized
activities in the church.
   ``I'll be the first to get arrested again,'' said Henry Chmiel,
one of two parshioners arrested when police marched in and ordered
the dissidents to leave.
   A few hours after the dissidents were removed, Bishop Edward Egan
announced that the church was being closed indefinitely on grounds
that the protest had made it impossible to conduct services in a
reverential manner.
   The protesters have held prayer vigils outside the church each
Sunday since.
   Monsignor Nicholas Grieco, a spokesman for the bishop, said
Palaszewksi will not be returned to the church and Bambol will not
be removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
