<HEAD>Jet Makes Emergency Landing On Municipal Airstrip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that airstrip is a municipal field;
ADDS information about transport of evacuated passengers; ADDS that there
was no fire. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing 727 carrying 124 people made an
emergency landing at a municipal airport east of Dallas today after
a warning light falsely indicated an engine fire, Delta Air Lines
said. No one was injured.
   ``There was no fire and the crew and the passengers were all
off-loaded by the aircraft chutes,'' said Federal Aviation
Administration spokeswoman Gerrie Cook in Fort Worth.
   Inspectors found a pneumatic duct leak in one engine but no sign
of fire, Ms. Cook said.
   Delta said that the landing was a precaution and that there had
been no immediate danger.
   The jet, en route from Atlanta to San Diego, landed at Majors
Field 40 miles from Dallas shortly after 9 a.m. More than an hour
later the plane remained on the runway awaiting inspection and
repair, Ms. Cook said.
   Delta chartered buses to bring the 117 passengers and crew of
seven to Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport so they could make
connections to the West Coast.
   Majors Field is a two-runway municipal airport used primarily by
E-Systems Inc., a defense electronics contractor. Only one runway,
6,800 feet long, is in use.
   The former World War II Army Air Corps training field routinely
handles planes as big as 747s, which E-Systems modifies for military
and other specialized uses.
</TEXT>
