<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Jamming     03-14 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Jamming,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Liberty Says There Was No Soviet Jamming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Free Europe said Tuesday its
engineers found no indication the Kremlin had resumed jamming it or
its sister station Radio Liberty to block reports on demonstrations
in the Soviet Union.
   Soviet dissidents said Monday that Radio Liberty broadcasts had
been jammed.
   Radio Liberty, a sister station of the U.S.-financed Radio Free
Europe, broadcasts to the Soviet Union, while Radio Free Europe
beams to the Baltic states and the rest of Eastern Europe. The two
stations, based in Munich, have combined management.
   Radio Free Europe spokesman Bob Redlich said there was no jamming.
   ``We have no indication of any jamming,'' Redlich said from the
station's headquarters in Munich.
   ``Our engineers checked this very closely and they could not find
any jamming anywhere. There is no jamming,'' he said.
   Redlich said an effect similar to jamming could have been caused
by increased solar activity in recent days that can hamper radio
reception.
   He said Radio Free Europe-Radio Liberty monitors noticed no
incidents of jamming over the weeked.
   Dissidents in Moscow said Radio Liberty's broadcasts were jammed
to block its reports on anti-government demonstrations and
detentions in Moscow, Leningrad and two other Soviet cities.
   The Soviet Union stopped interfering with the broadcasts of Radio
Liberty and several other foreign radio stations, including West
Germany's Deutsche Welle and the Voice of Israel, on Nov. 29, 1988.
</TEXT>
