<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FurnitureFires     03-14 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Furniture Fires,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union, Trade Group Agree to Support Calif. Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A firefighters' union and a furniture
manaufacturers' trade association said Tuesday they have agreed to
support California's strict proposed public furniture fire
resistance test for adoption in all states.
   Adoption of the test could raise the manufacturing cost of sofas
and chairs by 20 percent but save thousands of lives by the end of
the 1990s, said the International Association of Fire Fighters and
the American Furniture Manufacturers Assocation.
   The standard would apply only to furniture used in public areas,
such as hotel lobbies, day care centers, jails and the like, and not
in hotel rooms or private homes.
   ``We had to crawl before we could walk. We want to see the effect
of this,'' said Alfred K. Whitehead, president of the union, in
explaining why the two organizations were limiting the coverage of
their proposal.
   The California standard has been proposed by that state's Bureau
of Home Furnishings but is not in effect there yet. However, some
California cities have adopted it locally.
   The test calls for placing five sheets of newspaper in a
specified open steel box on the seat of the item being tested,
igniting the paper and monitoring the test chamber to see that
temperature rise, smoke density, carbon monoxide concentration and
weight loss from the test item do not exceed specified levels for an
hour and a half.
   The aim is to delay the onset of ``flashover,'' the sudden
ignition of the entire room and the combustible gases it contains
given off by the burning item.
   Furniture passing the test ``will, at a minimum, slow the spread
of fire in these occupancies allowing firefighters to save more of
the occupants from death or injury,'' Whitehead said.
   The test is ``many times more stringent'' than current industry
standards for resistance to cigarette ignition, which accounts for
75 percent to 80 percent of furniture-related fires, said Les Flippo
of the association's Upholstered Furniture Action Council.
   ``No furniture meets it today,'' except for costly, specially
made items, said Flippo, whose association members account for 80
percent of the industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Lance     03-14 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lance,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lance Responds To FDIC Lawsuit, Says He Is Political Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former federal budget director Bert Lance, who
resigned amid controversy over his banking practices, says he is the
victim of an illegal and politically motivated campaign by the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   Lance filed his response Monday to a lawsuit filed against him
last month by the FDIC in federal court in Rome. The FDIC lawsuit
seeks $1.5 million which the agency contends Lance owes to a defunct
Tennessee bank.
   Lance charged that the FDIC, in the late 1970s, ``commenced a
policy of selectively `leaking' to the news media information about
(his) personal financial situation.'' Such information ``was
confidential and its release by the FDIC was contrary to law,'' he
said in his response.
   He asked that the lawsuit be dismissed or taken to a jury trial,
and that the FDIC be forced to pay his legal fees.
   The FDIC lawsuit, filed Feb. 8, contended Lance and his former
holding company owed the money because of renewal agreements for
loans made with United American Bank of Knoxville, Tenn.
   The Tennessee banking commissioner assumed control of United
American Bank six years ago, and the FDIC later took over various
UAB loans, including the Lance loans.
   The lawsuit listed four notes with principal balances totaling
$1,247,667 and said Lance also owed interest.
   Lance responded that he is under no obligation to pay the FDIC
anything because he had already repaid the loans. He also said the
FDIC failed to deal with him in good faith and said the renewal
agreements were forced on him by the FDIC.
   Lance, once a Calhoun banker and Georgia's transportation
commissioner, became federal budget director after fellow Georgian
Jimmy Carter was elected president in 1976. Lance resigned in
September 1977 after his banking practices were questioned.
   Three years ago, Lance agreed to pay a fine of $50,000 and not
work at any federally insured bank in a settlement resulting from
charges of bank fraud filed by the federal Office of the Comptroller
of the Currency.
</TEXT>
