<FIRST>r a AM-BellevueKilling     03-14 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bellevue Killing,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband of Slain Doctor Sues City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The husband of a pregnant doctor who was slain at
Bellevue Hospital is suing the city for $25 million for negligence
in treating the mental illness of the alleged killer, an attorney
said Tuesday.
   Dr. Kathryn Hinnant-Johnson, 33, who was five months pregnant
with the couple's first child, was beaten, raped and strangled in
her fourth-floor office at Bellevue on Jan. 7.
   The alleged killer was Steven Smith, 23, a homeless man who
apparently set up a hideaway in a closet and roamed the hospital
wearing a doctor's scrub suit and lab coat and carrying a
stethoscope.
   The victim's husband, Eric A. Johnson, charged the city with
medical negligence in the treatment of Smith and negligent security
at Bellevue, said Johnson's lawyer, Thomas A. Moore.
   Moore said Smith was ``negligently and carelessly discharged''
from Bellevue after a Dec. 18-27 stay and ``not properly treated for
an acute and chronic psychiatric condition.''
   Johnson also charged the city and its Health and Hospitals Corp.
with negligent security for allowing Smith, who was arrested Jan. 1
for posing as a physician, to live in the closet and walk through
the hospital.
   Moore on Monday filed a notice of claim with the city, the first
step in a lawsuit. Suzanne Halpin, a spokewoman for Health and
Hospitals, said the agencvy would not comment on litigation.
