<FIRST>r w AM-Aircraft-Blind     03-14 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aircraft-Blind,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Hears Dispute Over Seating Blind Filers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the blind clashed with federal
regulators and aviation industry officials Tuesday over whether it's
safe to allow blind people to sit next to emergency exit doors on
airplanes.
   In a crash involving a fire it is essential to get an evacuation
started immediately and any delay can be fatal, said Anthony J.
Broderick, associate administrator of the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   Thus, the FAA has prepared rules that would ban seating any
disabled individual next to emergency exits, Broderick told the
aviation subcommittee of the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee. The regulation would also apply to
pregnant women, small children and others such as frail elderly who
might have difficulties with the emergency exit door.
   During an evacuation ``anything which slows the opening of doors
or impedes the start of passengers getting off the plane increases
the likelihood of fatalities,'' Broderick said.
   But Kenneth Jernigan, executive director of the National
Federation for the Blind, contested Broderick's contention that
blind passengers would slow down the flow of people exiting from a
plane.
   ``The truth is that we are being made victims of a misdirected
and misapplied federal policy that has irrationally gone wild,''
said Jernigan.
   In cases where a cabin was filled with smoke or the lights had
failed, a blind person could be more effective than a sighted one at
getting a door open and helping people leave, Jernigan said.
   ``As far as I have been able to determine, there is not a case on
record in which a blind person has been involved in the blocking of
an exit or the slowing of traffic in an emergency,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, airlines discriminate against the blind, he said,
and the proposed regulation would just make that worse.
   Dan Frye, a blind student, told the subcommittee of a case in
which a flight was canceled because he declined to move from a seat
in the row leading to an emergency door, and said he was threatened
with arrest and publicly humiliated.
   Since there is no way to accurately determine what disabilities
any individual may have, Frye suggested that airlines simply remove
the seats from aisles leading to emergency exits.
   On the other side, however, was the Association of Flight
Attendants.
   Association president Susan Bianchi-Sand said in prepared
testimony that the proposed rules are long overdue.
   Emergency doors do not operate the same as normal doors, the
instructions are often written on them, and opening the door without
being able to check outside could allow a fire to enter the cabin,
she warned.
   In addition, people exiting a plane need to be able to determine
whether the emergency slide has been properly deployed and if there
is water or land or even spilled fuel below.
   In addition, she pointed out that pulling the wrong handle can
detach the emergency chute rather than deploying it.
   Restrictions on who can sit next to the emergency exit need to
apply to anyone why may not be able to lead an evacuation, whether
blind or someone returning from a skiing vacation on crutches, she
said.
   James E. Landry, senior vice president of the Air Transport
Association, also agreed with the proposed FAA rules.
   ``While it may be true that certain blind persons will react
better than certain sighted persons in an emergency situation in a
darkened cabin interior, there is no test by which these qualities
could be discerned by airline employees,'' he said in prepared
remarks.
   That being the case, he said, ``a reasonable, precautionary rule,
applied on a class basis to protect the public safety, is prudent
and sensible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
