<FIRST>r w AM-GreatLakes-Pollution     03-14 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Lakes-Pollution,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Group Says Birth Defects Among Birds Have Increased</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Birth defects among birds in the Great Lakes
region have increased over the past two decades, according to
research released Tuesday by the Sierra Club.
   The environmental organization said researchers found toxic
chemicals causing the defects are in the food chain.
   A 1986-88 survey of water bird eggs in the upper Great Lakes
region found deformities in Caspian terns occurring 31 times more
frequently than in the late 1960s and early 1970s, said James P.
Ludwig, a consulting ecologist from Bay City, Mich.
   Among deformities found in Ludwig's research were malformed hips,
club feet, eye abnormalities and body organs attached outside the
birds at birth.
   Even low levels of contamination produced effects in the Great
Lakes food chain, Ludwig said.
   ``In a broad sense, these chemicals are eliminating the diversity
in the Great Lakes,'' Ludwig said. ``We have a few species, but the
elegance is gone.''
   His research included birds nesting in highly contaminated areas,
such as Saginaw Bay in eastern Michigan.
   Many contaminants are blown into the lakes from many hundreds of
miles away, an ecologist said in describing research last year on
Isle Royal, Mich., an island in Lake Superior.
   Deborah Swackhammer, an ecologist with the University of
Minnesota, studied fish in Siskiwit Lake on the island and found
concentrations of the toxic chemical polychlorinated biphenyl.
   The PCB could only have reached the lake from the air, since the
lake's level is above that of the surrounding Lake Superior, she
said.
   ``Not only is every fish in the Great Lakes contaminated by
chemicals to some extent, but anything that consumes those fish is
also contaminated to some extent,'' including people, she said.
   The research was released as part of the annual Great Lakes
lobbying project in Washington by the Sierra Club.
   At a news conference, the organization, to demonstrate the
effects of pollution, showed a live cormorant with a twisted beak.
The bird, which was found on Naubinway Island, Mich., in northern
Lake Michigan, may eventually be placed in a Bay City petting zoo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
