<FIRST>u w PM-NorthTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 03-14 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>McFarlane Lashes Out at Prosecutor</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 11th-25 grafs, In testimony, with 13 grafs of testimony
from today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former national security adviser Robert
McFarlane testified today that a letter he sent Congress about
Contra support ``probably would have come out differently'' had it
not been written the day before he tried to commit suicide.
   McFarlane responded angrily to John Keker, a prosecutor at Oliver
North's Iran-Contra trial, when questioned today about the Feb. 8,
1987, letter to then-House Intelligence Committee Chairman Lee
Hamilton.
   Keker said the letter is ``just complete nonsense, isn't it?''
   McFarlane cited his ``state of mind the day before I tried to
take my life'' and said the letter ``probably would have come out
differently'' if he had ``tried to parse every last dime.''
   The letter said a foreign national offered to contribute money to
the Contras in a May 1984 meeting with McFarlane and that the amount
donated was $5 million or less. In fact, the offer came from the
government of Saudi Arabia through its ambassador, and the country
donated $32 million to the Contras starting in 1984.
   The letter said the money ``was from his (the foreign national's)
own wealth and not from any government.''
   When Keker pointed out that that statement was false, McFarlane
responded: ``That is a gloss, but that is what he (the Saudi
ambassador) told me.''
   ``In my own state of mind, I was acknowledging my participation
in a third-country donation. I knew darn well it was something about
a million dollars a month ... if I had toted up the full amount,''
McFarlane said. He added that ``I am dead wrong'' in the letter
about the amount.
   The letter by McFarlane followed his testimony to the House
Intelligence Committee in December 1986 in which he said he was
unfamiliar with any Saudi contribution.
   His 1986 testimony was one of four misdemeanors to which
McFarlane pleaded guilty to withholding information from Congress in
the Iran-Contra affair.
   McFarlane testified about the events of November 1986, when
details of the Iran initiative were emerging and the diversion of
funds to the Contras was discovered.
   At the request of then-national security adviser John Poindexter,
McFarlane on the night of Nov. 18, 1986, went to North's office,
where the national security council aide reported that government
lawyers ``believed there might be a problem'' with a November 1985
shipment of 18 Hawk antiaircraft missiles from Israel to Iran.
   The possible problem concerned ``whether or not the involvement
of the CIA was appropriate ... or properly executed,'' he said. The
CIA had helped arrange the shipment.
   McFarlane testified that North told him that ``he and I hadn't
learned of this shipment until later on ... he wasn't certain about
it'' and that at the time U.S. officials believed the material being
shipped was oil drilling equipment.
   McFarlane said that ``by 1986 I had no clear recollection'' of
when he had learned of the shipment, which he had been told about in
November 1985 in Geneva. McFarlane had informed President Reagan and
Secretary of State George Shultz of the plans for the Hawk shipment.
   Acting on North's comments, McFarlane changed the chronology by
taking out a reference to the 1985 shipment being Hawk missiles,
replacing it with a general mention of other transfers of
unspecified equipment. McFarlane said the change succeeded as an
effort ``not to contradict the truth,'' which he said he wasn't
certain of at the time.
   One of the accusations against North is that he obstructed
Congress by saying in the final version of the chronology that no
one in the U.S. government learned before January 1986 that Hawk
missiles had been shipped to Iran in November 1985.
   The former national security adviser also testified that he went
into a meeting at Poindexter's office as it was breaking up the next
morning and that someone made the comment that there was no problem
in connection with the Iran initiative.
   ``Just popping off, I said, `I believe you have a problem with
the use of Iran money' for the Contras,'' recalled McFarlane, who
had been told of the diversion by North the previous May. Poindexter
and North returned minutes later and admonished McFarlane that one
of the participants in the meeting was unaware of the diversion, he
testified.
   McFarlane also testified that on a car ride to the White House on
Nov. 21, North said ``we're going to have a shredding party ... to
relieve any fears I had'' about becoming involved in a political
brouhaha with Congress over the Iran initiative.
   McFarlane agreed with Keker that North was referring to
``probably hundreds'' of documents, including memos to McFarlane
spelling out North's involvement in the Contra aid efforts during a
congressional ban on military aid to the guerrillas.
   ``I said, `don't worry about anything','' McFarlane recalled.
``Tell it like it is and everything will be okay.''
   On cross-examination, McFarlane agreed with North lawyer Brendan
Sullivan that North was the hardest-working person he had ever
encountered and that ``you would want him in your life raft.''
McFarlane got two six-month extensions from the Marine Corps for
North to remain at the National Security Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
