<DOCNO> AP890314-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 5thLd-Writethru a0539 03-14 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0539,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronauts Ordered to Conserve Power Because of Hydrogen Tank Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with NASA official optimistic
about solving problem, lights also dimmed; PICKS UP 9th graf pvs, `Today's
relatively ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A puzzling pressure reading on a
hydrogen tank forced Discovery's astronauts to dim lights and turn
off computers and other systems to conserve power today and raised
the possibility of an early return to Earth.
   Mission Control emphasized the trouble posed no threat to the
five-man crew or its mission but could cut the flight from five to
four days.
   The crew members went about their scientific experiments as usual
after the ``powering-down,'' taking pictures of environmentally
damaged areas of the Earth such as the rain forests of Brazil and
the Mexican coastline.
   The order came three hours after the crewmen were awakened by the
raucous shouts of James Brown's ``I Got You (I Feel Good).''
   Flight director Ron Dittmore said the hydrogen tank exhibited
erratic readings.
   The tank is one of three that feeds liquid hydrogen to
Discovery's power-producing fuel cells. Without it, the shuttle
might not have electrical energy to support a five-day flight plus
two days for any contingencies.
   Flight firector Al Pennington said he was optimistic the problem
would be solved. ``Right now we plan to land on Saturday, unless we
get some engineering data that says we can't use that tank,''
Pennington said at a news conference.
   If the tank can't be fixed, the shuttle probably will come home
early, he said. Pennington said a decision would have to be made by
early Thursday.
   Even if the flight were cut short, he said, the astronauts would
achieve most experiment objectives.
   Pierre Thuot, capsule communicator in the control center, told
Discovery commander Mike Coats to turn off some lights and other
systems to assure the crew could complete a four-day mission and
still have capacity to spend two extra days in orbit in case bad
weather or some other problem made it impossible to land on the
fourth day.
   Among the systems shut down were computers deemed unnecessary and
two data display screens. The shuttle has numerous backup computers.
   Today's relatively light schedule contrasted with the fire and
thunder of Monday's liftoff and the release of the $100 million
satellite, the mission's primary task.
   Mission Control in Houston wakened the astronauts with the
recording by the ``Godfather of Soul,'' who is serving six-year
sentence in a South Carolina prison for charges stemming from a
two-state auto chase.
   ``We're trying to figure out how you got James Brown out on
parole to sing that to us,'' quipped Discovery commander Mike Coats.
   ``That was just a special appearance,'' replied capsule
communicator David Low in the control center. ``We thought that was
very appropriate music. You've got the whole ground team here
feeling real good.''
   The deployment of the 2{-ton Tracking and Data Relay Satellite
completes a network that will enable NASA and the Defense Department
to maintain almost constant radio contact with space shuttles and
more than a score of unmanned satellites.
   During the mission's remaining days, the astronauts were to
observe four crippled rats; explore the causes of space sickness;
conduct tracking tests that could have applications to the ``Star
Wars'' program; research treatment of diseases, and film damaged
areas on Earth.
   The astronauts rode Discovery into orbit Monday on the 28th
shuttle flight and the third since the Challenger explosion killed
seven astronauts more than three years ago.
   Before the deployment of tracking satellites, NASA depended on
ground stations and their huge dish antennae around the globe.
Shuttle astronauts could speak to Mission Control only as they flew
over the ground stations, a link that covered only about 15 percent
of each mission.
   NASA will soon close six ground stations at a monthly savings of
$3 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
