<HEAD>NYU Dean Announces for New York City Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herb London, a syndicated columnist and dean of
an interdisciplinary studies department at New York University, on
Tuesday announced his candidacy for the Republican mayoral
nomination.
   London, a little-known conservative, faces Ronald Lauder, a
cosmetics fortune heir and former U.S. ambassador to Austria.
Rudolph W. Giuliani, a former federal prosecutor, is expected to
enter the race.
   ``We will win by focusing on unique solutions to New York's
chronic problems while Mr. Lauder campaigns against Mr. Giuliani's
`liberalism' and Mr. Giuliani campaigns against Mr. Lauder's
money,'' London said.
   London said he favored privatization of city-run housing and the
prompt auction of property taken by the city for back taxes. He also
favors the death penalty for police- and drug-related killings.
   London, 50, is dean of NYU's 1,000-student Gallatin Division,
which he founded in 1972, and a senior fellow at the Hudson
Institute, a conservative think tank.
   In the Democratic race, Mayor Edward I. Koch is expected to face
Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, Comptroller Harrison J.
Goldin and real estate developer Richard Ravitch.
   The primary is set for September and the general election for
November.
