<FIRST>u a PM-IndianActivist     03-14 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Activist,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Indian Activist Should Go Back to North Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAMPSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today denied asylum in New York
to a fugitive Indian activist and ordered him sent back to North
Carolina to face kidnapping charges in a 1988 armed takeover of a
newspaper office.
   Lawyers for Timothy Jacobs filed an appeal even before the ruling
was issued, meaning he will remain in New York while the legal
battle continues.
   Defense attorney Lewis Pitts had argued that Jacobs' life was in
danger in North Carolina because of his knowledge of corruption
there.
   But Madison County Judge William O'Brien II told Jacobs: ``You've
spent the entire time here with the same information about drug
trafficking and there has been no evidence of any harm to you or any
threats to you.''
   The judge revoked Jacobs' $25,000 bail, and the 20-year-old
Tuscarora Indian was taken away to jail.
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Martin has asked New York to return
Jacobs so he can be tried in the takeover of The Robesonian
newspaper in Lumberton, N.C.
   Jacobs and fellow Tuscarora Eddie Hatcher, 31, both of Pembroke,
N.C., used shotguns to hold 20 people hostage for 10 hours before
surrendering. Hatcher and Jacobs said they were trying to publicize
allegations of corruption.
   The siege ended when Martin agreed to investigate their charges
that county officials were involved in drug dealing and murder. A
task force found no evidence to support the claims, which Martin
later said were based on ``rumor and gossip.''
   A federal jury acquitted Jacobs and Hatcher of hostage-taking
charges in October, but they were indicted by a Robeson County grand
jury in December.
   Jacobs fled North Carolina befoe he could be arrested and tried
to take refuge at the Onondaga Indian reservation near Syracuse.
   Hatcher had fled to Idaho but was arrested Friday by the FBI
after attempting to seek refuge at the Soviet consulate in San
Francisco.
</TEXT>
