<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1411EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SharkSuit     03-14 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shark Suit,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shark-Bitten Surfer Sues County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shark-bitten surfer is suing Dade County for
negligence, arguing that while lifeguards post signs for jellyfish
and dangerous undertows, they fail to advise bathers of possible
shark attacks.
   ``This isn't your typical run-of-the-mill shark attack,''
attorney Scott Silverman told jurors as the trial began Monday.
``Metro-Dade County, for two to three weeks before the attack, had
been having problems with sharks'' at Haulover Beach.
   Jonathan Popper, 22, was bitten May 21, 1983, as he surfed. The
shark grabbed his foot and let go, ripping a nerve and severing
tendons in his right foot. He wants the county to pay him for $5,000
in medical bills, lost time at work and an unspecified amount for
pain and suffering.
   Popper would never have entered the water if he knew sharks were
present, Silverman said.
   ``Sure they had signs for undertow, it's dangerous,'' Silverman
said. ``Sure they had signs for man-of-war, it's dangerous. They
didn't have signs for shark attacks.''
   But Assistant County Attorney Ron Bernstein said Popper, a surfer
since age 13, was well aware of shark dangers. And he said that
while sharks had been reported in the area on previous days, none
was spotted May 21.
   ``This case involved an attack by a wild animal in the Atlantic
Ocean,'' Bernstein said. Popper ``understood that sharks lived in
the area. He knew that from surfing.''
</TEXT>
