<FIRST>u a AM-Brites     03-14 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is illegal in this state to use Drano
without a permit or trot across a toll bridge on the back of a horse.
   But thanks to the state Legislature, Nevadans may win back these
rights _ as well as the sanction to graze cattle within three miles
of the post office.
   ``We asked research to find laws on which there was no
controversy and which were antiquated,'' said Assemblywoman Gaylyn
Spriggs.
   The Assembly voted Monday to repeal the laws, and the Senate is
expected to follow suit.
   Some of the provisions date to 1865.
   A 1911 statute prohibits ``riding or driving any animal or
animals upon a toll bridge faster than a walk.''
   There are no toll roads on private land in Nevada to which the
law would apply, Mrs. Spriggs said.
   Another law set for repeal is a 1901 statute forbidding sheep
herders from grazing their flocks ``within 3-mile radius of post
office of town whose population is 50 or more.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one can insult Oakland County Sheriff
John F. Nichols by calling him a ``pig.'' His office is a shrine to
the animal.
   His collection of more than 300 porcine replicas includes a
60-pound concrete pig and a litter of piglets on his desk.
   ``Some people who walk in on me get so occupied with the display
they forget what they came in for,'' Nichols said.
   Nichols, 70, began his collection as deputy superintendent of the
Detroit Police Department in the 1960s, when anti-Vietnam War
protesters first coined ``pigs'' as a derogatory term for the police.
   ``The term never offended me,'' Nichols said. A visitor to police
headquarters in Detroit gave him his first pig _ a cast-iron replica
he now uses as a paperweight.
   ``Before I knew it, other pigs were brought in and the collection
started.''
</TEXT>
