<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Raffles 1stLd-Writethru a0631 03-14 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Raffles, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0631,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landmark Singapore Hotel Closes For Renovation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to ADD word ``British.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raffles Hotel, a stately but tattered monument
to the grandeur of British colonial days, closed Tuesday for
renovation to help it compete with the city's skyscraper lodgings.
   ``This is a trip down nostalgia lane for me,'' said frequent
visitor Mike Gallagher of Darwin, Australia, as he sat beneath
whirring ceiling fans and sipped a Singapore Sling in the Long Bar,
where the gin-based drink was invented 74 years ago.
   Down the hall, padlocks barred last-day visitors from the
Elizabethan Grill and the Writers' Bar, where literary figures drew
inspiration.
   Somerset Maugham, said to have written ``The Moon and Sixpence''
in his suite overlooking the graceful Palm Court, said Raffles
``stands for all the fables of the exotic east.''
   Joseph Conrad supposedly was inspired to write ``Lord Jim'' while
sitting on Raffles' veranda and reading a newspaper story about a
British crew who abandoned their ship and left 200 passengers to die.
   Rudyard Kipling advised: ``Feed at Raffles when visiting
Singapore'' but sleep elsewhere because the beds were uncomfortable.
   Today's Raffles also is surpassed in comfort by the modern
hotels; it needs a coat of paint, and the plastic cushions in the
cramped lobby could do with replacing.
   But up until Raffles closed its doors at midnight, hundreds of
the curious and nostalgic thronged to the hotel.
   Some danced to Frisco Soliano and his quartet. Others chatted and
drank under the stars in the Palm Court or in the Long Bar, where a
squad of bartenders worked non-stop concocting Slings and pouring
Tiger Beer.
   Raffles will reopen in 1991 after $78 million is spent to
modernize the building, restore the grand original entrance and
build an extension in keeping with the French Renaissance style and
three-story height of the main building.
   ``It will be very faithfully restored as a national monument ...
as a grand hotel,'' said Richard Helfer, an American who is
executive director of the new Raffles property management firm.
   He has been general manager of the two Westin hotels across Bras
Basah Road from Raffles, both skyscrapers like the other new hotels
in this thriving island republic.
   But Helfer said the new Raffles will not be a giant like many
others. Instead, it will have about 110 suites _ fewer than the
present 127 rooms _ at a luxury level of ``six stars if you call
five stars the best.''
   Visitors, he said, will be drawn to a cultural center to be part
of the new extension.
   Raffles is named after Sir Stamford Raffles, who founded the
British colony of Singapore in 1819.
   The hotel dates to the early 1800s when it was founded as a
``tiffin house,'' or restaurant in a private home. But the existing
hotel was started in 1886 by three Armenian brothers.
   Under the British empire, the hotel was a social center for
colonial officials, mariners, planters and merchants.
   But modern, business-minded Singapore seemed to give Raffles
little thought. It was dwarfed by new hotels, and there were fears
it would be razed, as has happened to much of old Singapore.
   Some old monuments have been saved, and the government-controlled
land corporation that holds the Raffles property resisted the
temptation to put up another skyscraper on the valuable land.
   Still, the restoration is a sad event for the staff and those who
run shops in the ground-floor arcade.
   Mohamed Shariff, money-changer and proprietor of a notions shop,
said he and his father before him had made a good living in Raffles
for 45 years.
   ``It's very sad to go,'' he said, adding that he had no hope of
returning in the new hotel. ``There's a new generation coming in.''
   Roberto Pregarz, the general manager who is leaving along with
about 200 jobless staff members, said: ``There's nothing to
celebrate tonight.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
