<FIRST>r a AM-CougarRelease     03-14 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cougar Release,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Officials Bring Two New Texas Cougars To Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two caged Texas cougars were positioned
Tuesday for eventual release in North Florida as game officials try
to revitalize the state's experiment on expanding the range of the
endangered Florida panther.
   The cats were moved onto private land near the Osceola National
Forest and will be allowed to venture out of the cages on their own
in the next week to 10 days, said Lt. Dewey Weaver of the game
commission's Lake City office.
   In southern Florida, a native panther that has recovered from
injuries suffered when hit by a car last November near Fort Myers
was scheduled to be released Wednesday in Corkscrew Swamp in
northern Collier County. The panther was treated at the University
of Florida's veterinary hospital in Gainesville.
   Fewer than 30 of the Florida cats are believed left in the wild,
in the Everglades in southern Florida. They once ranged across the
state.
   The two Texas cougars, close relatives of the panther and the
Western mountain lion, will be set free under a ``soft release''
technique that allows them to adjust to their new environment before
their cages are opened.
   ``They leave on their own whenever they are ready to leave,''
said Weaver. ``It depends on the cats, how they settle down and get
acclimated to that area.''
   Both the western cougars are adults, one male and one female.
   The cougars, sterilized and fitted with radio-tracking collars,
are being used to test the area for compatibility for Florida
panthers.
   Cougars and panthers have many of the same living habits. If the
cougars can survive in North Florida, game officials might try to
relocate some Florida panthers to the area.
   The habitat expansion program suffered major blows in recent
months with the deaths of three of five cougars released in North
Florida last June. A $7,000 reward is out for information regarding
the deaths of two Texas cats that died under suspicious
circumstances.
   Loss of habitat caused by increasing human population and
development has been the primary reason for the panther's demise.
</TEXT>
