<SECOND>AM-BRF--Canyon Deaths,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Scheduled In Grand Canyon Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND CANYON VILLAGE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A review board will
investigate accidents in which two tourists fell to their deaths in
the Grand Canyon in six days, National Park Service officials say.
   A Japanese woman died Sunday when she slipped from a rock on the
South Rim and fell over a 300-foot cliff. The previous week, a West
German woman fell, apparently after fainting at Mohave Point.
   Park Service spokesman Chuck Lundy noted Monday that both
accidents happened in areas with no guardrails. The service tries to
discourage visitors from entering such areas.
   However, he said: ``We feel we have adequate guardrails on the
North and South rims. At some point, it becomes a matter of personal
responsibility. We don't want to restrict access with guardrails all
over the rims.''
   He said all tour companies and the government warn tourists of
dangers at the canyon. The Japanese woman fell only minutes after
the guide for her group mentioned the German woman's death, Lundy
said.
