<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BibleBreakout     03-14 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bible Breakout,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Follow The Good Book And Make Exodus From Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inmates who discovered that the Bible
could set them free escaped from the Dorchester County Jail by using
the good book as a good jimmy.
   ``Well, the Bible is the key of all keys,'' Sheriff Philip
McKelvey said Tuesday. ``It unlocks a lot of doors, including jail
doors, evidently.''
   Kenneth Sylvester McRae, 27, was awaiting trial for a convenience
store robbery and Donald Tyrone Gross, 21, was awaiting trial on
charges of breaking and entering a home.
   They were in a temporary facility used to ease overcrowding at
the county's 106-year-old jail. They jimmied a lock on a
malfunctioning fire escape door Saturday night and were caught
Sunday in this city on Maryland's eastern shore, officials said.
   ``The Bible cover is pliable and yet strong enough to jimmy the
lock. The locking mechanism itself wasn't working properly and it
should not have been able to be jimmied like that,'' McKelvey said.
   The two were charged with escape from confinement. If convicted,
they could be sentenced to 10 years.
