<FIRST>r w AM-WeaponsCost     03-14 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weapons Cost,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cost Estimates for Major Weapons Programs Soaring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The estimated cost of the Pentagon's 94 biggest
weapon programs skyrocketed by $57.5 billion last year, primarily
because the services want to buy more of certain weapons in the
mid-1990s, a new report indicates.
   However, President Bush told Congress in February he would cut
back the military build-up plans of former President Reagan. So the
statistics in the latest Selected Acquisition Report released
Tuesday ``have already been overtaken by events,'' said Jim Turner,
a Pentagon spokesman.
   The update is based on the budget and policy guidelines of the
Reagan administration because Congress mandates the review be
conducted every Dec. 31, Turner said.
   Nonetheless, the report outlines the priorities of the services
and the budget items over which Bush, Congress and the military are
likely to clash.
   As of Dec. 31, the Pentagon said the 94 key programs that Reagan
was pursuing carried a combined pricetag of $818.6 billion, up $57.5
billion or 7.6 percent from a quarterly estimate last Sept. 30.
   Of the increase, $42.7 billion was attributed to changes in
purchasing plans for the middle and late 1990s. And of the $42.7
billion, more than 40 percent stemmed from changes to just three
Navy programs _ big jumps in orders for the DDG-51 destroyer and the
SSN-21 Seawolf submarine, plus an increase in orders for Trident II
missile submarines and missiles.
   Other programs that had won the blessing of the outgoing Reagan
administration for purchase increases in the ``out years'' included
the Army's M-1A1 tank, AH-64 attack helicopter and UH-60 Blackhawk
transport helicopter; the Marine Corps' air-cushioned landing craft,
and the Air Force's Titan IV rocket booster for unmanned satellite
launches.
   Pentagon officials declined comment Tuesday on how those and
other purchasing plans might change.
   The Selected Acquisition Report is a review of all major weapons
programs and is designed to provide a broad gauge of how well the
Pentagon is doing in managing its weapons buying.
   The reports do not reflect any change in a program unless there
are major schedule delays or an increase of at least 5 percent in
the cost. The reports do not disclose when the last year of buying
for each weapon is scheduled.
   In the December report, most of the programs showing cost
increases were cited because of changes in the size of the order as
opposed to management problems. Of the $57.5 billion increase, $2.9
billion was attributed to scheduling problems or changes and $6.9
billion to revised contract estimates, compared to the $42.7 billion
attributed to quantity changes.
   The report shows the Navy planned to increase by 10 the number of
DDG-51 destroyers it purchased _ to a new total of 33 _ as well as
increase from five to 12 the number of SSN-21 Seawolf submarines it
purchased.
   Both of the those ship types are now in development and have yet
to enter the fleet.
   The Navy also planned to increase from 11 to 13 the number of
huge Trident II nuclear submarines it purchased.
   The Air Force planned to buy 34 more Titan IV rocket boosters on
top of the 23 originally approved, and the Army planned to buy 1,460
additional M-1A1 tanks, increasing its total buy to 9,317.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Baker     03-14 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emergency $100 Million to Be Sought to Deal with Flow of Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration will ask Congress for
an emergency $100 million to help deal with a higher-than-expected
flow of refugees this year, particularly Soviet Jews, Secretary of
State James A. Baker III said Tuesday.
   Baker disclosed the request in answer to a question from Rep.
David Obey, D-Wis., at a sometimes-contentious budget hearing before
the House Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee, which Obey
heads.
   Obey noted that the administration was asking for a cut in
refugee spending for the fiscal year opening Oct. 1, despite
increased flows of refugees around the world. ``How on earth are we
going to deal with this problem?'' he asked Baker.
   Baker said a review of refugee programs was under way at the
State Department and would be completed soon after May 1. For the
current year, he said, the administration is preparing a request for
an additional $100 million ``because we can't make it'' to the end
of the year on current appropriations of $412 million.
   The request surprised Obey, who would have to act on any
supplemental money bill for refugees. Baker seemed surprised that
Obey did not know about it, saying he was supposed to have been
notified by the Office of Management and Budget several days ago.
   An OMB spokesman said a supplemental funding package including a
long list of other requests was still being prepared for submission
to Congress.
   The Soviet Union has been permitting Jews to leave the country at
a high rate in recent months, and the State Department said last
week that more than 5,000 are in various stages of processing to
come to the United States. Obey noted that money to pay for
resettlement aid would run out in the next three months.
   Baker said a supplemental money request also would be sent to
Congress to extend U.S. aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, who are
encamped in Honduras along the Nicaraguan border. Current
``humanitarian'' aid authority runs out at the end of the month,
although supplies are considered adequate to maintain the rebels at
least through April.
   But he termed ``not accurate'' reports that the request would
total $40 million to $50 million, the amount that would be needed to
last the rebels into early 1990, when Nicaraguan national elections
are scheduled.
   Baker said the effort to maintain the anti-Sandinista Contras in
place was not inconsistent with a call by the five Central American
presidents last month to draw up a plan to disband the 10,000-man
force.
   It represents ``a genuine view that they do represent somewhat of
an incentive for the Sandinista government to keep the promises they
haven't kept in the past,'' including steps toward democratization
and civil liberties, he said.
   Baker and Obey clashed repeatedly over Obey's announced intention
to scale back President Bush's $14.6 billion foreign aid request to
$13.2 billion. Obey said he was skipping ahead of the normal
negotiation process to arrive at the foreign aid figure, which he
said was the necessary result of Bush's refusal to seek new tax
revenues.
   ``Absent new revenues, this is all you're going to get,'' he told
Baker. ``I have read his (Bush's) lips.''
   ``If you really believe these things are important ... this is
not the way to approach the problem,'' Baker responded, charging
that the Obey budget would ignore the ``very real national security
and foreign affairs needs of this country.''
   Obey replied that Democrats are not about to try to dissuade Bush
from his ``no new taxes'' campaign pledge, but will make him face up
to the consequences of not having new revenues, ``because then we
can get rid of these silly, phony promises.''
   He said Congress would never consent to exempt foreign aid
programs from budget cuts while giving an inflationary increase to
the Pentagon and slashing domestic programs such as health and
education.
</TEXT>
