<FIRST>r i AM-Romania     03-14 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diplomat Arrested After Disclosure of Letter Critical of Ceausescu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian media reported Tuesday that a
senior Romanian diplomat had been charged with espionage, and emigre
sources linked the case to a letter by veteran communists demanding
improved human rights.
   An announcement from the Romanian General Prosecutor's office
carried in Romanian dailies and on the state news agency Agerpres
said Mircea Raceanu had been ``engaged in steady treasonable
action'' since 1974 when he allegedly was recruited to spy for an
unidentified country.
   Raceanu served in Washington during the 1970s and most recently
was deputy head of the Foreign Ministry's U.S. desk in Bucharest. He
was arrested in January.
   The General Prosecutor's office did not mention a letter that
five Communists and Raceanu's father had signed, condemning economic
and political policies of President Nicolae Ceausescu.
   The letter, written in January, first reached the West over the
weekend and was prominently reported on Western radio stations
broadcasting to Romania.
   It also was reported by official media in Yugoslavia and Hungary,
indicating Romania's growing isolation from its Communist allies.
   The letter marked the first time senior communists have banded
together to protest Ceausescu's policies.
   It attacked Romania's isolation in Europe and Ceausescu's plans
to destroy up to 7,000 of the country's 13,000 villages in a
resettlement campaign.
   ``How are you going to improve Romania's external relations when
all the leaders of the non-communist nations of Europe refuse to
meet with you?'' the letter said according to a text made available
to The Associated Press.
   It demanded an immediate halt to food exports from the
shortage-plagued agricultural nation.
   The letter also condemned a late 1970s decree that forbids
Romanians to speak to foreigners, and denounced alleged systematic
violations of private mail and telephone communications.
   It was signed by Raceanu's father, Ion, former Politburo members
Gheorghe Apostol and Alexandru Birladeanu, former Foreign Minister
Corneliu Manescu and party veteran Constantin Pirvelscu.
   Silviu Brucan, a former ambassador to the United States, was the
sixth signatory. Repeated calls in the past three days to Brucan's
Bucharest home have gone unanswered.
   Radio Bucharest played what it said were taped interviews from
workers' meetings in several Bucharest plants. It did not explain
how such gatherings could be organized just hours after the first
publication of the charges against Raceanu.
   ``I was stupefied after reading the communique in our press. Our
Socialist justice must deal exemplary punishment to such traitors,''
a worker from the Grivita Rosie chemical equipment plant in
Bucharest was heard saying.
   ``Foreign circles, envious of Romania's achievements, are trying
to torpedo its achievements,'' another said.
   Emigre sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said Raceanu
and his wife were detained Jan. 31 en route to the U.S.
amabassador's residence for a film showing, but that she later was
released.
   A Western diplomat in Bucharest confirmed by telephone that
Raceanu was invited to the movie, but did not show up. Raceanu later
was said to have been transferred from his Foreign Ministry post,
said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The maximum penalty for treason is death, if the espionage is
deemed to cause grave damage to state security. The next most severe
penalty is 20 years in jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
