<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Gimpel     03-14 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Gimpel,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Renowned Pianist Jakob Gimpel Dead at 82</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jakob Gimpel, a pianist whose career began at
age 8 in his grandfather's theater in Austria and brought him renown
in the concert halls of America and Europe, has died. He was 82.
   Gimpel died Sunday at his home in Westwood, said his son, Peter.
   The pianist, who had retired a few years ago as distinguished
professor in residence at California State University, Northridge,
had suffered from arthritis and circulatory problems, his son said.
   He performed his last recital in 1987, at the University of
California, Los Angeles, despite great shoulder pain, Peter Gimple
said. He added that his father ``continued to play very bravely''
through years of arthritic pain.
   As a professor he told his students, ``Performing artists must
have tenacity, endurance and courage.''
   The child of musical parents, Gimpel became proficient on the
piano at an early age, recalling years later that by his eighth
birthday he was performing at a theater his grandfather owned.
   ``I had my union card,'' he said. ``I played in a cabaret. Of a
childhood, I had absolutely none. But all these experiences made me
a better musician.''
   He made his concert debut in 1923, and in 1938 moved from his
native Vienna to the United States with his wife, Mimi.
   In Los Angeles, Gimpel played with the MGM orchestra, but labored
primarily in obscurity until 1949, when he was invited to
participate in the New York segment of the Chopin centennial.
Reviews were favorable.
   He returned to Europe to perform concerts in 1954.
   West Germany awarded him the Order of Merit, First Class for his
``great service as an interpreter of German Music'' and in
recognition of his role in the resumption of German-American
cultural relations following World War II.
   He was the brother of the late violinist Bronislaw Gimpel, a
former concertmaster of the Los Angeles Philharmonic.
   He is survived by his wife and son. A funeral was held Monday.
</TEXT>
