<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>US May Increase Aid to Cambodian Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is weighing the
possibility of an increase in assistance to non-communist resistance
forces in Cambodia, U.S. officials said Tuesday.
   That issue was discussed Monday with Prince Norodom Ranariddh, a
leader of a rebel group headed by his father, former Cambodian head
of state Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   At present, the administration plans to provide the resistance
with about $7.5 million in non-lethal aid during the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1.
   Some members of Congress have expressed interest in providing
military aid to the anti-communist rebels but the officials said the
Bush administration is opposed to any change in the existing program.
   Prince Ranariddh, who met with President Bush on Monday, was
meeting with members of Congress on Tuesday.
   The administration's goals in Cambodia include promoting the
withdrawal of Vietnamese forces and the emergence of a democratic
government to replace the Hanoi-dominated regime now in power.
   In addition, the administration opposes any significant role for
the third rebel group operating in Cambodia, the Khmer Rouge. That
group is accused of pursuing policies that led to the deaths of more
than 1 million Cambodians during their 1975-78 rule.
   In Beijing, meanwhile, the two non-communist resistance forces
took a first step Tuesday toward unifying their armies by forming a
defense council headed by Prince Sihanouk.
