<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Zita     03-14 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Zita,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Empress Zita of Austria Dead at 96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZIZERS, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Empress Zita of Austria, the last
queen of the Hapsburg empire who was denounced as a spy for her role
in a plot to end World War I, died Tuesday in this town 20 miles
from the country that shunned her. She was 96.
   Her late husband, Charles I, was the last king of the
multilingual Austrian-Hungarian monarchy who gave up his imperial
rights after the Allied victory in World War I.
   The empress, who never formally abdicated and was barred from
Austrian territory for 64 years, had been ailing for some time, said
Bernd Posselt, a spokesman for the House of Hapsburg.
   Born May 9, 1892, in Pianore Castle, near Viareggio, Italy, the
former Princess of Bourbon-Parma was related to several European
royal families.
   Charles I became Emperor of Austria and King of Hungary after the
death of his uncle, Francis Joseph, who had reigned for 68 years.
   When Charles and Zita were crowned, they believed only a rapid
truce could save the crumbling dual monarchy, then allied with the
Reich of the German Kaiser. Zita, then 24, had a key role in
arranging secret contacts with the Allies in search of a peace
treaty.
   The go-between was her brother, Prince Sixtus of Bourbon-Parma,
then serving in the Belgian army. He was in touch with French
President Raymond Poincare who, in turn, notified King George V of
Britain.
   French Premier Georges Clemenceau, who hated Poincare, revealed
the secret in 1918, creating an international stir and rocking the
German-Austrian alliance. German propaganda whipped up sentiment
against the once-popular Zita, labeling her ``the spy of the
Bourbons.''
   After the Allied victory in 1918, Charles I agreed to
``temporarily relinquish'' his imperial rights. The couple initially
lived in exile in a Lake Geneva chateau, where Charles launched two
attempts to recapture the Hungarian throne.
   After the second bid in 1921, the Allies banished them to the
Portuguese island of Madeira. Charles died there of pneumonia a year
later, at age 34.
   Zita was a 29-year-old widow and mother of eight. Turning down
invitations from royal relatives, she chose to bring up her children
in modest settings in a Spanish fishing village and the Belgian
countryside.
   When Adolf Hitler moved to annex Austria, her oldest son, Otto,
the new head of the House of Hapsburg, urged the Western allies to
intervene, which made the Nazis issue an order for his arrest.
   The family fled to Canada and the United States, living for a
time in Tuxedo Park, N.Y.
   After World War II, Zita toured American cities to promote
humanitarian aid for Austria. In the early 1950s she returned to
Europe, eventually settling at Zizers.
   In 1982, Austria lifted the entry ban following a personal
request by King Juan Carlos of Spain. On her first return to Vienna,
she was cheered by 10,000 people.
   Since 1965, Zita, who once held court at Vienna's
Versailles-sized castle of Schoenbrunn, lived in two small rooms of
a Roman Catholic home for the aged in this village on the Upper
Rhine. She turned down offers for a bigger apartment. Family photos
and an oil portrait of her husband provided a personal touch in her
small living quarters.
   Zita dressed in black from the time her husband died and never
wore jewelry.
   The empress will lie in state in the Austrian capital at St.
Stephen's Cathedral. She will be buried April 1 at the traditional
Hapsburg burial vault in Vienna's Capuchin Church.
   Charles is buried on Madeira. One of Zita's wishes was that his
remains be transferred to Vienna so they could be reunited in death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Derwinski     03-14 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Derwinski,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Derwinski Ready to Move Up to Cabinet with Veterans Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As he prepares to take a seat at the Cabinet
table, Edward J. Derwinski is warning military veterans not to
expect miracles from the new Veterans Affairs Department but
``painful'' budgets in the next few years instead.
   ``I was never one to promise what I couldn't produce,'' the
former Illinois congressman said in an interview. ``I would much
rather under-promise, and have them pleasantly surprised at the end,
than overpromise.''
   Derwinski heads the second-largest agency in the federal
government, the Veterans Administration, which on Wednesday becomes
the 14th Cabinet department. Veterans groups had sought the
upgrading for years, but the election-year endorsement of the idea
by then-President Reagan was needed to bring it about.
   To mark the change, Derwinski will take the oath of office at the
White House and attend a ceremony on the South Lawn.
   ``In the long run, I think we're going to do well,'' Derwinski
said Monday. He said he was talking about ``five, 10 or 15 years.''
   The short run is a different story.
   ``What I tried to tell the American Legion is the mere creation
of a department is not the pot of gold at the end of the rainbow for
us budget-wise,'' he said.
   Derwinski said he was ``assuming that the political facts of life
are that in the short run, neither the president nor the Congress is
going to step out and say, `I want new taxes.'''
   He said he further assumed ``neither the president nor the
Congress is going to step out and say, `Scrap
Gramm-Rudman-Hollings,''' the law requiring declining budget
deficits.
   ``So my personal view is that the law will run its course, the
discipline of it will run its course. That's the next four years. In
those four years there are going to be some painful budget
decisions. My job is to see that the VA does better in the budget
infighting than it would have if I weren't aboard.''
   That is precisely why the veterans organizations and their
congressional supporters fought so long for the department: They
believed the rank of a Cabinet officer would enable them to do
better in the infighting.
   Whether it will happen that way remains to be seen. In a report a
year ago, the National Academy of Public Administration said it did
not believe Cabinet status ``would significantly improve either
access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources or the
organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and
benefits.''
   Though its 240,000 employees are more than any federal agency
except the Defense Department, and its budget is the fifth largest,
the VA is an uncomplicated organization. Derwinski has six months to
reorganize it, but he says any changes ``won't be drastic.''
   There are basically just three parts: medical care, money
benefits and the operation of 111 national cemeteries where 53,000
veterans and members of their families are buried every year
   The first two parts are gigantic. With 172 hospitals, 229
outpatient clinics and scores of other installations, the agency
runs the largest medical care system in the country and one of the
largest in the world, spending $10.8 billion a year and taking care
of 1.4 million hospital patients annually.
   Veterans benefits _ pensions, insurance, mortgage guarantees and
other programs _ account for about $17 billion a year.
   Derwinski has been praised by members of Congress for his open
style and for winning approval in principle from the Office of
Management and Budget for a $300 million supplemental appropriation
for the current fiscal year for VA medical care.
   He said in the interview that the approval was only ``90 percent.
We don't have the official OMB blessing.''
   Some of the agency's medical issues have been front-page issues
for years. For example: post-traumatic stress disorder in Vietnam
veterans and possible health effects of the defoliant Agent Orange.
   Derwinski, though, is looking down the road.
   ``The big problem is one, interestingly, where there is no
debate: aging. The patient's needs start to change. ... It
ultimately means long-term health care rather than dramatic surgical
procedures.''
   It is projected that the number of veterans over 75 will grow
from more than 1.2 million to 4.4 million in the year 2005.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
