<DOCNO> AP890314-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SmokelessTobacco     03-14 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smokeless Tobacco,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warning Labels Required on Promotional Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission must require
health warnings on promotional items such as T-shirts, caps and tote
bags given away by makers of snuff and chewing tobacco, a federal
appeals court ruled Tuesday.
   The commission disregarded the clear instructions of Congress
when it exempted those items from the 1986 requirement of health
warnings in advertising for smokeless tobacco products, said a
three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia.
   The panel's decision upheld a lower court ruling of last year.
   The 1986 legislation at issue exempted only billboards, and
congressional sponsors of the bill submitted statements to the
commission that they fully intended promotional items bearing
product logos to carry the warnings.
   The warning must be one of these:
   _``Warning: This product may cause mouth cancer.''
   _``Warning: This product may cause gum disease and tooth loss.''
   _``Warning: This product is not a safe alternative to
cigarettes.''
   The commission said it feared the phrase ``this product'' would
be taken as referring to the T-shirt or other item, rather than the
tobacco, and thus be ridiculed.
   ``The commission is sensitive to the need to avoid diminishing
the seriousness of the required warnings by mandating their display
in absurd situations,'' the commission said.
   The court's decision, however, said, ``Warnings on these items
would have conceded benefits; the FTC's position is that the
perceived negative effects _ derision, etc. _ would either outweigh
those benefits or render them minimal. This balancing requires a
more explicit congressional grant of authority than is present
here.''
   The commission's case might have merit if the congressional
directive would clearly lead to absurd results, but ``Congress'
rigidity is not a sign of its folly, but rather signals its intent
to act swiftly and deciively to stem the dangerous growth of
smokeless tobacco consumption. Whatever else may be said, Congress
has the general authority to take such rigid measures,'' the court
said.
   Susan Ticknor, a spokeswoman for the commission, said lawyers
there had not seen the decision and could not comment.
   The exemption for promotional items was challenged by the
American Heart, Lung, and Public Health associations, the American
Cancer Society and Public Citizen, and was defended by a trade
association, the Smokeless Tobacco Council, in a friend-of-the-court
brief.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
