<HEAD>Head of Journalists' Group Appeals for Release of Soviet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the International Federation of
Newspaper Publishers appealed Tuesday to Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to release dissident journalist Sergei Grigoryants from
jail.
   Grigoryants, editor and publisher of the unofficial magazine
Glasnost, was detained along with a colleague while taking pictures
of an unauthorized demonstration in Moscow on Sunday, said the
Paris-based federation.
   According to reports from Moscow, the two journalists were
sentenced to 10 days in prison.
   ``This continued harassment of a journalist trying to do his job
is intolerable and makes a mockery of your policy of glasnost,''
federation President Giovanni Giogannini of Italy said in his
message to Gorbachev. ``On behalf of newspaper publishers worldwide
I appeal to you most earnestly to release these journalists
immediately.''
   Grigoryants was named this year's winner of the group's Golden
Pen award for press freedom. He has been regularly arrested for his
publishing activities since being released from prison in 1987.
   He has been invited to the World Congress of Newspaper Publishers
in New Orleans in June to receive his prize.
