<FIRST>u w PM-HijackingTrial 2ndAdd a0689 03-14 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial, 2nd Add, a0689,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: 4 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The jury found Younis guilty of conspiracy to commit sky piracy,
which carries a maximum sentence of five years; seizing hostages,
life imprisonment; and hijacking a commercial airliner, 20 years.
   The jury returned innocent verdicts on charges of using or
threatening violence against passengers or crew members of a
commercial airliner, destroying a civilian aircraft, and carrying
aboard a civilian aircraft devices likely to damage it.
   During two days on the witness stand last week, Younis
acknowledged that he led a band of five heavily armed men aboard
Royal Jordanian Airlines Flight 402 in Beirut on June 11, 1985, and
held its 70 passengers and crew members hostage for 30 hours.
   But Younis testified that he was acting under orders from the
Amal militia, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem group to which he belonged.
He said that although he knew that hijacking was illegal in
peacetime, Amal was engaged in the Lebanese civil war.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. told the jury,
however, that ``orders to hijack a plane ... are illegal orders.
Obedience to illegal orders is no defense.''
   Younis was lured aboard a yacht and arrested in international
waters in the Mediterranean Sea on Sept. 13, 1987 by a team that
included members of the FBI hostage rescue squad, the U.S. military
and intelligence agencies.
