<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Taba     03-14 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Taba,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Workers Demonstrate on Eve of Taba Transfer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   TABA, Israeli-Occupied Egypt (AP) _ Employees of the Sonesta
Hotel saw to it Tuesday that this patch of a tourist resort, an
irritant to Israeli-Egyptian relations for years, would not be
handed over to Cairo without one last fuss.
   They waved signs and Israeli flags and burned tires in a
demonstration to ask what will become of them when the 250-acre
strip of beach becomes part of Egyptian territory on Wednesday.
   ``The hotel is in Egypt, the management is in Israel, and the
employees are in the garbage,'' said a sign carried by one of the
more than 300 workers.
   They staged the protest as Egyptian workers in long galabia robes
put up a border gate and Israeli soldiers in drab olive uniforms
built their barrier nearby.
   Egyptian Tourism Minister Fuad Sultan walked by scores of
protesters and said all was going well.
   ``I'm sure that this will be the cornerstone for a better
normalization process between the two countries,'' he said.
   So far, Taba has had exactly the opposite effect.
   When Israel withdrew from the Sinai Peninsula under a peace
treaty in 1982, it stayed in Taba, which contains little more than
the 12-story hotel and a village of thatched huts.
   Both Israel and Egypt maintained the land was theirs, with their
arguments tracing back to where the border was in 1906 between
British-held Sinai and Turkish-ruled Palestine.
   In September, an international arbitration panel accepted Egypt's
version. On Feb. 26, the nations agreed the land would be handed
over to Egypt on Wednesday.
   On Tuesday, Egyptian and Israeli officials worked out final
details, including arranging passes _ stamped by Egypt, Israel and
the Sonesta Hotel _ to give Israeli workers access to their jobs.
But the employees are worried about an Egyptian law requiring that
90 percent of workers in a hotel be Egyptian.
   ``Tomorrow this is going to be Egypt, and we don't know what's
happening,'' said Erez Efrat, the 30-year-old protest leader. ``They
tell us we don't have a problem, but what about in a month?''
   The workers also are concerned about economics. One carried a
sign saying: ``An Egyptian works for $100 a month, an Israeli for
$1,000. Who do you think will be employed?''
   The hotel has distributed circulars saying the staff and
management will stay the same, although it has been bought by
Egyptians for $37 million.
   Other details being negotiated Tuesday were passes for Israeli
guests and 24-hour access to Taba, a 15-minute drive from the
Israeli resort town of Eilat.
   On Tuesday, Western tourists, Israelis and Egyptian workers
climbed atop a rocky hill overlooking the Red Sea that offers a view
of Egypt, the tip of Israel and Jordan.
   Samer Abdi Shahed, a 23-year-old Cairo native taking a break from
putting up a new flagpole, looked out from the hill. ``Every piece
of the land of Egypt is part of my heart,'' he said.
   A 25-year-old Israeli woman, who identified herself only as Irit,
heard his comment and declared the land should be Israel's because
``all that is here was built by Israelis.''
   Another Israeli, David Biton, 32, said he was reluctant to leave
Taba. He has been living on the beach and his 10-month-old daughter,
named Taba, was born here.
   He said he put up a tent on the hill, but police made him take it
down. So he painted ``Love Taba'' in red paint on the rocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
