<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Earthquake     03-14 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Earthquake,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Blames West German Industry for Mining-Related Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany charged Tuesday that West German
mining activities may have contributed to a severe earthquake that
rocked East German border towns. But it also said its own miners may
be at fault.
   The 12-second temblor Monday afternoon injured seven people and
damaged 200 East German homes along the two Germanys' border, said
East Germany's state news agency, ADN.
   It suggested a blast at Merkers potash mine on the East German
side of the border caused a cave-in and shifting of underground rock
formations that touched off the earthquake.
   But ADN also said West German potash operations just across the
border may have ``created the seismic tension conditions'' that made
the tremor possible by pumping waste water that seeped into East
German mineshafts.
   ADN also said ``faults among mine officials'' on the East German
side, or ``insufficient scientific knowledge'' about previously
unused mining fields ``could not be excluded.''
   The agency said experts believe waste water from the West German
potash operations was the ``main cause'' of a cave-in and shifting
of rock formations that set off the quake.
   West German officials could not be reached to comment on the
charge Tuesday night.
   Both sides of the German frontier were struck by the temblor, but
East Germany apparently bore the brunt.
   Some of the injured were struck by falling chimney bricks, it
said.
   The quake sent children fleeing from their schools and forced
miners to spend two hours underground until the danger was over, ADN
reported. No miners were hurt.
   ``I had the feeling that everything was falling apart'' the
agency quoted Voelkershausen Mayor Herbert Hermann as saying. ``I
watched as cracks formed on my walls and plaster fell from the
ceiling. All I could think of was opening a window and getting out
of there.''
   Voelkershausen, 130 miles southwest of Leipzig and six miles from
the West German border, was hardest-hit of the East German border
communities. The quake knocked out electricity and water services
and badly damaged 80 percent of homes of the 1,350 townspeople, ADN
reported.
   ``Residents were evacuated from 15 homes that are no longer
inhabitable, and were taken in by neighbors and relatives,'' ADN
said.
   The news agency said miners detonated controlled explosions in
the mine at 2:01 p.m. Monday.
   A large mining field caved in when the earthquake began, it said,
but miners were working about 2,000 feet beneath the earth and were
protected by special steel-encased chambers they use during
underground blasting.
   ``Even as the severe tremor was occurring above them, their lives
and health were never in danger,'' ADN reported.
   The miners returned to the surface after about two hours, the
agency said.
   It did not say how many miners were underground at the time or
whether there were any difficulties getting them out.
   West German authorities said the earthquake registered 5.7 on the
Richter scale, while ADN put the magnitude at 5.5. Such a quake can
cause considerable damage.
   Bruce Presgrave of the U.S. Geological Survey in Boulder, Colo.,
said his office received reports the quake may have originated in a
rockburst, which occurs when rocks under pressure suddenly fail.
Such events often happen in mining areas.
   According to the survey's files, the quake was one of the largest
on record in that part of Germany. The largest previous quake
occurred Feb. 22, 1953 and measured 5.4, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Iraq     03-14 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Exchange Accusations of Cease-Fire Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Tuesday it was ready to resume
stalled peace talks with Iraq next month, but the two countries
exchanged accusations of cease-fire violations.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iraqi troops
violated the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire by shelling Iranian positions
in three cities across the southern border starting late Monday
night.
   An Iraqi military spokesman said the Iranians shelled the
positions of an infantry division in the southern port city of
Basra, official Baghdad radio reported.
   The radio said the U.N. observers did not comment on the
incident, but they confirmed an Iraqi complaint had been registered.
   IRNA, which is monitored in Nicosia, quoted a military official
as saying five Iranian soldiers were wounded during the Iraqi
bombardment of the southern cities of Shalamcheh, Abadan and
Khorramshahr.
   IRNA accused the Iraqis of starting the latest border clash and
said the shelling of the port cities of Khorramshahr and Abadan
Tuesday afternoon created panic among personnel of the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group.
   ``Although the Iraqi troops initiated the clash, they contacted
the UNIIMOG eight times appealing for an end to the fire exchange,''
IRNA quoted the military official as saying.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati, meanwhile, proposed
resuming peace talks with Iraq in the third week of April ``to show
our goodwill,'' IRNA reported.
   ``I stress again that at this moment there is nothing more
important than the withdrawal of Iraqi forces from Iranian
territory,'' Velayati said in an interview with the agency.
   ``Until the withdrawal takes place, there will be no progress in
the talks,'' he said.
   The U.N.-sponsored peace talks in the eight-year Persian Gulf war
began five days after a U.N.-mediated cease-fire took effect last
Aug. 20.
   But the talks broke down immediately over the issue of Iraqi
troop withdrawals and the status of the Shatt Al-Arab waterway.
   Three further rounds of talks failed to break the deadlock.
   U.N. special envoy Jan Eliasson held separate meetings in New
York last week with Velayati and Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz,
on resuming talks.
   The two belligerents agreed in January to form a joint military
group to help U.N. observers supervise the cease-fire agreement, but
the group has failed to meet ever since.
   Iran claimed last week that Iraqi forces hold a total of 1,028
square miles of Iranian territory.
   According to United Nations estimates, Iraqi troops still occupy
about 260 square miles of Iranian territory.
   ``I have asked the (U.N.) Secretary-General (Javier Perez de
Cuellar) to deal seriously with this issue,'' Velayati said.
   Velayati insists that as the next step in implementing the U.N.
Security Council peace plan contained in the 1987 resolution, Iraq
should withdraw to the border recognized in a 1975 treaty between
the two neighbors.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein abrogated that treaty in 1980,
just before Iraqi troops pushed across the border after weeks of
clashes between patrolling soldiers.
   Iraq argues that Iran's revolutionary government under Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini disavowed all previous treaties and the 1975
treaty no longer is in effect.
   Iran says it never relinquished the treaty. Under international
law, a treaty is valid unless all parties agree to a change.
   In Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, meanwhile, Islamic foreign ministers met
Tuesday to arrange a swap of prisoners between Iran and Iraq and
discuss ways to revive peace talks between the longtime foes,
sources said.
   The ministers, meeting under the auspices of the 46-member
Organization of Islamic Conference, also planned to discuss postwar
reconstruction projects in the Persian Gulf nations.

</TEXT>
