<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-KittyGenoveseKiller     03-14 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kitty Genovese Killer,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slayer Seeks New Trial in 25-Year-Old Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winston Moseley, convicted of stabbing Kitty
Genovese to death while 38 of her neighbors listened but did nothing
to help her, sought a new trial on the 25th anniversary of the
slaying.
   Moseley, 54, is serving a life term for the March 13, 1964
murder. He maintained in court papers that he did not receive a fair
trial because his lawyer was representing Miss Genovese in another
matter at the time of her death, according to Dick Piperno, a
spokesman for Queens District Attorney John Santucci.
   A hearing on Moseley's motion was scheduled April 6 in state
Supreme Court. Moseley prepared the case himself and filed the
papers in recent weeks, Piperno said.
   The district attorney's reply has not been prepared yet, but it
was expected the motion would be opposed.
   The story of Miss Genovese's murder received wide attention as a
symbol of urban apathy and an indictment of people who play deaf
because they are afraid to get involved.
   The victim, a 28-year-old bar manager, was stalked for half an
hour as she walked home from work. Her screams roused 38 people from
their beds, but no one helped or even called police.
   Moseley, arrested later for a burglary, admitted killing Miss
Genovese and was tried in June 1964.
   He said in his motion that his court-appointed lawyer, Sidney
Sparrow, did not disclose that he had represented Miss Genovese in
an appeal of a bookmaking conviction.
   Moseley said Sparrow's silence about a conflict of interest
warranted a new trial.
   Sparrow, 76 and still practicing law, said he was certain he had
told both Moseley and the trial judge of his prior connection with
the victim. He also said his representation of the woman ended with
her death.
   Moseley was condemned to death but the sentence was changed to 20
years to life on appeal. Three applications for parole since 1984
have been denied.
</TEXT>
