<DOCNO> AP890314-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MIARemains     03-14 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Remains,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Identifies Remains from Vietnam War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army laboratory has identified the remains
of six American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Five of the six were identified by the Army's Central
Identification Laboratory in Honolulu after the remains were
repatriated to the United States by Vietnam last November and
December, the Pentagon said in a statement.
   The remains of the sixth were recovered in December during a
joint excavation at an air crash site in Savannakhet province of
southern Laos, the Pentagon added.
   All six of the servicemen were aviators. The Pentagon said the
family of one had asked that his name not be released and that he be
interred at the Punchbowl National Cemetery in Honolulu.
   The remaining five will be flown on Wednesday from Hickam Air
Force Base, Hawaii, to Travis Air Force Base, Calif., the Pentagon
said.
   It identified those five as:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Cmdr. Gene A. Smith of the Navy, born April 18, 1933, lost over
North Vietnam June 27, 1966. His home of record was listed as Salt
Lake City, Utah.
   _Maj. Sam G. Cordova of the Marine Corps, born Aug. 27, 1943,
lost over Laos Aug. 26, 1972. His home of record was listed as
Huntington Beach, Calif.
   _Lt. Cmdr. Frederick J. Fortner of the Naval Reserve, born May
15, 1943, lost over North Vietnam Oct. 17, 1967. His home of record
was listed as Pomona, Calif.
   _Lt. Cmdr. Michael W. Wallace of the Navy, born Sept. 12, 1936,
lost over Laos March 28, 1968. His home of record was listed as Salt
Lake City.
   _Airman 1st Class James E. Pleiman of the Air Force, born Jan.
15, 1944, lost over North Vietnam March 14, 1966. His home of record
was listed as Russia, Ohio.
   The Pentagon said Wallace's remains were recovered during the
joint excavation in Laos. Fortner's remains were among 23
repatriated by Vietnam on Nov. 3, and the others were among 38
repatriated by the Vietnamese on Dec. 15, 1988.
   The Pentagon added it was not surprised that Cordova's remains
were among a group repatriated by Vietnam even though he was shot
down over Laos.
   ``Maj. Cordova was lost in an area of Laos close to the
Vietnamese border, and in an area controlled by the North Vietnamese
at the time,'' the Pentagon said.
   With the latest identifications, 2,371 Americans continue to be
listed as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of
whom 1,737 are listed as missing in Vietnam, 545 in Laos, 83 in
Cambodia and six in China.
   All told, the remains of 182 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
Army lab since the end of the war. An additional 28 have been
identified after recovery from Laos and two after recovery from
China.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the cooperation of the
Vietnamese and Lao governments that resulted in the accounting for
these Americans and hopes that unilateral turnover of information
and remains along with joint investigative efforts will continue and
increase,'' the Pentagon said in its statement.
</TEXT>
