<FIRST>r a AM-EmergencyLanding     03-14 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Faulty Warning Light Triggers Precautionary Landing In Dallas Suburb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A faulty engine-fire warning light
prompted the pilot of a Delta Air Lines flight carrying 93 people to
make an emergency landing at a municipal airport east of Dallas,
officials said.
   No fire was found on the Boeing 727, and the 86 passengers and
seven crew members were uninjured, Delta spokesmen said.
   Passengers of Flight 423, flying from Atlanta to San Diego,
safely slid down the plane's chutes and were taken by chartered bus
65 miles to Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport to board another
plane.
   The pilot told passengers he was landing at Majors Field in
Greenville, a former World War II Army Air Corps training field.
   ``We came down a little quicker than usual,'' said passenger Gene
Odom of Savannah, Ga. ``It's an inconvenience, but it's better than
being scattered all over a field someplace.''
   Inspectors found an air duct leak in one engine but no sign of
fire, said Gerrie Cook, a Federal Aviation Administration
spokeswoman in Fort Worth.
   Delta spokesman John Clower said two mechanics who happened to be
on the flight diagnosed the problem as a faulty warning light.
   The defense electronics contractor E-Systems Inc. is the primary
user of the airport. Only one runway, more than 8,000 feet long, is
in use and routinely handles planes as large as Boeing 747s, which
E-Systems modifies for military and other specialized uses.
   E-Systems also regularly services the president's Air Force One.
</TEXT>
