<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     03-14 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seoul Begins Maneuvers With US, Accuses North of Stirring Up Anti-Americanism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea began major joint military
maneuvers with the United States on Tuesday and charged that North
Korea was preparing for war.
   A Defense Ministry statement said the communist North was
fomenting anti-Americanism in South Korea to force out U.S. troops
as part of its plot to conquer the country.
   Villagers forced a military range used by U.S. fighter jets to
close for a second day Tuesday as about 200,000 South Korean and
U.S. troops, plus naval and air units, began 10 days of annual
military games codenamed Team Spirit.
   The demonstrators, protesting practice bombing by the jets,
hurled rocks and firebombs onto Koon-ni range, about 70 miles
southwest of Seoul, inflicting minor fire damage on three
guardhouses, a U.S. military spokesman said.
   The Defense Ministry statement rejected the North's charges that
Team Spirit exercises were preparations for a nuclear attack on the
North.
   South Korean defense officials said Tuesday the exercises are
defensive and pose no threat to the North.
   The Pyongyang regime put its armed forces on combat alert and
mobilized reserves, as it has done during previous exercises. It
warned on Monday that the maneuvers could trigger war.
   ``The tension between the North and the South has been screwed up
to the highest pitch, and a dangerous situation has been created on
the Korean peninsula in which a war may break out any moment,'' said
Pyongyang's official Korean Central News Agency.
   The South said, ``The North should immediately stop its
continuous military buildup and war preparations and clearly show
that it is giving up its strategy of communizing the South by
force.''
   South Korean officials said Pyongyang was trying to stir up
anti-American sentiment among some South Koreans to try to force
removal of the 42,000 U.S. troops based here under a mutual defense
treaty.
   ``We are compelled to point out ... the North's scheme to
heighten anti-Americanism and get American troops out and ...
eventually realize revolution to communize the South,'' the Defense
Ministry statement said.
   Some groups in the South, including dissidents, radical students
and farmers, have become increasingly anti-American because of U.S.
trade pressure, and they see the United States as having supported
authoritarian regimes.
   This year's Team Spirit involves about 70,000 American troops,
including the 42,000 stationed here and 27,000 from Hawaii, Okinawa
and the U.S. mainland, according to a U.S. military spokesman in
Seoul.
   Like the other U.S. military spokesman, he spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The North cited Team Spirit earlier as impeding North-South
talks, and those peace talks have been stalled.
   The peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist, pro-Western South Korea at the end of World War II, when
U.S. and Soviet troops ended Japan's colonial rule over the region.
The two Koreas have remained bitter enemies and fought a war from
1950-53.
</TEXT>
