<FIRST>r w AM-MexicanHogBan     03-14 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexican Hog Ban,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Mexico Turning Away Trucks of Live Hogs at Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico is turning away truckloads of live hogs
at the border because the animals have not been vaccinated for a
disease eradicated in the United States, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said
Tuesday.
   The Texas Democrat said the Mexican ban of U.S.-bred hogs was
imposed with litte or no warning, ``has no basis in scientific
fact,'' and may be based on ``mistaken information.''
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said he was
asking U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills and Agriculture
Secretary Clayton Yeutter to negotiate an end to the problem.
Bentsen's office said Mexico began turning away U.S. hogs Friday.
   He said Mexico is barring the hog imports because the animals
have not been vaccinated for hog cholera, which has been eradicated
from the United States for over a decade.
   ``In fact, it is illegal under U.S. law to vaccinate hogs against
hog cholera, and since the hogs in question are market hogs destined
for slaughter, such a vaccination would be moot in any case,'' said
Bentsen.
   Pat El-Hinnaway, a spokeswoman at the Agriculture Department,
said the agency ``just received official notification from Mexico''
about the ban. ``We are in the process of translating it (from
Spanish) and analyzing it.''
</TEXT>
