<FIRST>r a AM-WifeSlaying     03-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wife Slaying,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Matheney Intends To Plead Insanity In Killing Of Ex-Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with beating his former
wife to death while he was free during a brief furlough from prison
intends to plead insanity, his attorney told a judge Tuesday.
   The furlough program was suspended after the killing.
   Alan L. Matheney, 38, stood silently during the hearing in St.
Joseph Superior Court while his court-appointed attorney filed a
series of motions.
   For his protection, Matheney was transferred from the St. Joseph
County Jail, where he was assaulted March 6, to the Indiana State
Prison at Michigan City, said defense attorney Philip R. Skodinski.
The assault is under investigation.
   Judge Jeanne J. Swartz accepted the insanity notice and said she
would appoint two psychiatrists to examine Matheney and determine
his competency to stand trial June 19.
   Matheney's furlough raised a public furor, prompting Gov. Evan
Bayh to suspend the program and to order seven prison officials to
face disciplinary hearings.
   Matheney had been serving an eight-year sentence for beating his
ex-wife, Lisa M. Bianco, and criminally confining her two daughters.
   Ms. Bianco was beaten to death March 4 outside her Mishawaka home
by a man wielding an unloaded shotgun. She died of a massive skull
fracture, a coroner said.
   Prison officials failed to notify Ms. Bianco, 29, of Matheney's
release hours before the assault, despite her requests and
Matheney's continued hostility toward her, according to a Board of
Correction report released Monday.
   Prosecutor Michael P. Barnes said he would decide later this week
whether to seek the death penalty. Matheney also is charged with
burglary.
   At the hearing, Matheney asked the prosecutors for recordings of
telephone conversations between Ms. Bianco and Matheney made before
his imprisonment. Skodinski said he didn't know what information the
tapes contained but said they might help the defense.
   Chief Deputy Prosecutor John D. Krisor said the recordings
apparently were related to the 1987 battery case against Matheney.
Krisor said he did not know if the prosecutor's office had the tapes.
   Ms. Bianco had divorced Matheney in 1985 and last year became a
counselor for battered women at the Elkhart County Women's Shelter.
She also joined the Mishawaka Commission on the Status of Women.
   Hours before the slaying, officials at the Industrial
Correctional Complex at Pendleton gave Matheney an eight-hour
furlough to confer with an attorney in Indianapolis.
   Matheney should have been restricted to the Indianapolis area,
about 40 southwest of Pendleton and 160 miles south of Mishawaka,
but that condition did not appear on his furlough pass, according
the Correction Board report.
   Seven officials from the Department of Correction were ordered to
face disciplinary hearings after the report blamed bureaucratic
ineptitude and poor decision making for Matheney's release.
</TEXT>
