<DOCNO> AP890314-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0607 03-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Economic Hardships Threaten Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with with end of strikes, Solidarity
statement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday that social
tension caused by economic hardship could threaten agreements
reached in negotiations with the political opposition, which began
Feb. 6 and are nearing completion.
   ``The social effects of economic phenomena may be dangerous,''
government spokesman Jerzy Urban said. ``Inflation, difficulties in
acquiring goods and ... regulating incomes by strikes may undermine
the national agreements (and) evoke disturbances and crisis
situations.''
   Urban cited strikes led by ``extremist'' elements that briefly
idled four mines Tuesday in Jastrzebie. Last August, a nationwide
series of strikes that began in the southern city prompted
authorities to propose the talks on political and economic reform.
   Alojzy Pietrzyk of Jastrzebie, a Solidarity negotiator in the
talks, said the latest ``warning strikes'' were prompted by the
refusal of management to pay annual bonuses to workers who struck in
August.
   ``Solidarity has made frequent statements saying strikes are
unfavorable for the country at the moment,'' Pietrzyk said in a
statement. ``At the same time, we state that strikes can be avoided
only by reaching an agreement which would satisfy work forces at
mines and implementing it as soon as possible.''
   Government and opposition negotiators have agreed in principle to
restore legal status to the independent union Solidarity, the
farmers' union Rural Solidarity and the Independent Students'
Association. All were formed in 1980 and outlawed after martial law
was imposed in December 1981.
   Negotiators also have announced agreement on free elections to a
newly created Senate.
   Anger over low wages has led to several strikes in recent months,
but Urban said the frequency of strikes had declined in the past
week.
   Economic problems besetting Poland include annual inflation of at
least 60 percent and a foreign debt of more than $38 billion.
   Most stores are short of goods or stocked with items of poor
quality, so many Poles part with precious hard currency at state-run
dollar shops or make shopping trips abroad.
   ``Poland has to go through a difficult preliminary period in the
upcoming year of the transition stage. The economy will decide about
everything,'' Urban said.
   He said it appeared government estimates that 1989 inflation
would be kept to 20 percent were too optimistic and ``difficult,
revolutionary economic steps'' lie ahead.
   Under discussion at the talks is an opposition proposal on
indexing wages to inflation, which the government has said would
make matters worse.
   Urban said failure of the dialogue ``would be a historic tragedy
for the nation. ... The failure of this experiment would not only
destroy the hopes of Poles, but also Poland's position in the
world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
