<FIRST>r w AM-Barry-Bennett     03-14 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barry-Bennett,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett and Barry Huddle on City's Drug Situation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, head of the national drug
control policy office, met with Mayor Marion Barry Jr. and other
city officials on Tuesday on ways for federal and local authorities
to fight drug-related problems that have contributed to a crime wave
in the nation's capital.
   ``It was a very good meeting,'' Barry said. ``We're just getting
to know each other in this area, and he and I agreed ... there will
be no quick fixes.''
   Bennett has said he would make solving the city's drug problem a
top priority. Thus far this year, 107 people have been slain in the
district, about twice as many as at this time last year. A record
372 people were killed in 1988. Place blame many of the murders on
drugs.
   Barry said he told Bennett that the city needs federal money to
build more jail facilities, expand drug treatment programs and put
more police on the street.
   The mayor maintained that Washington is a safe place to visit.
``There are certain parts of our city where these killings are
taking place, and there is not a `Wild West' here in Washington,''
Barry said. ``Conventioneers can come, tourists can come.''
