<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Ethics     03-14 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Ethics,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Promises Executive Order on Government Ethics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he would issue a new
executive order spelling out ethical standards of conduct expected
of high-ranking government officials.
   Bush said that while he might not accept all of the changes
advocated by a presidential study panel, ``I will be moving quickly
to seek implementation of the great bulk of the commission's
recommendations.''
   After meeting privately with members of the commission headed by
former federal judge Malcolm Wilkey, Bush issued a statement saying
that ``upholding exacting ethical standards throughout the
government is extremely important to me and to all Americans.''
   He reiterated that he also will soon propose legislation.
   The House and Senate last year passed a bill aimed at attacking
the ``revolving-door'' problem in which people leave government
positions and then lobby the agencies where they used to work.
Then-President Reagan vetoed the bill, saying it would discourage
people from going into the service of their country.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
``certainly agrees'' with a commission recommendation that would
treat the executive office of the president as a single agency for
purposes of ethics rules. The aim of this change would be to stop
former White House employees from attempting to use their influence
as lobbyists with separate entities in the executive office complex.
   The standard presidential executive order on ethics has gone
unchanged since it was issued by Lyndon B. Johnson in 1965.
</TEXT>
