<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil     03-14 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Grips Brazil But Millions Report For Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide general strike closed
schools and factories and halted public transportation Tuesday, but
millions of workers ignored union calls and went to their jobs.
Scattered violence was reported.
   The first day of the planned 48-hour strike fell short of the
union leaders' vow to ``stop all economic activity'' in major cities
in this nation of 144 million, Latin America's largest.
   Buses and taxis were stoned in some cities, and there were
reports of looting in Caxias, a suburb of Rio de Janeiro.
   The strike was called to protest a government-decreed wage
freeze. It was organized by Brazil's two largest labor movements _
the leftist Central Workers Union and more centrist General Workers
Central. Those federations say they represent 35 million of the
nation's 60 million workers in about 3,000 unions.
   Jair Meneguelli, president of the Central Workers Union, told a
news conference the strike was a huge success with at least 70
percent of the country's total work force staying off the job.
   But Carlos Henrique de Almeida Santos, President Jose Sarney's
press spokesman told reporters in Brasilia, ``The strike failed to
live up to the expectations of its organizers because it was not a
nationwide movement. There were isolated stoppages in many urban
centers but in no way could it be considered a general strike.
Everything indicates that tomorrow the strikes should fizzle out.''
   Tens of millions of commuters were stranded as many trains, buses
and subways stopped running.
   Army troops were posted outside the main station of Rio de
Janeiro's government-run commuter railroad which did not operate.
Rio has a population of 5 million and the trains normally carry
about one million passengers daily.
   Rio's subway system and the ferry service across Guanabara Bay
also were shut down.
   But the subway trains ran in Sao Paulo, South America's largest
city with 10 million people.
   Carlos Alberto Ferreira da Silva, a leader of the Sao Paulo
subway union, said the union was not adequately prepared for a
strike. He said 300 of the union's 9,000 workers attended a meeting
to respond to the strike call and they voted only to distribute a
letter expressing support of the strike.
   Airlines flew normal schedules and most supermarkets, gas
stations, shops and restaurants were open.
   The Federation of Industries of Sao Paulo State said more than 70
percent of the state's 2 million factory workers showed up at their
jobs.
   Several factories were reported shut down in the industrial
suburbs of Sao Paulo city _ the site of Brazil's foreign-owned auto
plants and union strongholds.
   Banks operated normally in most of the country but with reduced
personnel and fewer clients than usual, according to the National
Association of Banks.
   Many universities and public and private schools closed.
   Sao Paulo state security chief Luis Antonio Fleury Filho said
rock-throwing strikers damaged 95 buses and 30 people were arrested.
Buses also were stoned in Rio.
   Police used clubs to disperse crowds suspected of looting stores
in Caxias just outsice Rio and several people were detained. A
photographer of the Jornal do Brasil newspaper who was taking
pictures of the clashes was shot in the hand by a policeman,
according to the Jornal do Brasil radio station.
   In Belo Horizonte, the capital Minas Gerais state, police used
rubber truncheons and tear gas against groups of pro-strike
demonstrators and there also were street fights in Vitoria, capital
of Espirito Santo state. Brazil has 26 states.
   The strike is to protest the wage freeze that is part of the
government's ``Summer Plan'' announced in January to curb inflation
that was running at an annual rate of about 1,000 per cent. The plan
includes a price freeze.
   The plan brought inflation down from 28.7 per cent in December to
3.6 per cent for the first 11 days of February, according to the
latest government figures.
   Jair Meneguelli, president of the Central Workers Union, said the
wage freeze cut workers' purchasing power by up to 49 percent ``and
we want it back.''
   More than half of Brazilian workers earn less than $50 a week.
</TEXT>
