<FIRST>r w AM-ContraAid     03-14 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Aid,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conflicting Signals on Contra Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration sent conflicting
signals Tuesday about the amount of non-military aid it will seek to
keep the Nicaraguan Contra rebels afloat until a peace agreement is
carried out.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said a total of $40
million to $50 million, quoted in news stories this week, is ``in
the ballpark'' of what President Bush wants to follow after the
current $27 million package expires March 31.
   But on Capitol Hill, Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
that figure is ``not an accurate number as far as I'm concerned.''
   Baker commented on the Contras at a budget hearing before the
House Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee.
   Later, Fitzwater later said he agreed with Baker, and that his
comment about the numbers being in the ballpark merely reflected
that ``It's a big ballpark,'' encompassing all figures.
   Fitzwater said no final decision has been made on Bush's proposal
``and we are not setting artificial timetables for decisions.''
   Baker and Fitzwater agreed a money request will be sent to
Congress for non-lethal assistance to the Contra forces. That are
about 11,000 Contras in camps on the Honduras side of the border
with leftist-ruled Nicaragua.
   Rebel leader Adolfo Calero said administration officials told him
the aid request would be in the neighborhood of $40 million, which
would be intended to see the rebels into early 1990, when Nicaraguan
national elections are to occur.
   Fitzwater reiterated the administration's intent for a diplomatic
solution, and said Bush's plan would include ``the ideas of
incentives and disincentives that might go with that.''
   ``In this approach we are also pursuing the building of a
bipartisan support for whatever policy emerges,'' he said, in
highlighting the administration's wish to work out some kind of aid
package that can make it through the Democratic-controlled Congress.
Contra aid has been a highly contentious issue for six years.
   Fitzwater also acknowledged that a key factor will be the
cooperation of Honduras in allowing the Contras to keep their camps.
   He noted that Undersecretary of State Robert Kimmitt visited
Honduran President Jose Azcona on Monday to discuss the situation
and U.S. policy.
   A delegation of Honduran officials, breaking a ban on talks with
the Contras, met with Calero and a group of rebel leaders in
Washington on Monday.
   Afterward, the Hondurans were uncustomarily conciliatory in
comments about the Contras, declining to repeat previous Honduran
demands that the rebels be expelled from Honduran territory.
   Baker said the effort to maintain the anti-Sandinista Contras in
place represents ``a genuine view that they do represent somewhat of
an incentive for the Sandinista government to keep the promises they
haven't kept in the past,'' including steps toward democratization
and civil liberties, he said.
   The five Central American presidents agreed last month in El
Salvador to construct a plan by this spring for the disbanding of
the rebels in exchange for democratic reforms in Nicaragua.
   Administration officials have said their concern is to keep the
Contras in place until it can be assured the Sandinistas will keep
their pledges regarding democracy moves.
   U.S. officials have said Bush is prepared to ease the U.S. trade
embargo against Nicaragua and take a number of other conciliatory
measures if the Sandinistas show they are serious about holding fair
elections next year.
   Under such circumstances, the administration also would be
prepared to upgrade diplomatic relations with Nicaragua, including
the exchange of ambassadors, the officials said.
   The administration has prepared a list of about 20 incentives for
Nicaragua, as well as a potential list of punitive measures of
similar length if Nicaraguan opposition forces are not given what
U.S. officials perceive to be an equal chance in the balloting.
</TEXT>
