<DOCNO> AP890314-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseFraud     03-14 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Fraud,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singer Charged With Defense Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Singer Company and a former subsidiary were
accused by the government Tuesday in a $231 million lawsuit of
fraudulently inflating the price of military aircraft flight
simulators.
   The suit filed by the Justice Department charged that Singer Co.
and Link Flight Simulation Corp., fabricated higher cost estimates
to offset price concessions they might be forced to make during
contract negotiations with the Defense Department.
   The action was taken in a False Claims Act lawsuit originally
filed under seal last fall in U.S. District Court in Baltimore by
Christopher Urda, a former Link Flight price administrator.
   The amended complaint filed by the Justice Department supersedes
the original suit filed by Urda and Taxpayers Against Fraud.
   Under the Civil War-era False Claims Act, private citizens may
sue on behalf of the government if they suspect fraud. The
government is empowered to take over the case if it determines that
the original claims have merit.
   Justice Department spokeswoman Amy Brown said the $231 million
claimed by the government made the case one of the largest suits
brought under the False Claims Act.
   Urda's complaint, which was ordered unsealed by U.S. District
Judge Herbert Murray at the government's request, had accused Singer
of arbitrarily adding a 10 percent labor charge onto original
estimates for the flight simulators over a 15-year period.
   But the government's amended complaint only alleged price fraud
on seven contracts between 1983 and 1986 on flight simulators and
related projects. Link Flight had received a sole-source fixed-price
contract to produce the million-dollar devices for the Pentagon.
   The simulators are used by the military to train pilots to fly
Cobra, Apache, Blackhawk, Chinook helicopters, F-4 and F-16 fighters
and B-52 bombers.
   The government's complaint charged that it added the phony
charges to ``cost estimates which it believed were least likely to
be questioned by the government or which it believed the government
had the least ability to evaluate.''
   The government claimed that it lost $77 million as a result of
the alleged fraud and sought treble damages under the law, plus
civil penalties of $5,000 to $10,000 for each false claim submitted
to the Pentagon.
   The phony bid information was approved by the company's bid
committee, which usually was comprised of the president of Link
Flight and various operating units of the company, the lawsuit said.
   Singer was acquired in 1987 by corporate raider Paul Bilzerian's
Singer Acquisition Co. Last year, Link Flight, based in Binghamton,
N.Y., was sold to CAF Industries, a Canadian company which renamed
it CAE Link Corp.
   Company officials at Singer's corporate headquarters in Stamford,
Conn., said Phil Watson, Singer's general counsel, had left for the
day and was unavailable to make a comment on the lawsuit.
   Bilzerian's secretary in Tampa, Fla., said he was also
unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SatanicVerses     03-14 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writers Urge United Nations to Protect Rushdie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Moslems, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kurt Vonnegut and other U.S. writers on
Tuesday urged the Security Council to protect Salman Rushdie from a
death sentence issued by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini for alleged
blasphemy in his book, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   But it appeared highly unlikely the council would champion
Rushdie's cause and antagonize Iran, which has agreed to
U.N.-mediated peace talks in its war with Iraq.
   PEN, the association of poets, essayists and novelists; the
National Writers Union, the Authors Guild, the human rights group
ARTICLE 19, and other authors' groups presented petitions to
Britain, Canada and other members of the 15-nation council Tuesday
and asked them to take up the case as an issue of free speech.
   The petition, signed by more than 1,500 writers worldwide,
urgently requests the council to intervene in the Rushdie affair for
humanitarian reasons.
   A delegation of authors met British and Canadian envoys Tuesday
and planned to meet with French, Finnish, Colombian, U.S. and
Yugoslavian representatives. They also sought meetings with all
other members of the most powerful U.N. body.
   So far, only Malaysia, a largely Moslem nation, has declined a
meeting, the authors said. But council members Algeria and Senegal,
also Moslem, were expected to decline.
   British Mission Spokesman J. Stephen Smith told reporters later
that Britain initially had considered taking the matter to the
council but ultimately concluded it was preferable to take action
through diplomatic channels.
   Western diplomats added that with three Moslem members, the
council could not possibly agree on a statement or action strong
enough to satisfy many Western nations.
   Council members also think the Rushdie issue is primarily a
religious, not a political case, and is not the appropriate topic
for council consideration, Western diplomats said.
   The council already has declined to take up the Rushdie case
because the body does not want to offend Iran and jeopardize the
delicate U.N.-mediated Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   But the authors and human rights activists, who began a 36-hour
vigil across the street from here, said their intention was to
publicize the issue.
   The council includes five permanent members with veto power: The
United States, Britain, China, France and the Soviet Union, and 10
other members: Algeria, Brazil, Canada, Colombia, Denmark, Ethiopia,
Malaysia, Nepal, Senegal, Yugoslavia.
   Last month Khomeini ordered Moslems to murder Rushdie on grounds
his book insulted Islam. Rushdie, an Indian-born British citizen, is
in hiding.
   The British government defended Rushdie and the Tehran government
broke its recently restored diplomatic relations with London.
   The delegation and demonstrators included Vonnegut, Philip
Caputo, William Styron, Alix Kates Shulman, Nat Hentoff, Victor
Navasky, National Writers Union President Alec Dubro, publisher Rick
MacArthur of ARTICLE 19, exiled South African poet Dennis Brutus,
and Chilean author Ariel Dorfman.
   In Stirling, Scotland, British Commonwealth Secretary-General Sir
Shridath Ramphal said writers condemning the death threat against
Rushdie had spoken for the rest of the world.
   He said the call for Rushdie's murder had ``understandably and
rightly'' produced a wave of adverse reaction throughout the
Commonwealth, the 48-member organization of Britain and its former
colonies.
   ``The world's writers have more than given a lead in this matter:
I believe they have spoken for the world community in its
collectivity,'' Ramphal told an audience at Stirling University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
