<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     03-14 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Resistance Forms Defense Council Led by Sihanouk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's three resistance movements moved toward
a unified fighting force Tuesday by forming a defense council led by
Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former ruler turned rebel leader.
   A joint statement from him and the other leaders, who often have
been at odds, also announced a ``common political program''
envisioning ``Western democracy'' and free enterprise after a
Vietnamese withdrawal from Cambodia. Vietnam invaded in December
1978.
   Amnesty International urged Cambodia's Vietnam-backed government
to furnish information about hundreds of political prisoners it says
were not freed under an amnesty proclaimed last May. A statement
issued in Paris said Amnesty has names of more than 400, including
some arrested 10 years ago, who have not been charged or tried.
   Sihanouk said all rebel forces ``now are practically under my
command.'' The prince, who lives in Beijing part of the year, serves
as president of the Cambodian government-in-exile formed by the
three movements.
   He announced plans for the High Council for National Defense
together with his partners in the resistance government, communist
Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan and Son Sann, who heads a smaller,
non-communist party.
   They have met privately in the Chinese capital since Sunday to
discuss Cambodia's future in light of a Chinese-Soviet summit
planned for May and the Vietnamese rejection of Sihanouk's peace
proposals.
   The prince said he was confident China will not drop its support
of the Cambodian resistance to reach agreement with the Soviets on a
speedy Vietnamese withdrawal. Moscow is Vietnam's main ally.
   ``I am 100 percent sure (China) will continue to support my plan
and support us,'' Sihanouk said. A Vietnamese withdrawal that leaves
the Hanoi-sponsored government of Hun Sen to confront the resistance
``a la Afghanistan'' is not acceptable, he declared.
   Soviet troops finished withdrawing from Afghanistan on Feb. 15,
after nine years of involvement in the communist government's war
with Moslem guerrillas.
   Sihanouk predicted President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet
Union and Deng Xiaoping, the senior Chinese leader, will agree at
the summit to exert pressure on behalf of the prince's plan.
   It calls for U.N. supervision of a Vietnamese withdrawal and free
elections under a provisional government of all parties.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw by September if a political
agreement is reached, but promised to leave in 1990 in any case.
   A major obstacle to Sihanouk's plan is the refusal of Vietnam and
Hun Sen to accept U.N. supervision and Khmer Rouge participation in
a future government.
   The United States, which helps the resistance, also has been wary
of a return to power by the Khmer Rouge, which gained control in
1975 under the leadership of Pol Pot. At least 1 million people had
died in a reign of terror by the time Vietnam invaded.
   Pol Pot is said to have retired, and Sihanouk said Khieu Samphan
had agreed the former leader would remain out of the picture.
   ``If they break their promise, my army will fight them
indefinitely,'' the prince said, turning to Khieu Samphan. The Khmer
Rouge leader, smiling broadly, said his party would ``accept
realities'' in order to end the occupation.
   Much of the conflict within the alliance has arisen because of
the Khmer Rouge. Sihanouk has accused its forces of repeated attacks
on his army, but told the news conference Tuesday no attacks had
occurred in several months.
   He said one of the defense council's duties would be to resolve
such conflicts. The joint statement said the council would ensure
``solidarity, cooperation and mutual respect and assistance'' among
the three armies.
</TEXT>
