<FIRST>u i AM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru a0733 03-14 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Killed in Ambush, Officers Reprimanded Over 1982 Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with IRA claim of responsibility,
details</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish Republican Army gunmen
killed a part-time member of the security forces Tuesday at the
meat-packing plant where he worked.
   Police said they arrested six men immediately after the murder
and were questioning them.
   Thomas Hardy, 48, who had a wife and two sons, was shot at
Granville Meat in Dungannon, County Tyrone, a police spokesman said
on condition of anonymity. Hardy was a part-time member of the
Ulster Defense Regiment, the locally recruited wing of the army.
   The outlawed IRA claimed responsibility in a statement to the
British Broadcasting Corp. in Belfast. It has made security forces a
target in its 20-year-old campaign to drive Britain from
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the Irish
Republic, which is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   Police said they found a car abandoned about 500 yards from the
plant and there was a two-car accident 1{ miles farther on. Three
people were arrested at the accident scene and three others near the
shooting scene, police said.
   On Tuesday night, police reported two more violent incidents:
   _A bomb exploded and shots were fired as a police vehicle passed
Andersonstown Road in mainly Catholic west Belfast. The car was not
damaged but two girls who were passing suffered from shock and were
taken to a hospital.
   _In Cookstown, County Tyrone, a bomb exploded in a hedge about 50
yards from a car police were told had a supicious device inside.
Officers were evacuating the area when the bomb went off and no one
was injured.
   In another development, authorities said 18 policemen were
reprimanded over allegations that the Northern Ireland force
illegally shot six unarmed Catholics to death in 1982.
   Another was cautioned, and charges were dismissed against a 20th
man, said a statement from the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the
provincial police force.
   Five of the dead were acknowledged IRA guerrillas but the sixth
was a teen-ager not involved in the sectarian conflict.
   The affair has been a sore point with Catholics, and Britain's
decision to hold a disciplinary inquiry and not prosecute angered
the Irish government in Dublin.
   All six victims were Catholics, killed in three incidents over a
three-week period. Allegations arose that a shoot-to-kill policy was
in effect, but the police denied it.
   Allegations of a coverup were revived in 1986 when John Stalker,
a police officer from England sent over to investigate the killings,
was forced off the case. He claimed that happened because he was
close to proving a murder conspiracy.
   Two senior officers were suspended and have since resigned on
health grounds.
   The 20 officers were not identified, but nearly all were
sergeants or constables, the British domestic news agency Press
Association reported. It said they were accused of breaches of
discipline ``of a relatively minor nature.''
</TEXT>
