<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     03-14 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Stroessner Aide Brought to Court on Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Justice Minister Jose Eugenio
Jacquet, an aide to ousted president Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, was
brought to court Tuesday on corruption charges.
   In another development, opposition leader Domingo Laino said the
Electoral Board was hindering efforts to register voters, and he
questioned the integrity of national elections set for May 1 to
replace Stroessner.
   A criminal lawsuit charges five Stroessner Cabinet members and
seven members of his government or the ruling Colorado Party with
``crimes against public administration'' including embezzlement,
bribery and fraud.
   Stroessner flew to exile in neighboring Brazil following the Feb.
3 coup led by Gen. Andres Rodriguez. Former Interior Minister Sabino
Montanaro was given conditional asylum in Honduras, but he may be
called back to face charges.
   A police report accused Jacquet of selling licenses to notaries
and court clerks for $4,000 each, and an audit of the Labor and
Justice Ministry turned up 157 ``planilleros,'' or ``payrollers'' _
people who showed up only to cash their checks each month.
   Jacquet also pressured judges to rule on cases according to his
instructions, ``which resulted in important economic gains,'' the
police report, conducted after the coup, alleged.
   Jacquet's attorney Ramon Alberto Aquino said the charges were
vague. He did not say how his client pleaded, if at all. The
defendants were called to court for formal notification of the
charges against them, and to answer questions from the judge. They
were not obliged to respond to the charges.
   Among the Cabinet members, former Education Minister Carlos Ortiz
Ramirez was accused of creating ``ghost'' employees on his agency's
payrolls and pocketing their salaries when their checks went
uncollected.
   Laino, meanwhie, said the 9-member Electoral Board had provided
only about five voter registration books for every 100 he requested.
His Authentic Radical Liberal Party, the largest opposition group,
has not yet decided whether to contest or boycott the elections.
   ``The facts we have now give us the right to doubt just how clean
and transparent the elections they want us to participate in will
be,'' Laino told a news conference.
   The government reopened registration lists for an additional
month on March 1. The Electoral Board, dominated by members of the
ruling Colorado Party, argues that some 80 percent of all eligible
voters are already registered.
   Laino said the figures used by the board are bloated from
electoral fraud on the part of the Stroessner government. He added
that independent analysts place the number of unregistered, eligible
voters in Paraguay at 35 percent.
   ``In elections last year, according to official figures by the
Electoral Board, the number of votes surpassed the number of
registered voters in 39 districts,'' Laino said. ``Even the dead and
ghosts voted.''
   Gen. Rodriguez is the presidential candidate of the Colorado
Party, which has been in power since 1947 and is widely expected to
retain control of the presidency and congress.
</TEXT>
