<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-14 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Wind Blows Dust Over West Plains, Snow Hits Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wind blowing up to 120 mph blasted the western Plains and stirred
up blinding dust storms Tuesday, while heavy, blowing snow closed
schools and halted travel on the northern Plains.
   Snow fell from Utah, Colorado and Wyoming to northern and central
Nebraska, South Dakota, southeastern North Dakota, central
Minnesota, northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan. Schools were
closed in sections of Wisconsin, Minnesota and South Dakota.
   Wind hammered eastern Colorado early in the day. Gusts up to 120
mph northwest of Loveland knocked down trees and utiltiy poles,
wiped out a section of bleachers at Bandimere Speedway and closed
eastern Plains roads with blowing dirt.
   A dozen ski lifts in Colorado's Summit County were shut down for
a time by the wind. On Monday, 220 skiers had to be evacuated from a
chairlift at Aspen Mountain resort when a gust knocked the lift
cable off its track.
   In Loveland, the wind shoved a truck across U.S. 287 and knocked
it onto its side and toppled utility poles near the Rocky Flats
nuclear weapons plant. Trees were knocked down in western Denver.
   Winds gusted to 53 mph at Pueblo, Colo., 66 mph at Hill City,
Kan., and 86 mph west of Albin, Wyo.
   In western Kansas, visibility was reduced to about one city block
in Garden City and Hill City. State authorities reported numerous
traffic accidents, and many roads, including sections of Interstate
70, were closed.
   ``The whole county is in the air, so to speak,'' said a secretary
at the Thomas County sheriff's office in Colby. She said all roads
in and out of Colby were closed.
   Winter storm warnings for heavy snow and strong wind were posted
for southeastern North Dakota, northeastern and north-central South
Dakota, much of Minnesota, and northern Wisconsin.
   Snowfall since Monday afternoon across Wyoming included 32 inches
at Burgess Junction, 18 inches at Story, 7 inches at Big Horn and 6
inches at Sheridan. Interstate 90 between Sheridan and Buffalo was
closed by snow, the National Weather Service said.
   In South Dakota, there were reports of 8 to 10 inches of new snow
at Deadwood and Galena and a foot at Belle Fourche. North Dakota
snowfall included 9 inches at Wahpeton, 8 inches at Hankinson and 6
at Wisher. Minnesota snowfall included about 10 inches at
Evansville, 6 inches at Fort Ripley and 5 inches at Ortonville.
   Blowing snow cut visibility to zero at times around Aberdeen,
S.D., and snowplows had to be pulled off highways because their
drivers couldn't see.
   The heaviest snow in Wisconsin was in Douglas County in the
state's northwestern corner, where many roads were closed by snow
and drifting snow.
   South of the snow belt, rain fell across northern Iowa, southern
Minnesota, southern and central Wisconsin and into northern Illinois.
   Elsewhere, rain was scattered along the northern Pacific Coast.
   In the South, Midland, Texas, warmed to a record 87 degrees for
the date and Atlanta tied its record of 80.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 14
degrees at Devils Lake, N.D., to 91 at Beeville and McAllen, Texas.
Monday's low for the Lower 48 states was 11 degrees above zero at
Great Falls, Mont.
   For Wednesday, rain was forecast from New England and northern
New Jersey to New York, much of Pennsylvania, northern Ohio,
northern Indiana and southern lower Michigan, becoming snow and
reaching across northeastern Illinois, the rest of Michigan,
northern Wisconsin and eastern Minnesota. Snow over Montana was
expected to change to rain, reaching across the northern two thirds
of the Pacific Coast.
   Highs only in the teens were predicted over northeastern Montana;
in the 20s from the remainder of northern Montana across North
Dakota, northeastern South Dakota, the upper Mississippi Valley,
much of Wisconsin, upper Michigan and northern lower Michigan; in
the 30s and 40s in northern New England, the lower Great Lakes, the
lower Ohio Valley, the middle Mississippi Valley, the central
Plains, southwestern South Dakota, the northern Rockies, the Idaho
Panhandle and eastern Washington; in the 50s and 60s from cental and
southern New England to the upper Ohio Valley, the lower half of the
Appalachians, the Tennessee Valley, northern sections of the central
Gulf Coast states, Arkansas and northern Louisiana, Oklahoma,
northern Texas, the lower half of the Rockies, the Great Basin and
the northern three-fourths of the Pacific Coast; and generally in
the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
