<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     03-14 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Declares Loyalty to Government After Headgear Rumpus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkey's highest-ranking military man
declared the army's loyalty to Turkish democracy on Tuesday after
the opposition expressed fear the military would intervene in a
controversy over Islamic headgear.
   A constitutional court last week declared unconstitutional a
parliamentary ruling that allowed Moslem women to cover their heads
while attending university classes with men.
   Moslem fundamentalists staged protest marches and the government
of Premier Turgut Ozal found itself in an increasingly uncomfortable
situation during campaigning for March 26 local elections.
   Advocates of secularism see the headcover as a political symbol
of those who want Turkey to return to Islamic laws, as Iran has.
   Tolerance for the fundamentalists angered some secular groups,
including Turkey's elite and military leaders.
   On Sunday, Gen. Necip Torumtay,, chief of staff of the armed
forces, paid a surprise visit to President Kenan Evren. Torumtay
later told the Istanbul daily Cumhuriyet, ``We are following the
issue closely.''
   This led Erdal Inonu, leader of the major opposition Social
Democratic Populist Party, to declare: ``We are against a solution
through (military) intervention. We believe we can overcome these
dangers within the democratic system.''
   Turkey's armed forces staged coups in 1960, 1971 and 1980.
   On Tuesday, Torumtay said in a written statement to news media:
   ``The Turkish armed forces ... knows its place and duties within
the constitutional order and is a true believer in and loyal to
parliamentary democracy with all its members.''
   He said he issued the statement because his earlier statements
underwent ``different interpretations in newspapers.''
   Yusuf Ozal, the premier's brother and a Cabinet minister,
criticized the court decision as ``badly timed. ... It was wrong to
take such a decision before elections.''
   Turgut Ozal's governing, conservative Motherland Party is
competing with several center-right parties for the votes of Moslem
fundamentalists, who comprise about 10 percent of the total
electorate of 27 million.
   Ozal's own party is split on the headgear issue, and interference
by Iran complicated matters.
   On Monday, Iranian women students marched through Tehran to
protest the ban on Islamic dress in Turkey's campuses.
   Turkish papers reported that Tehran radio, in Turkish-language
broadcasts beamed to eastern Turkey, urged fundamentalists to rebel
against the secular order.
   Newspaper reports said authorities detained Iranian agents who
were among the protesters in Turkey, but officials did not confirm
these reports.
   Beginning in the 1920s, Turkey adopted Western laws with the
reforms of Kemal Ataturk, founder of the republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AppleBan 1stLd-Writethru a0701 03-14 0768</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple Ban, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Director Criticizes School Apple Bans As Premature</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with health director's comments;
picks up 7th graf pvs, `Daminozide is ...;' Adds byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators who yank apples from school lunch
rooms for fear of chemical contamination are running from a ``toxic
bogeyman,'' the state health director said Tuesday.
   Biting into a shiny, red apple as he discussed the issue with
reporters, Kenneth Kizer, said fears that children will get cancer
from the farm chemical daminozide, or Alar, are based on a
misinterpretation of a recent study by a private interest group.
   Apples and apple products are being banned from school cafeterias
in cities around the nation because of publicity about the potential
cancer threat from Alar, a chemical used in a minority of orchards.
   School systems in Atlanta, San Francisco, Chicago and dozens of
other cities stopped distributing apples this week, following the
earlier lead of New York City and Los Angeles. Schools in San Diego
and Portland, Ore., decided against such a ban.
   California is conducting its own tests on apples to assess any
risk. The results aren't due for another 10 days, but Kizer said he
believes the school apple bans are ``reactionary and premature, and
indeed our fear is they have really created a toxic bogeyman.''
   Kizer advised consumers to continue eating fruit, saying there
may be worse dangers in sugary alternatives.
   ``When we send a message to our kids that apples aren't safe,
what are they going to eat? They're going to eat Twinkies and
Zingers,'' he said.
   Despite his comments, millions of schoolchildren went without
apples, applesauce and juice Tuesday as more schools quit serving
apple products because the fruit might be tainted with Alar.
   Farm groups maintain there is little threat from the chemical,
and the manufacturer, Uniroyal Chemical Co. of Middlebury, Conn.,
estimates it is used on only 5 percent of America's apple crop.
   ``It's far more dangerous for them (school children) to ride the
school bus or breathe the air ... than eating an apple treated with
Alar,'' said Ron Myers, a Wenatchee, Wash., apple grower who is also
a member of the Washington Apple Commission.
   Daminozide is used most commonly on apples but also on other
fruit and on flowers. It prevents apples from dropping or being
blown from trees before they ripen, brings out color in some
varieties and may help improve texture and shelf life.
   The latest controversy over Alar was prompted by an NRDC report
that said daminozide poses a greater cancer threat to children than
to adults. The public interest group said research shows that is
because children's bodies are smaller and because they tend to eat
more apples and apple products.
   Worries about Alar grew as ``60 Minutes'' broadcast a report on
the subject and actress Meryl Streep spoke out in alarm.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said in February that tests
show a correlation between the chemical and cancer in mice. The
agency is conducting an 18-month review with an eye toward banning
the chemical.
   Atlanta school officials say Monday's decision to scratch apples
from school lunch menus was strictly precautionary, taken in the
absence of any evidence that Alar-treated apples have been served in
the system's 116 schools.
   ``When you're talking about children, we believe it's better to
take precautions,'' said Modenia N. Andrews, director of nutrition
for Atlanta schools. ``There's so much in the media, we felt it
expedient to go ahead and make that decision until more information
is available.''
   ``Because of the public outcry, I feel it's better to be
conservative and eliminate the apples until it's cleared by the
FDA,'' said Richard Farrar, director of food services for the San
Francisco Unified School District.
   A spokesman for the California Farm Bureau Federation and apple
growers said the San Francisco district's move was unfounded.
   ``They are attacking the whole industry, when it's just a small
group of growers in the Northwest using (Alar),'' said grower John
Bella. ``They are hurting us real bad and it's unfair. They should
get their facts straight.''
   Uniroyal Chemical estimates use has dropped to about 5 percent of
the U.S. apple crop because of health concerns raised in recent
years. That's down from 40 percent of the crop in 1985, when cancer
concerns were last raised.
   Varieties most commonly treated are MacIntosh, red delicious,
golden delicious, and Jonathan. Granny Smith, Pippin and other green
apples generally aren't treated.
   California is the nation's fourth-biggest producer of apples, a
market dominated by Washington state.
</TEXT>
