<FIRST>r w AM-US-Korea     03-14 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker: Premature to Talk of a US Withdrawal from Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Tuesday that it is premature to talk about withdrawing U.S. troops
from South Korea, but he said the Bush administration is pressing
the Seoul government to increase its share of the common defense
burden.
   ``I do think it's a bit premature to talk about pulling troops
out when you consider the security threat that still exists as far
as the North Koreans are concerned,'' Baker told a House
Appropriations subcommittee.
   ``If we were ever to get to that point, I would think we would
only get there after the South Koreans themselves had significantly
beefed up their own armed forces,'' he added.
   Baker, testifying before the committee about the U.S. foreign aid
program, was asked by Rep. Robert J. Mrazek, D-N.Y., why the U.S.
had no plans to withdraw its 40,000 troops from South Korea, ``a
nation that has the most dynamic economy in the world right now.''
   ``There are over 40 million South Koreans, there are around 20
million North Koreans, and we continue to spend billions of dollars
in supporting our troops in that nation,'' said Mrazek.
   He said the Pentagon has a draft plan for the withdrawal of U.S.
troops from Panama and contingency plans to reduce U.S. bases in the
Philippines, but nothing for Korea.
   ``Overwhelmingly the American people recognize that at this
particular juncture _ considering the investment of almost $100
billion since 1954 _ that the South Koreans can pretty well take
care of themselves,'' Mrazek said.
   ``I don't see any reason why South Korea can't put more people in
uniform in defending its own interests,'' he added.
   Baker answered that ``it's very important to recognize that there
may be more South Koreans than North Koreans, but there are a heck
of a lot more North Koreans in uniform and in the armed forces, and
they are, percentage-wise, I suppose, the most heavily armed nation
_ or one of the most heavily armed nations _ in the world.''
   ``Our commitment to the security of South Korea is what has
enabled it to become the dynamic economic power that it has
become,'' he added. ``It has only recently come out of the shadows
of being a debtor nation.''
   He said that when he and President Bush and he visited South
Korea last month, they impressed on President Roh Tae-woo and other
South Koreans the importance of increasing their share of the
defense burden and ``accepting the role in the world that success
brings.''
   ``They are no longer a developing country,'' Baker said. ``And we
need access to their markets and we need, we need fairness with
respect to exchange rates and things like that.''
</TEXT>
