<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Whales     03-14 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Whales,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 30 Stranded Whales Escape But 10 Perish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUNTA ARENAS, Chile, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue teacms succeeded in helping 30
grounded whales back into the open waters of the Strait of Magellan,
but eight others died on the beach, authorities reported Tuesday.
   Alejandro Roman, regional director of the National Fishing
Agency, said the whales had been stranded for more than 24 hours at
Playa Pescado, 18 miles north of the town of Punta Arenas. The
whales ranged in length from nine to 15 feet.
   Reporters for state television covered the rescue operation and
said most of the whales that died resisted efforts to move them into
the water.
   It was the third mass grounding of whales on beaches along the
Strait of Magellan in two weeks. Navy officials said dozens of the
mammals were saved by navy personnel and fishermen who managed to
get them back into deeper waters but at least 90 perished.
   Marine specialists said they had no explanation for the
groundings actions but speculated that the normally frigid waters at
the tip of South America were unusually warm and that affected the
whales' sonar system of determining directions.
</TEXT>
