<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Jamaica     03-14 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Jamaica,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker: Manley More Moderate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Tuesday that Michael Manley, the new Jamaican prime minister, has
moderated his political views and would prove an ally in the battle
against drug trafficking.
   Baker's assessment came in answer to a question from Rep. David
Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the House Appropriations foreign
subcommittee, during a hearing on the Bush administration's foreign
aid package.
   Manley is here to meet with a variety of U.S. officials,
including Baker.
   Baker told the panel that ``it's the view of many people in our
government that he has moderated his views and policies and that he
will be a reliable partner in terms of the drug problem.''
   Manley was re-elected last month, nine years after his leftist
government was voted out of office. During his first tenure, he had
alarmed the United States with some of his policies.
   Manley has been stressing his desire for the ``widest and most
constructive'' relationship possible with the Bush administration
and has said he will try to cooperate with U.S. officials to combat
drug trafficking through Jamaica.
   Manley told reporters he plans to raise the issues of drugs,
tourism and development when he meets with U.S. legislators.
   He is also supposed to Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and
William Bennett, the drug czar.
   Jamaica wants help from the United States because it needs to
``greatly improve interdiction and intelligence capabilities,''
particularly against cocaine smugglers, Manley said. Additionally,
the country has no drug rehabilitation facilities, a lack that needs
to be addressed.
   Manley said the country wants to increase the number of hotel
rooms and work to end the harassment of tourists. Tourism is a major
part of the Jamaican economy.
   As for relations with Cuba, Manley said his country intends to
re-establish diplomatic ties that were broken in the early 1980s.
The Cubans would be permitted to establish an embassy in Kingston.
   Though Manley said he doesn't agree with Cuban leader Fidel
Castro's political philosophy, he believes in having normal contact
with all nations, just at the United States has diplomatic links
with the Soviet Union.
   ``We don't intend to allow those relations to be provocative,''
he said.
   Manley said he told former Secretary of State George Shultz about
the plan to re-open a Cuban Embassy.
</TEXT>
