<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArt 1stLd-Writethru a0696 03-14 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Art, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Novelist Heinemann, Illinois Arts Group Support Flag Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with state legislators condemning
the exhibit, city park board action; picks up 5th graf, `Heinemann, a ...'
INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th graf to UPDATE with city council in Michigan
condemning exhibit; picks up last graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State legislators Tuesday condemned a student
artwork that features a U.S. flag spread on the floor as novelist
Larry Heinemann joined a statewide arts organization in support of
the embattled exhibit.
   After more than an hour of impassioned debate in Springfield, the
Illinois House approved a non-binding resolution 99-5 urging that
the exhibit at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago be closed.
   ``It's not a veterans issue, it's an American issue,'' said state
Rep. Linda Williamson, who had joined in protests in Chicago against
the exhibit. Most of the demonstrators were veterans and their
families.
   The Finance Committee of the Chicago Park District, owner of the
land on which the Art Institute is located, also on Tuesday reversed
itself and recommended that the Art Institute and seven other
Chicago museums get $28.4 million in funding. The full board later
approved the appropriation.
   Last week, the committee, citing the flag exhibit, voted to cut
off the money. The Art Institute's share is $6.5 million.
   Republican state Sen. Walter Dudycz, a leader in protests against
the flag exhibit, held a noon rally at the Capitol in Springfield to
draw attention to his resolution condemning the artwork.
   Heinemann, a Chicagoan who won the 1987 National Book Award for
his novel ``Paco's Story,'' said the enormous public response to the
exhibit at the School of the Art Institute indicated the school was
doing its job.
   Although the display has ``deeply and greatly shocked many
people,'' Heinemann said, ``any arts institute ... fails if students
are not given the freedom to explore subject matter and content.''
   Both Dudycz and Heinemann are Vietnam veterans.
   The Illinois Arts Alliance said the Art Institute had a
constitutional right to display the work by student Scott Tyler.
   ``And when we trample on the U.S. Constitution, we trample on
everything the American flag symbolizes,'' said Henry Fogel,
president of the multidisciplinary, statewide advocacy organization
for the arts. Fogel appeared at a news conference with Heinemann.
   The work, ``What is the Proper Way to Display a U.S. Flag,''
consists of a 32-by-59-inch flag spread on a floor next to a wall.
On the wall are mounted a photograph of several flag-draped coffins
and a small shelf. On the shelf, which is located directly above the
flag, are a bound collection of other photographs _ including one of
a U.S. flag being burned _ and a ledger in which visitors are
invited to write comments.
   The display is part of a 66-student show that opened on Feb. 17
and is scheduled to close Thursday.
   The exhibit has enraged veterans groups, who contend it
encourages people to walk on the U.S. flag, and has prompted daily
demonstrations outside the Art Institute, including one on Sunday
that drew more than 2,000 people.
   In Midland, Mich., the City Council on Monday night unanimously
approved a resolution condemning the Chicago exhibit. Midland is
near Saginaw, about 250 miles northeast of Chicago.
   ``My whole being just rebels at the thought of any dishonor to
the flag,'' said Councilman Harry McCaffrey, who introduced the
resolution.
   On Tuesday a tavern in Beach Park, a town north of Chicago, said
it would cover its floor with pictures of artist Tyler on Wednesday
and invite patrons to walk on them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
