<HEAD>Three Dead In U.S. Air Force Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two U.S. airmen were recovered
Wednesday after their helicopter crashed into the ocean during a
routine practice mission. Air Force officials said a third man was
killed but his body had not been recovered.
   Paul Berger, chief of community relations at Kadena Air Base in
Okinawa, said the two bodies were found early Wednesday by rescuers.
   The names of the victims were not released pending notification
of the next of kin, he said.
   The HH-3 helicopter with five crew members aboard crashed at 8:35
p.m. Tuesday during a routine practice mission near Ieshima island,
north of Okinawa.
   Two of the five were picked up by an Air Force rescue aircraft
and were reported in good condition at Kadena, Berger said. The
cause of the accident was under investigation, he added.
   The helicopter belonged to the 33rd Aerospace Rescue Recovery
Squadron at the air base 1,000 miles southwest of Tokyo.
