<HEAD>Two Air Force F-16s Collide, One Feared Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to CLARIFY condition of pilot. Pick up 7th
pvs, `Both aircraft...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. Air Force F-16 jet fighters
collided Tuesday during a training mission over central Spain's
Cuenca province, and one pilot was missing and feared dead, military
officials said.
   A second pilot parachuted to safety and was released after being
examined at a hospital.
   Air Force Capt. Willette Parker said the jets had left Madrid's
Torrejon Air Base when they collided.
   She identified the pilot who parachuted to safety as Capt. Steven
Kempf, 27, of Glendale, Ariz., who was examined and released from
Torrejon base hospital.
   She said the identity of the other pilot was not available and
that the cause of the accident had not been determined yet.
   A statement released by the Spanish Ministry of Defense said the
missing pilot had died.
   Both aircraft belonged to a squadron of the 401st Tactical
Fighter Wing, part of the 16th Air Force headquartered at Torrejon.
   On Dec. 5, the commander of the 16th Air Force, Gen. Winfield S.
Harpe, was killed during a similar accident in the same general area.
   Jane's Defense Weekly reported in December that the U.S. Air
Force lost 20 F-16s in service in countries of the 16-member North
Atlantic Treaty Organization last year.
   The 72 F-16s in the 401st Tactical Fighter Wing are to be
transferred to a base in Italy within three years under terms of a
new agreement signed in December by Spain and the United States.
