<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Azores-Crash     03-14 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Azores-Crash,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blame Overlapping Messages for Jet Crash in Azores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The February crash of an
American-chartered jetliner in the Azores that claimed 144 lives
probably was caused by overlapping radio messages, the government
reported Tuesday.
   It said the Boeing 707 apparently was flying at an altitude of
about 2,000 feet instead of 3,000 feet when it crashed into the
fog-covered Pico Alto mountain, killing all aboard.
   The Ministry of Public Works, Transport and Communications gave
this account of the overlapping messages:
   The control tower authorized the pilot to descend to 3,000 feet,
advised him which runway to use and asked him to renew contact when
the plane was at 3,000 feet.
   But at the same time the tower was sending the message the pilot
was radioing plans to descend to 2,000 feet.
   Neither the pilot nor tower heard the other's message and the jet
continued on its fatal course.
   ``The plane hit ... in a zone where flying is not permitted below
an altitude of 3,000 feet,'' the report said.
   The plane, owned by Independent Air Corp. of Smyrna, Tenn., was
carrying Italian tourists on their way to the Caribbean with a stop
at the Azores island of Santa Maria when the accident occurred Feb.
8.
   The report said the investigating commission found no indication
of mechanical or technical failure of the plane and ruled out
sabotage or other criminal action.
   Traffic controllers at the tower did give the jet's crew an
atmospheric pressure reading of 1,027 millibars instead of the
correct 1,108.7 millibars, according to the report. It said the
difference in pressure readings would mean the jet's altimeters told
the pilot he was 240 feet above his actual position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
