<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-Amnesty     03-14 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Amnesty,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Assembly Approves Amnesty For Former Somoza Guards</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly on Tuesday
approved amnesty for 1,933 former members of the national guard,
most of whom had been jailed since the Sandinista revolution
overthrew the Somoza dynasty in July 1979.
   Among those given amnesty were 39 former guardsmen, including
three lieutenant colonels, whose names did not appear on a list of
1,894 prisoners that President Daniel Ortega recommended be granted
amnesty.
   Ortega announced at a celebration of the Sandinista revolution
last month that he would recommend that the assembly grant the
amensties.
   The prisoners are to be released in a ceremony on Sunday at the
prison in Tipitapa, 14 miles east of the capital. Joao Baena Soares,
secretary-general of the Organization of American States, is
expected to attend. Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo may also be there.
   The Sandinista-dominated legislature approved the mass amnesty,
68-4, with two members abstaining.
   The vote came after an intense five-hour debate, during which the
opposition argued for the amnesty of those on the original list
submitted by Ortega, along with 39 others.
   Several Sandinista deputies argued against the release, saying
the prisoners committed unpardonable crimes when they served under
President Anastasio Somoza .
   Somoza fled Managua on July 17, 1979, two days before the
Sandinstas marched triumphantly into the capital. He was later
assassinated in exile.
   The National Assembly's Committee on Human Rights and Peace had
examined the list and earlier determined that 39 prisoners had
committed ``atrocious crimes'' against the Nicaraguan people and
``had not demonstrated will to change their ways.''
   But during Tuesday's debate, opposition representatives noted
that the Organization of American State's Inter-American Commission
on Human Rights had recommended that the leftist Sandinista
government free all jailed former guardsmen.
   The assembly approved the additional 39 cases even though their
amensty is sure to be challenged by authorities, legislators said.
   The amnesty is the result of accords reached by Central American
presidents in El Salvador on Feb. 14.
   After the meeting, Ortega promised to institute democratic
reforms and move up the presidential elections to February 1990, 10
months earlier than scheduled.
   The presidents also agreed to draft a plan within 90 days to
dismantle the U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebel force now living in
Honduras.
   The assembly approved the amnesty with the understanding ``that
the freeing of the prisoners will contribute to creating conditions
for the demobilization, relocation and repatriation of those
Nicaraguans who have been involved in either indirect or direct
armed activities in Honduran territory.''
   Relatives of jailed guardsmen pleaded for their release in
Tuesday's debate.
   Rosa Maria Herrera, wife of jailed former guardsman Juan de Dios
Herrera, sobbed quietly when the assembly approved her husband's
release.
   Her sister, two brothers-in-laws and a cousin also will be freed
under the amnesty. ``They were innocent,'' she said.
   Sandinsta deputy Danilo Aguirre Solis opposed the amnesty and
said despite it, ``the Nicaraguan people will never forget their
crimes.''
   He said those being let go were responsible for the deaths of
about 50,000 Nicaraguans during the revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
