<DOCNO> AP890314-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Japan-USColleges Adv20   03-14 0933</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Colleges, Adv 20,0963</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, March 20, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japanese Consider Importing U.S. College Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese balk at importing American beef and
rice, but they might be ready to import U.S. college educations.
   Supporters of the idea have almost utopian visions of a future in
which American colleges here add to international understanding,
reduce trade frictions, break the stuffy mold of Japanese higher
education and produce more Japanese world citizens.
   Southern Illinois University opened a branch campus last spring
and says it is faring well with about 450 Japanese in intensive
English courses.
   ``Things look quite bright and we're pretty much on schedule,''
said Jared Dorn, director of the project that in May moves from
temporary housing in a youth center to a custom-built campus.
   More than 150 American colleges and universities have expressed
interest in branch campuses in Japan in the past two years, but
perhaps only a dozen will succeed.
   A strong Japanese proponent of importing education is Chikara
Higashi, the president of Temple University's 2,000-student branch
in Tokyo and a member of Parliament from the governing Liberal
Democratic Party. Philadelphia-based Temple has had a branch here
since 1982 and offers a full, four-year degree course.
   In recent years Japan has opened up industry, banks, stockbrokers
and pharmaceuticals to more foreign competition, Higashi said in an
interview.
   ``Education should be the first to be internationalized, but it
is the last.''
   Japanese education is effective in its early years, he said.
   ``But when Japan is a leading country and is asked to play a
larger world role, we need Japanese who can communicate and take
leadership in international communities. We lack that.''
   Almost every week, American and Japanese educators visit the
Southern Illinois University branch in Nakajo, a town of 30,000
people 150 miles north of Tokyo, or the mother campus in Carbondale,
Ill., Dorn said by telephone from Nakajo.
   ``They are all going very slowly, waiting to see what happens
with us and others.''
   They are ``inching toward agreements,'' he added.
   The branch-campus wavelet, despite doubts in the Ministry of
Education, has political backing in Tokyo and Washington.
   The top U.S. sponsor is Richard Gephardt, the Missouri
congressman who sought the Democratic presidential nomination last
year on a platform critical of Japanese trade surpluses.
   But Gephardt says his objective is to find ways to help Americans
export more to Japan and make the two countries better understand
each other. Gephardt is co-chairman of the USA-Japan Committee for
Promoting Trade Expansion, a group of U.S. congressmen and members
of Japan's Parliament, the Diet. The committee coordinates the
mating of U.S. colleges and host towns.
   Yusuke Kataoka, executive director of the Tokyo office of
Gephardt's committee, said Japanese university graduates are
ill-suited to an outward-looking era in which Japan has major world
responsibilities.
   American branch campuses, Kataoka said, will be ``a kind of
perestroika (the Soviet term for restructuring) to break through the
inbreeding of the Japanese higher-education system.''
   U.S. higher education is ``more practical, broader, more
cosmopolitan,'' he said.
   Japan is renowned for turning out diligent students who top world
rankings in math and science tests. But that applies mostly to grade
school and high school; university years are often spent gaining
friends and a diploma useful in one's career and concentrating on a
narrow field without studying hard.
   By contrast, a U.S. college education is regarded here as hard
work and broad training that develops a more rounded and creative
adult than Japan's system, which produces gifted team workers but
not so many precedent-setters.
   For example, only two Japanese scientists have won Nobel Prizes
in physics and chemistry since 1970, while 39 Americans have been
honored for basic research _ an area where Japan lags the United
States.
   Japanese education is also notorious for the inability of
graduates to speak English, and this is where the American campuses
see their toehold.
   The typical plan is a year of intensive English, followed by two
years of general college education _ all taught in English by
professors from U.S. institutions. Then successful students can
transfer their credits to the mother college or a related
institution in the United States and earn a U.S. bachelor's degree
in two more years.
   After the campuses establish themselves, they also would offer
courses on Japan and related topics to American students.
   But that is in the future.
   So far, said Kataoka of the Gephardt committee, four U.S.
universities are lined up to follow Southern Illinois into Japan:
Texas A&amp;M, Oklahoma State University, the Minnesota state
universities system and Mississippi State University.
   Ministry of Education officials tend to doubt U.S. colleges will
succeed. Yoshiyuki Nishizawa, head of an office to promote
educational and cultural exchanges in the ministry, said it may be
hard to attract students because graduates will not receive the
Japanese university degree that is often essential for getting a
good job.
   ``And if a student fails to learn English and doesn't get to go
to the United States, he will have nothing for two years' work,''
Nishizawa said, adding that it will be hard for the branches to
maintain strong faculties.
   But he conceded that some parents are more interested in having
their children study abroad than before.
   Graduates of Temple-Japan have no trouble landing good jobs,
President Higashi said, and their success may have paved the way for
the growth of U.S. college branches.
   ``So we will be happy to see more universities come, but it will
be difficult.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
