<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-TMI-Denton Adv26   03-14 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-TMI-Denton, Adv 26,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For TMI Figure Denton, Song Remains the Same</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-TMI Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harold Denton is like a rock group that
produces a hit, then is obliged to perform it again and again.
   Denton, 52, was the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's most senior
official sent to the Three Mile Island power station for the
nation's worst commercial nuclear accident.
   His calm, easy manner and frank discussion of what was happening
helped reassure the public while technicians got the crisis under
control.
   Ten years later, he remains an ardent booster of nuclear power.
His career has taken him to nuclear-powered generating plants around
the world _ including two visits to Chernobyl, where an April 1986
accident killed at least 31 people and released a radioactive cloud.
   But people still associate Denton with Three Mile Island.
   ``I'm always introduced _ never can get rid of it _ as TMI
spokesman,'' he recalled during an interview at the agency's
headquarters in this Washington suburb.
   Being a symbol during the uncertainty of the emergency carried
responsibilties. The biggest was that no matter how bad things got,
Denton knew he could not leave.
   ``We had people on our own staff who got too concerned to be
useful and had to return home. They just didn't want to be there,''
he said.
   ``The tension was so high, it's hard to re-create. People would
joke that if they saw a truck being hitched up to my trailer and my
leaving, that would be a distinct clue that it was time to leave,''
he said.
   Recognizing his status as an industry spokesman, he returned to
the plant 16 months after the accident to demonstrate his faith in
the safety of venting radioactive krypton gas into the atmosphere.
The gas had escaped into the reactor containment building during the
accident.
   At the time, Denton was the NRC's chief safety officer for
reactors, a post he held until becoming director of the agency's
governmental and public affairs unit in 1987.
   It is his new job overseeing the NRC's international programs
that took him to Chernobyl.
   Denton considers Three Mile Island ``way, way down'' on the
seriousness scale when compared to Chernobyl. ``Very little
radioactivity got out of TMI,'' he said.
   In terms of public safety, Three Mile Island fortunately never
amounted to much, he said.
   ``In retrospect, the biggest threat to health and safety was on
Wednesday. By the time we got there (on Friday), the accident was
over. We just didn't know that,'' he said.
   The damage to the public's confidence in nuclear technology was
another matter, Denton conceded.
   ``I think people's perception for a long time got more and more
negative afterwards as there were allegations of (adverse) health
effects,'' he said. ``Suddenly, people got interested in reporting
events around all reactors, so the perception, I think, of the
public was that the industry was really about to have another TMI at
any moment.''
   But to Denton, the accident was a wakeup call that has made the
industry safer. Reactor operator qualifications have improved,
instruments provide more detail, emergency response is better, and
the NRC has become more adept at managing information, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday March 26</NOTE>
