<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0712EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-14 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Just Coolin''' (Atlantic) _ LeVert
   
   LeVert describes Side 1 of ``Just Coolin''' as a ``conceptual
funk suite,'' and the term is unintentionally apt. The five songs
will send most listeners into a conceptual funk that will have them
second-guessing their record-buying habits.
   In an attempt to attract a younger audience, LeVert has made
music for the curbside, with a backbeat guaranteed to drown out all
conversation and even honking cars. The problem is, it sounds like
the same backbeat on all five songs.
   Monotonous is not a strong enough word. The music lacks the humor
or grit of the best rap, and the street dialogue between cuts is
lame.
   Side 2 sees LeVert revert to the ballads that helped make their
first two albums big sellers. The tunes are in the Marvin Gaye
tradition _ the late singer is even mentioned in ``Let's Get
Romantic.'' But again, there's no variety in the tempos, and the
songs aren't good enough to justify the sleep-inducing pace. The
slow side is better than Side 1, but so is Tiffany.
   The best strategy for LeVert at this point would be to find some
stronger material, put out another album quickly and announce they
were just foolin' about ``Just Coolin.''' Refunds would be nice too.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``I Wanna Have Some Fun'' (Jive) _ Samantha Fox
   
   On the cover of this, her third album, we find Miss Fox pretty
much clothed, which must mean the former British pinup queen is
getting serious about This Music Thing. What she isn't getting is
much better.
   Oh, all right, most of this is harmless enough, I guess. She has
a serviceable, if unspectacular, voice and she has an army of
producers behind her, creating syntho-pop dance music, the likes of
which Donna Summer did an awful lot better 10 years ago.
   But there's one track in this morass that sinks below the others:
a blasphemous synthed-up ruination of the Dusty Springfield classic,
``I Only Want to Be With You.'' Whoever is responsible should be
forced to listen to the original _ or to Southside Johnny's soulful
remake _ repeatedly, while doing some prison time somewhere. Gaaaaak.
   _ By Robert Byrd, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Hold An Old Friend's Hand'' (MCA) _ Tiffany
   
   Teen-age pop phenom Tiffany is older now, all of 17, as she
follows up her immensely successful but shallow debut album recorded
when she was just 14.
   People will probably like ``Hold An Old Friend's Hand'' just as
much, but just what is it about this adolescent girl that inspires
such adoration?
   The 11 tracks here are the stuff of teen-age girl talk _ yearning
for boys, trying to be noticed by them, feeling rejected when one
stops calling and always keeping in mind that a girl doesn't need a
boy's attentions to validate her.
   All this has been done before, in a much more stylish manner,
than the accumulation of techno-pop brights and syrupy balladeering
engineered by Tiffany and her producer-mentor, George Tobin.
   But the hooks, as on ``All This Time'' and ``Radio Romance,'' are
mindlessly catchy, and Tiffany has a serviceable voice that often
recalls Stevie Nicks, especially in the lower registers.
   Some songs, such as ``I'll Be the Girl,'' dimly echo the girl
groups of the early 1960s, even to the point of having spoken verses.
   Perhaps it is the simple teen-age romance lyrics Tiffany sings
and the California wholesomeness she exudes that draws fans to her
like moths. She is the antithesis of the rebellious youth whose
image is projected by many rock acts; instead, she's everyone's
perfect daughter.
   Tiffany may be simply trying to reflect her age _ the 1980s, a
return to conformism and a distaste for experimentation of any kind.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
