<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Doctorow Adv24-26   03-14 1142</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Doctorow, Adv 24-26,1171</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 24-26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: A Doctorow State of Mind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.L. Doctorow may be New York's ``State Writer''
but the author is thinking about spending some time away.
   Doctorow has been living for 20 years in the vintage 1906 New
Rochelle house that inspired the best-seller and film ``Ragtime.''
But with his three children all grown he and his wife, Helen, think
a change of scenery might be in order.
   ``New York does mean a lot to me but we've been talking about
living out West or in Europe,'' said Doctorow, who was recently
awarded the New York Writers Institute Edith Wharton Citation of
Merit.
   Wherever the writer may settle, his novels will be remembered for
their evocative look at New York in the first half of the 20th
century. Open up one of Doctorow's books and be prepared: Harry
Houdini may come to visit; Emma Goldman might offer advice on love;
and Admiral Peary may invite readers along on a trip to the North
Pole.
   Look up and see the mighty Hindenburg zeppelin float by. Grab a
piece of paper and enter a contest for ``The Typical American Boy.''
Hop on the subway and discover the Town of Tomorrow at the World's
Fair. Sneak on a train and discover America.
   But be careful, bad things are everywhere: ruthless business
tycoons; pale-faced thugs; anti-Semitic punks; and legendary
gangsters such as Dutch Schultz, who loomed large in the Bronx of
the 1930s, a world of sweet potato vendors, junk hustlers and
``capable boys'' like Billy Bathgate, the narrator and adventurer of
Doctorow's latest novel, ``Billy Bathgate.''
   ``I think Billy is a rhapsodist,'' the author said in an
interview. ``He has enormous zest and the ability to be thrilled.
Billy really takes the world in. He embraces it all. No matter how
ugly, hideous or bizarre.''
   Doctorow, a native of the Bronx himself, returns in ``Billy
Bathgate'' to his childhood setting, the backdrop for earlier works
including ``Loon Lake'' and ``World's Fair.'' Billy Bathgate, the
author's ``alter ego,'' lives with his unstable and lonely mother
and dreams of meeting Schultz, who makes a cameo appearance in
``World's Fair.''
   One day Schultz's Packard pulls up in front of a local warehouse
and Billy has his chance. He impresses the gangster with his
juggling act, a ``Galilean maneuver'' that involves two rubber
balls, a navel orange, an egg and a black stone. The performance is
greeted with applause and a crisp $10 bill from a laughing Schultz.
   The resourceful Bathgate eases himself into the gangster's
entourage, winning the confidence of Abbadabba Berman, the
syndicate's financial wizard, and having a wild affair with
Schultz's mistress.
   ``The myth of Schultz is what I deal with,'' Doctorow said, ``but
he does really get involved with him in not a casual way. He's so
attracted to the idea of Schultz. The reigning gangster hero of his
neighborhood.''
   But the gangster has clearly seen better days. With prohibition
repealed, bootlegging is no longer profitable. An aggressive young
district attorney named Thomas E. Dewey is hot on his trail and
Schultz has become careless, committing murder at the slightest
provocation. He is eventually gunned down at a New Jersey hideout.
   Names and places often repeat themselves in Doctorow's novels
with the author citing ``a sort of repertory company of souls who
make their appearance in each book.'' But the writing covers a
variety of styles.
   ``Ragtime'' is breezy and crisp, with short, snappy sentences
moving events along. ``Lives of the Poets,'' six short stories and a
novella, is an experiment in minimalism as Doctorow departs from the
rich language of his other novels to give a stark version of life in
the 1980s.
   ``Loon Lake'' and ``Billy Bathgate'' use a stream-of-consciouness
narrative that speeds up, slows down and races ahead like bumper
cars at an amusement park. In ``Billy Bathgate,'' Doctorow writes of
Billy's initiation with guns:
   ``And then what happens, if you don't make it yours you are dead,
you have created the circumstance, but it has its own free-standing
rage, available to anyone, and this is what you take into yourself,
like an anger that they've done this to you, the people who are
staring at your gun, that it's their intolerable crime to be the
people you are waving this gun at.''
   Billy Bathgate adds to Doctorow's gallery of young heros from
``Loon Lake'' and ``World's Fair.'' The boys all behave very
differently but some common themes emerge.
   ``The stories are sentimental educations about young people
learning the ways of the world and their own emotions,'' Doctorow
said.
   Edgar Lawrence Doctorow was born in 1931, the son of David R.
Doctorow, who sold records and music equipment, and Rose Doctorow, a
pianist. While attending the Bronx High School of Science, he worked
on the literary magazine, ``Dynamo,'' and went to major in
philosophy at Kenyon College in Ohio.
   In the late '50s he read screenplays at Columbia Pictures and was
later hired as an editor with the New American Library. His first
two novels, the Western ``Welcome to Hard Times,'' and ``Big as
Life,'' a science-fiction story, were written in his spare time, as
Doctorow often put in 20-hour work days.
   In 1969, he began writing full time, and two years later came out
with ``The Book of Daniel,'' a critically acclaimed story inspired
by the lives of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, members of the Communist
Party who were executed in 1953 for selling atomic secrets to the
Soviets.
   ``Ragtime,'' a critical and commercial success, came out in 1975.
It was a montage of life in New York at the turn of the century.
Doctorow received the National Book Critics Circle Award and an Arts
and Letters Award from the American Academy and National Institute
for Arts. In 1986, he received the National Book Award for ``World's
Fair.''
   ``I don't believe in literature as an elitist taste,'' Doctorow
said. ``My great ideal of this sort of thing is Dickens, who was
read avidly by people who read newspapers and monthly magazines.
That's my idea of the way society and writers should relate.''
   ``Billy Bathgate'' has given the author the will to leave his
beloved Bronx for good. ``It is history, that pig, biting into the
heart's secrets,'' Doctorow wrote in ``The Book of Daniel,''
lamenting the transformation of his native Bronx from peaceful
getaway to crowded borough.
   Doctorow sees his next book as ``something huge.''
   ``I see it as something that will be some way of saying
everything that has to be said. I have a compulsion to find a form
for so many disparate things. Books leave me rather exhausted and
completed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 24-26</NOTE>
