<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     03-14 0852</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0891</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines will ask a bankruptcy court
judge this week to approve the sale of its Northeast shuttle to New
York developer Donald Trump for $365 million, the first of an
expected series of asset sales by the troubled airline, an Eastern
attorney said.
   Representatives of the airline's pilots and mechanics unions said
Monday they would challenge the deal, which they expect to be
further slowed by weeks in bankruptcy court because of procedural
matters.
   Meanwhile, observers said the airline, after attracting throngs
of bargain-hunting fliers with a $12 Northeast shuttle fare over the
weekend, could be ready to expand its cut-rate strategy in an
attempt to keep cash coming into its strike-crippled operations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters officials reached a tentative
labor-reform settlement with federal prosecutors hours before the
start of a trial on a lawsuit to oust the union's allegedly
mobster-dominated leadership.
   A lawyer for the Teamsters said Monday the union agreed to
introduce constitutional amendments for election reform at its 1991
convention. Also three watchdogs, jointly chosen by the union and
the government, will investigate and arbitrate alleged union
corruption and oversee elections.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's 13,200 commercial banks earned
$25.3 billion in 1988, up from $3.7 billion in 1987 and topping the
previous high of $18.1 billion, set in 1985, the government said.
   However, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. Chairman L. William
Seidman chided the industry Monday for passing on more than half the
profits to stockholders and advised banks to adopt a more
conservative approach.
   Seidman, noting real estate loan problems in the East and in some
areas in the West, warned, ``Prudence, not go-go growth, should be
their motto these days.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House and Treasury Department officials
are reviewing a plan to protect fragile regional economies from the
quick sale of billions of dollars of real estate repossessed from
failed savings and loans.
   The plan was developed by former Deputy Treasury Secretary R.T.
McNamar, who presented it to Bush administration officials last week.
   According to an outline prepared by McNamar and obtained by The
Associated Press, it would create state or local trusts that would
issue bonds, backed partly by the federal government and partly by
state or local governments, and use the money to buy distressed
S&amp;Ls' real estate from the federal government.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal board created to help bail out
financially distressed banks of the Farm Credit System spent $690
million in its first year of operation, according to a report to
Congress.
   The Farm Credit System Assistance Board's report said Monday that
$629 million went to help regional banks in Jackson, Miss.;
Louisville, Ky.; Omaha, Neb.; and St. Paul, Minn.
   From 1985 to 1987, the cooperatively owned Farm Credit System
alone had losses of more than $4.5 billion. Currently, the system
has about $55 billion in loans outstanding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis V. Gerstner Jr., president of American
Express Co., was named chairman and chief executive officer of RJR
Nabisco Inc., the food and tobacco giant recently acquired by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Analysts said Gerstner's immediate tasks would include addressing
RJR's declining domestic tobacco market share and giving its
employees a sense of direction in the wake of the $24.53 billion
takeover by the investment firm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yamanouchi Pharmaceutical Co. and Shaklee
Corp. announced a merger agreement under which the Japanese firm
would buy the direct marketing company for $395 million in cash.
   The $28-per-share bid by Yamanouchi, which bought Shaklee's
Japanese subsidiary last month, apparently foiled an unsolicited
offer from an investor group led by takeover specialist Irwin Jacobs.
   Yamanouchi said the $28 it would pay for each of Shaklee's 14
million outstanding shares would be in addition to a one-time
$20-per-share dividend Shaklee recently declared.
</TEXT>
