<FIRST>u f AM-PittstonDebate     03-14 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pittston Debate,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW Presidents Decides Against Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers union's top
official is no longer willing to debate issues in a contract dispute
with the Pittston Co., a radio station reported Monday.
   UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said Monday that union President
Richard Trumka decided to call off the debate when he learned that
Pittston Chairman Paul W. Douglas wouldn't attend, Bluefield radio
station WVVA reported.
   Corcoran and Trumka were in Charleston on business Monday, but
they declined to discuss the nature of their visit, the radio
station reported.
   The Greenwich, Conn., Fellowship of Clergy suggested the public
forum after a demonstration by coal miners outside Pittston
headquarters in Greenwich last month, and invited Douglas and Trumka
to participate.
   In separate letters Friday to the Rev. C. Edward Deyton, pastor
of Diamond Hill United Methodist Church in Greenwich and fellowship
chairman, Trumka accepted the offer and Douglas designated Gene
Matthis, chairman of the Pittston Coal Group in Lebanon, Va., as the
company's representative at the debate.
   Members of the United Mine Workers have been working for more
than a year without a contract in Virginia, Kentucky and West
Virginia.
   Pittson has about 1,700 workers in 20 mines and has laid off
about 4,000 miners in recent years.
   Miners threatened to strike Feb. 1, one year after agreeing to
work without a contract while negotiations continued, but accepted a
30- to 60-day cooling off period requested by the governors of the
three states.
</TEXT>
