<DOCNO> AP890314-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RJRNabisco-Amex Bjt   03-14 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-RJR Nabisco-Amex, Bjt,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gerstner Departure Leaves American Express Without Its Key Strategist</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX10 of March 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. will lose a key strategist
and likely future chairman when Louis V. Gerstner Jr., its president
and head of its ``crown jewels'' credit-card and travel subsidiary,
takes charge of RJR Nabisco Inc. next month, analysts say.
   As chairman and chief executive officer of the Travel Related
Services Co. division, Gerstner was behind the expansion of American
Express' lucrative credit-card market share through new products
like the Platinum and Optima cards and oversaw the successful
``membership has its privileges'' promotion.
   His unit, which also is responsible for travelers checks and
travel service offices, consistently has been the most profitable
for American Express and in the entire financial-services industry.
   In last year's fourth quarter, the subsidiary's earnings rose 18
percent to a quarterly record $183.5 million.
   Gerstner's departure, announced Monday, after 11 years at
American Express will mean Chairman James D. Robinson III will have
to shoulder a larger portion of the daily activities now handled by
Gerstner, and leaves in doubt the choice of successor to Robinson,
analysts said.
   Robinson said he will assume the title of president of the parent
company, while Aldo Papone, president and chief operating officer of
Travel Related Services, will become chief executive officer of the
subsidiary.
   ``In all indication he (Gerstner) would have become chairman when
Mr. Robinson moved into retirement,'' said Perrin Long, analyst with
Lipper Analytical Services Corp.
   ``He (Gerstner) gets to run his own show now faster than he would
have had he stayed at American Express ... since there's only a five
or six year difference between he and Mr. Robinson.''
   Gerstner, 47, and Robinson, 53, had formed a highly effective
management team, analysts said, with Robinson establishing broad
corporate goals and Gerstner carrying them out and setting
market-share guidelines.
   Analysts said it was unlikely that Gerstner's departure would
have a major impact on American Express over the next few years,
since the company's long-range plans already are in place.
   But ``looking down the road, it will later depend on who emerges
in the next generation of leadership,'' said Adam L. Starr, an
analyst with First Manhattan Corp.
   Starr noted that Gerstner lately had been pushing for American
Express to focus more on the ``crown jewels'' travel related
services and less on high-risk businesses, including the Shearson
Lehman Hutton brokerage unit.
   Shearson's earnings have been hurt since the October 1987 stock
market crash. In the last two years American Express has cut its
stake in Shearson from 100 percent to 62 percent.
   Gerstner joined American Express in 1978 as president of the
American Express Card Division, and the next year was named
president of the Travel Related Services Group, responsible for
American Express cards, travelers checks and travel service offices.
   When Travel Related Services became a subsidiary in 1982,
Gerstner became its chairman and chief executive officer. He became
president of the parent company in 1985.
   During Gerstner's career at American Express, the company's card
membership rose from 8.6 million to 30.7 million as the card became
accepted in more retail stores worldwide.
   Gerstner's move came as somewhat of a surprise to analysts
because of his lack of experience in the food and tobacco
industries, RJR's core businesses.
   But those with whom he is closely associated said Gerstner
possessed the skills needed to run a company such as RJR, which
remains in a state of transition following its record $25 billion
acquisition by buyout specialists Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
earlier this year.
   ``A good manager can work in any industry,'' said Starr. ``He's
known as a real stickler for quality of service and products.''
   Gerstner will succeed F. Ross Johnson, who resigned Feb. 9 as
RJR's chief executive after leading an unsuccessful takeover bid for
the Atlanta-based company. He will assume his new post April 3.
   Analysts said Gerstner faces several challenges at RJR, including
deciding quickly what changes, if any, should be made due to the
buyout.
   RJR has indicated it will sell some lines of business to deal
with antitrust concerns raised by the federal government, but the
extent of any further restructuring _ such as other divestitures or
cutbacks _ is unknown.
   Gerstner also must develop strategies to address RJR's loss in
tobacco market share, said Marc Cohen, an analyst with Sanford C.
Bernstein in New York.
   Among RJR Nabisco's operating companies are R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco, Nabisco Brands, Del Monte Foods and Planters LifeSavers.
</TEXT>
