<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Fares     03-14 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Fares,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expected Cut-Rate Fares On Eastern Could Be Risky</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation is rife that strike-torn Eastern
Airlines will introduce fares as low as $49 one way between New York
and Florida in time for Easter and students' spring break to lure
back passengers.
   But before you grab your sunglasses and beach towel, consider
this: Fares that cheap usually carry risks, and these could have
plenty.
   The experience over the weekend with Eastern's special $12
Northeast shuttle fare, which drew throngs of bargain-hunting fliers
and stranded hundreds in three airports, could be a good example.
   Even if the cheap seats to Florida are reserved, there may not be
enough pilots to fly the planes, and it might not be possible to
book through a travel agent, industry observers said Monday.
   Most Eastern pilots and flight attendants have honored the strike
by the airline's Machinists union, which entered its 11th day today.
Miami-based Eastern filed for federal bankruptcy court protection
from creditors Thursday, citing a cash crisis stemming from the
labor walkout.
   In an attempt to shore up its crumbling market share, analysts
believe Eastern may expand its cut-rate strategy from the shuttle to
its primary market, Florida, as travelers begin flocking south for
spring holidays. Industry speculation points to a $49 one-way ticket
between New York and Florida, which would be about half the
prevailing discount fare.
   But experts cautioned that any fare-cutting probably would be
short-lived and unlikely to be matched by Eastern's competitors,
whose Florida flights are nearly fully booked.
   Furthermore, some travel agents may refuse to sell the cheap
Eastern tickets, fearing the risk to passengers of flying on a
strike-bound carrier and a potential deluge of refund requests if
flights are cancelled.
   ``I can't afford to have clients come back to me with
complaints,'' said David Perelman, president of DMS Travel in
Manhattan. ``It's a great deal _ if you can get on a plane.''
   Suzanne Jensen, a spokeswoman for Uniglobe Travel (International)
Inc. in Vancouver, British Columbia, said some of the company's
franchised travel agents would sell the cut-rate tickets if
customers insisted _ but would not provide refunds.
   Eastern wouldn't say Monday whether it was considering launching
the fares and officials declined to comment on how the airline would
provide enough planes to meet demand if such a promotion was staged.
   Hundreds of passengers were stranded in New York, Washington and
Boston airports Sunday night when Eastern could not get enough
planes in the air to accommodate the throngs that bought $12 shuttle
tickets.
   ``We will approach each market on an individual basis; we have
not indicated what our fare plans are,'' said company spokesman
Robin Matell in Miami.
   Eastern would not need approval from the bankruptcy court to cut
fares, Matell said.
</TEXT>
