<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Bankruptcy Bjt   03-14 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern To Ask OK For Shuttle Sale To Trump; Unions Will Fight Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots and mechanics unions say
they will mount a challenge in bankruptcy court to the proposed $365
million sale of the airline's Northeast shuttle to developer Donald
Trump.
   At attorney for strike-bound Eastern said the airline will ask
U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Burton Lifland this week to approve the
shuttle deal, the first of an expected series of asset sales by the
troubled airline.
   Farrell Kupersmith, a financial adviser to Eastern's 3,600
pilots, about 95 percent of whom are honoring an 11-day strike by
the Machinists union, said the pilots would oppose the shuttle sale
in court.
   Kupersmith, a partner with the consulting firm Touche Ross &amp; Co.,
also said a committee representing the interests of Eastern
creditors in the proceedings would want time to review the deal,
further delaying the sale.
   ``Every creditor knows that the only consistently profitable part
of Eastern is the shuttle,'' he said. ``You do not reorganize
companies by selling the best part.''
   A Machinists official also said Monday the union was working on
its own bankruptcy reorganization plan for Eastern, which could
include a buyout of the airline.
   The request to sell the shuttle would be the first step in what
is expected to be a long and bitter battle to reorganize Eastern,
which filed for Chapter 11 protection from creditors in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court last week.
   Eastern has 180 days to file a full reorganization plan, which
lawyers said would include the sale of some of Eastern's $4.5
billion in assets in addition to the shuttle. After the 180 days,
other parties in the case can file restructuring proposals.
   Under federal law, Eastern must persuade Lifland that the sale of
any asset is absolutely necessary to continue operations.
   The shuttle linking New York, Boston and Washington has been
operating since the Machinists went on strike March 4. The strike
sparked sympathy walkouts by pilots and flight attendants that
nearly shut the carrier down.
   The airline last weekend discounted shuttle fares to $12 and
reduced them to $49 during this week to lure passengers.
   Eastern lawyer Bruce Zirinsky said a request to close the shuttle
deal, announced in October, would be made by week's end. Repayment
of associated debt and a required pension fund payment would leave
Eastern with about $210 million in cash from the sale.
   ``If you don't sell it there's a significant risk that it will
deteriorate in value and Mr. Trump may walk away,'' Zirinsky said.
``We don't think it's prudent for Eastern and its creditors to bear
that risk.''
   U.S. Trustee Harold Jones, who will supervise administration of
Eastern's Chapter 11 case, said Monday that a meeting to appoint a
committee of about 20 creditors was set for March 22.
   The Machinists also will seek to block any Eastern-proposed
reorganization and keep the airline's assets from being sold, said
John Peterpaul, vice president of the International Association of
Machinists.
   Peterpaul said the union had a framework in place for a
reorganization that would include a joint buyout with outside
parties, but declined to elaborate. Trans World Airlines Chairman
Carl C. Icahn has been mentioned as a possible buyer.
   Union officials contend that Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's
parent Texas Air Corp., intends to strip Eastern's assets, attempt
to impose lower wages and break unions as part of a restructuring.
Lorenzo has pledged to keep the airline aloft by preserving its core
operations.
   The shape of Eastern's reorganization plan largely depends on
whether Lorenzo can replace pilots and increase the number of routes
being flown.
   Industry sources said Eastern is expected to begin advertising
this week for pilots because far fewer have returned to work than
the airline had hoped.
   Despite reports of a pilot shortage, sources said other airlines
were ``hiring like crazy'' and that the Air Line Pilots Association
planned to dissuade pilots from joining Eastern. The Trump sale also
could siphon some needed pilots from the airline.
   An industry official with knowledge of ALPA's plans said the
union this week is expected to approve loans, strike benefits and
payment of back salary to Eastern pilots. ALPA also plans to seek
commitments from other airline pilots unions not to fly planes on
routes purchased from Eastern unless the airline hires Eastern
pilots.
</TEXT>
