<DOCNO> AP890314-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChannelOne     03-14 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critic Remains Unbowed By Live Channel One Report On Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Channel One, an advertiser-supported TV news
service for schools, produced commercial-free live coverage of the
space shuttle launch, but one critic says the service still doesn't
belong in the classroom.
   Peggy Charren, head of the Massachusetts-based advocacy group
Action for Children's Television, said she expected the architects
of Channel One would be on ``their best behavior'' during the
current five-week test of the service.
   ``Trojan horses have some benefits. That's why people let them
into the city in the first place,'' she said.
   If the project moves beyond the test stage and is installed in
schools across the country, Mrs. Charren said she would not be
surprised to see an expansion of the time allowed for commercials.
   During the test in six schools, paid ads are limited to no more
than two minutes during Channel One's 12-minute daily news show.
   ``The problem isn't the two minutes of ads. The problem is we are
selling children to adverstisers. They think they are going to get
enough kids buying enough products to make the investment
worthwhile,'' she said.
   The special coverage of the shuttle Discovery's launch Monday was
billed by Channel One's producers, Whittle Communications LP of
Knoxville, Tenn., as a chance to demonstrate the vitality and
versatility of the news service that it hopes to make available to
8,000 schools next year.
   The 15-minute program included live shots of the blastoff and
commentary from ex-astronaut Don Lind and the two young news anchors
who appear on the regular Channel One show.
   It was left to each of the six test schools to use the program as
they saw fit, broadcasting it live in selected classrooms or taping
it for later use.
   At Mumford High School in Detroit, Principal Robin Oden said he
let teachers decide whether the show would be appropriate. He said
about three-fourths of the teachers showed it live.
   ``It was very, very exciting,'' Oden said. ``These are the kinds
of things that we can do with this system.''
   Stan Jasinskas, principal at Eisenhower Middle School in Kansas
City, Kan., said he had planned to record the show for later use,
but gave teachers the option of running it live after the launch was
delayed about two hours.
   Jasinskas said commercial-free specials ``certainly can't hurt''
Whittle's campaign to win support for the Channel One project.
   Channel One is in the second week of 25-show test at the six
schools. Whittle Communications gave each school $50,000 in video
hardware and a satellite dish. The news program, produced in Los
Angeles, is sent by satellite each morning to the test schools,
where it is recorded automatically for replay during school hours.
   The daily news show has included pitches for Levi's jeans,
Snickers candy bars, Wrigley's chewing gum and Head &amp; Shoulders
shampoo.
   Groups such as the National Parent-Teachers Association and the
National Association of Secondary School Principals have opposed the
idea of including paid ads in programs that are shown in school.
   But Whittle argues that the ads are a reasonable price for
schools to pay for the hardware and programming that none of them
have been able to afford otherwise. He also says the schools are
free to use the television equipment for other school purposes.
   Mumford's Oden, for instance, said teachers at his school plan to
make a videotape of tips on how to prepare for a required aptitude
test. He said the tape probably will be shown during the two-week
spring break hiatus that Channel One is allowing starting next week.
   Whittle also has agreed with a group of Western public broadcast
stations to make the Channel One distribution system available to
carry selected public service programs that schools could tape for
later use.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
