<FIRST>r f PM-US-CanadaTrade     03-14 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Canada Trade,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-Canada Free Trade Pact Going Well</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trade, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S.-Canada free trade agreement is going
so well that the countries will likely accelerate tariff reductions,
top trade officials say.
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills and Canadian Trade Minister
John Crosbie said they planned to begin reviewing requests to speed
up work toward eventual removal of tariffs on certain products.
   Mrs. Hills said that there was ``tremendous interest'' on the
part of U.S. firms to lower tariff barriers early. The historic free
trade agreement, which took effect Jan. 1, calls for the gradual
phase-out of all tariff barriers and most non-tariff barriers
between the two countries over the next 10 years.
   While the trade pact spelled out the cuts to be made each year in
tariffs on particular products, it provided for an acceleration if
both countries agreed.
   Crosbie predicted that faster tariff reductions could take effect
starting next Jan. 1 if negotiations are successful.
   Mrs. Hills said that her office already had received 200 requests
for accelerated tariff reductions on 2,000 items.
   Peter Murphy, the senior American negotiator on the free trade
agreement, said steel, textiles, chemicals, ``anything you can think
of,'' could be included.
   Mrs. Hills and Crosbie spoke to reporters Monday after the first
meeting of the U.S.-Canada Trade Commission. They are the only
members of the commission, which was created to resolve disputes
arising out of implementation of the accord.
   She termed the first session ``very, very productive,'' referring
in particular to the progress made in setting up a review procedure
for reductions in tariffs.
   About 70 percent of the $155 billion in trade between the United
States and Canada is already duty-free. The new agreement, which won
approval in Congress and the Canadian Parliament last year, is
expected to reduce the cost of doing business in both countries,
helping to spur productivity.
   Mrs. Hills and Crosbie discussed some areas of disagreement
between the two nations including disputes over trade in autos,
lumber, fish and wine.
   Crosbie predicted a complaint by American lumber companies that
Canada was unfairly blocking shipments of U.S. plywood into Canada
would likely be the first issue referred to a settlement board.
   Meanwhile, at a congressional hearing Monday, experts on trade
clashed over the question of whether the United States should have
more free trade accords like the one with Canada. Supporters said
America should explore similar agreements with Mexico and countries
in the Far East.
   ``Not only do free trade agreements provide tangible benefits,
they also demonstrate to a skeptical world ... the benefits provided
by increased trade liberalization,'' said Doral S. Cooper, the chief
negotiator of a U.S.-Israel free trade agreement.
   Mrs. Cooper, a former assistant U.S. trade representative who now
heads an international business consulting firm, said several
countries on the rim of the Pacific Ocean are interested in such
agreements.
   But C. Fred Bergsten, director of the private Institute for
International Economics, told the Senate Finance subcommittee on
international trade that he opposed separate free trade pacts.
   ``The United States cannot possibly achieve the liberalization of
foreign trade barriers it needs from even the most extensive
possible series of bilateral and regional deals,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890314-0248 </DOCNO>
