<FIRST>u f BC-BritainStocks     03-14 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Higher At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher in moderately active
trading at midday Tuesday, defying expectations of a quiet, drifting
market ahead of the introduction of the British government's fiscal
1990 budget in the afternoon.
   Wall Street's strong finish Monday led the London market higher
in the opening hours of trading. But as trading approached midday,
the market came off its best levels and volume slackened.
   ``It's all gone dead,'' one trader said. ``We won't see anything
now until after the budget speech.''
   At 3:30 p.m. in London, Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson
was expected to announce a fiscally tight budget for the year
beginning April 1. Such a budget would help deflate the market's
fears of continued high British inflation and that ``great hope''
buoyed early trading, said one trader.
   At about noon, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 15.3 points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,118.3, though down from the
high of 2,122.7 reached at about 10:15 a.m. (1015 GMT).
   Volume came to 373.9 million shares at midday compared with 270.3
million shares at the same time Monday.
   The 24.11-point rise Monday in the Dow Jones industrial average
to 2,306.25 boosted an already confident London market, dealers said.
   ``We closed Monday when the Dow was already up 16 to 17 points
and it was good to see it finished better than that,'' one London
trader said.
</TEXT>
