<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0830EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EMPSuit     03-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EMP Suit,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Seeks Dismissal of Suit over Electromagnatic Pulse Radiation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. is seeking dismissal of a suit
filed by an employee who said he contracted potentially fatal
leukemia from exposure to electromagnetic pulse radiation on the job
without his knowledge.
   In a motion filed late last week in King County Superior Court,
Boeing attorneys led by V.L. Woolston said the case brought by
Robert Strom, 49, of Kent, a 27-year employee of the aerospace
giant, was ruled out by the same law that established Washington
state's workers compensation system.
   Michael Withey, Strom's attorney, said Monday the case qualified
for an exception under the law.
   ``There are certain well-stated exceptions to the workers'
compensation system,'' he said. ``There's no question in our mind
that Boeing intended to subject Bob Strom to this radiation without
his knowledge.''
   On Friday, Strom's attorneys moved to expand the suit to a class
action covering about 350 employees of Boeing and other companies
who were exposed to the radiation, known as EMP.
   ``Given its broadest possible reading,'' the latest Boeing
document says, the suit claimed the company knowingly subjected
Strom ``to a dangerous form of radiation exposure, deliberately
departed from proper safety procedures and failed to warn him
regarding risks associated with radiation exposure.''
   ``Boeing flatly denies the truth of these scandalous
allegations,'' the document states.
   Withey and the Boeing attorneys have asked Judge Mary Wicks
Brucker to hear their motions April 10.
   Strom, an electronics technician, learned in June 1985 that he
had chronic myelogenous leukemia and filed for workers compensation
benefits the next year. He said he conducted EMP experiments in the
MX missile program.
   His claim was rejected by the state Department of Labor and
Industries, which held that the fatal disease was not the result of
exposure to the radiation. The Board of Industrial Insurance Appeals
upheld that finding twice.
   Last November an industrial insurance appeals judge ruled that
evidence failed to establish that EMP exposure caused the leukemia.
   Strom appealed that ruling to the King County Superior Court, an
action separate from the lawsuit, and Boeing attorneys argued that
the appeal is his proper legal course of action.
</TEXT>
