<DOCNO> AP890314-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Yamanouchi-Shaklee     03-14 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yamanouchi-Shaklee,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Firm Decision To Buy Shaklee Corp. Sends Stock Soaring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by a Japanese pharmaceutical firm
to acquire Shaklee Corp. for $395 million sent the giant direct
sales company's stock soaring.
   Following announcement of the $28 per share, all-cash bid by
Yamanouchi Pharmaceutical Co., Shaklee's stock jumped 9\ to close at
47] on the New York Stock Exchange Monday.
   The stock price set a 52-week high for Shaklee, a San
Francisco-based direct seller of vitamins, household and
personal-care products.
   ``I feel it's a very fair price for shareholders,'' said O. Lee
Tawes III, an analyst with New York-based Oppenheimer &amp; Co. He said
the combination of the bid and special dividend will work out to
about 24 times earnings.
   The bid by the Japanese pharmaceutical manufacturer foiled an
unsolicited offer from a Minneapolis group headed by corporate
raider Irwin Jacobs.
   On Monday, Jacobs said he will not make a new offer for Shaklee.
   Yamanouchi, which last month bought Shaklee's Japanese
subsidiary, will pay cash for Shaklee's estimated 14 million
outstanding shares and intends to retain current management.
   ``I am very pleased that we have joined with Yamanouchi in an
historical accomplishment _ a major acquisition accomplished through
the joint efforts of American management and a major Japanese
company providing substantial benefits to public shareholders,''
said Shaklee President David Chamberlain in a statement.
   Chamberlain, reached later by phone, said the Japanese firm
bought the company because they ``were very excited about the
management'' and liked the company's current direction.
   The $28 per share bid is in addition to a special dividend
recently announced that will provide another $20 per share to
Shaklee stockholders, payable next Monday.
   Yamanouchi, which had net income of $173 million and sales of
$1.42 billion last year, beat out a $40 per share, $528 million cash
offer by Jacobs' group on March 3.
   However, the Jacobs group, which included Minnesota Twins owner
Carl Pohlad, said its offer would be reduced to $20 per share if the
$20 special dividend was paid.
   Under the merger agreement, Shaklee agreed to pay $16 million to
Yamanouchi if Shaklee is purchased by another company.
   Jacobs, reached at his Minneapolis office, said his group had
purchased some two million shares of Shaklee stock at $25-26 per
share and stands to make up to $44 million in profit from the
Yamanouchi deal.
   ``We're disappointed we didn't get the company, but I'd be a fool
if I said I was disappointed financially,'' said Jacobs, a
49-year-old investor who had hoped to mesh Shaklee with Watkins Co.,
a direct seller of household products he bought 10 years ago.
   Jacobs insisted his intention was to buy Shaklee and that his
group was merely outspent by the Japanese company.
   ``We will not be competing on it,'' Jacobs said. ``They have a
chance to do very well. We wish them a lot of success.''
   The merger agreement also provides Yamanouchi the option to buy
15 percent of Shaklee's shares at the tender offer price under
certain circumstances.
   Shaklee had earnings last year of $27.2 million, or $2.05 per
share, on sales of $627 million. Almost half its earnings last year
and more than a quarter of its sales came from the Japanese unit it
sold to Yamanouchi for $350 million.
   Shaklee's board of directors unanimously approved the merger
agreement following a review and recommendation from a special
committee comprised of independent members of Shaklee's board.
</TEXT>
