<FIRST>r f PM-CNW-Japonica     03-14 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CNW-Japonica,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Investment Group Takes 8.8 Percent Stake In CNW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York investment group has bought an 8.8
percent stake in CNW Corp. and may attempt a takeover of the
railroad company.
   Japonica Partners, a limited partnership formed in 1988 by two
former executives of the New York investment firm Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co., told the Securities and Exchange Commission it wants to replace
current CNW directors with its own slate.
   Paul Kazarian, one of the partners, said Monday that Japonica is
``pursuing discussions with financial institutions'' aimed at
financing the takeover.
   CNW Chairman Robert Schmiege said the company will ``carefully
review'' the filing, but added that the Chicago-based railroad
company intends to remain independent.
   CNW is the holding company for the Chicago and North Western
Transportation Co., a leading freight hauler.
   Japonica told the SEC in a filing that it plans to wage a proxy
fight at CNW's annual meeting May 16 in an attempt to elect its own
slate of directors.
   It said that if it is ``successful in obtaining an active role in
the management and@or control of the company,'' it will consider
several possible actions, including taking CNW private,
restructuring the firm and selling certain assets.
   In a letter March 13 to Schmiege, Kazarian accused CNW of
refusing to ``sponsor adequate plans or programs to substantially
enhance stockholder value by closing the value gap between the
company's potential value and its prerumor stock price.''
   Schmiege saw it differently.
   ``Our board of directors and our management has made it very
clear that the interests of all of its constituencies are best
served by CNW remaining an independent company and pursuing its
recently adopted business plan,'' said Schmiege.
   Rumors of a possible takeover have driven CNW stock sharply
higher in recent weeks, gaining almost $8 a share since March 1.
   However, CNW stock fell 87 cents to $38.25 Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange after announcement of the filing.
   Anthony Hatch, an analyst with PaineWebber Group Inc. in New
York, said investors may have been disappointed that the takeover
attempt wasn't being mounted by someone with greater financial clout.
   In partnership with Kazarian, 33, is Michael G. Ledermann, 36, an
attorney with experience in railroad legal matters.
   Kazarian said he headed the team that advised Santa Fe Southern
Pacific on its restructuring but left Goldman before the effort was
completed.
   While at Goldman, Kazarian also worked on Conrail's public
offering and on the spinoff of the Illinois Central Railroad from
Whitman Corp.
   In 1988, CNW posted a 195 percent increase in net income, to $81
million, or $4.34 a share, on revenues of $995.4 million.
</TEXT>
