<FIRST>r f PM-Andersen-ICG     03-14 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Andersen-ICG,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consulting Group Files Countersuit Against Accounting Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an escalaton of a legal battle that began last
year, Information Consulting Group Inc. has filed a $300 million
lawsuit claiming accounting and consulting giant Arthur Andersen &amp;
Co. is out to destroy it.
   In a lawsuit filed Monday in Cook County Circuit Court, ICG
accused Andersen of intimidating prospective ICG employees and
clients, and of using its dominant market position to prevent
competition in the consulting field, violating Illinois' antitrust
laws.
   ``... Andersen has waged a campaign of false statements, coercion
and unfair trade practices against ICG,'' said Gresham T. Brebach
Jr., chief executive officer of New York-based ICG, a consulting
firm formed last year by six ex-Andersen partners.
   ``ICG is entitled to transact business without being intimidated
or otherwise inhibited in its ability to compete,'' Brebach said.
   Andersen said the lawsuit was a desperate attempt by ICG to
survive in a competitive field.
   In addition to the $300 million damages claim, ICG's lawsuit
requests an injunction barring Andersen from further interfering
with ICG's recruitment and business development efforts.
   The legal battle between the two firms began last year, when six
former Arthur Andersen employees, including Brebach, left the agency
to start their own competing firm with the assistance of
London-based Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC.
   Andersen, the nation's largest accounting and consulting firm,
has sued Saatchi and ICG, accusing them of trying to force Andersen
to sell at least part of its consulting business.
   Andersen has since restructured its operations by elevating the
internal status of its consulting partners in an apparent attempt to
end defections of the sort that led to the creation of ICG.
   ICG's lawsuit claims Andersen threatened partners and employees
who were considering leaving the company for ICG, and offered others
extra pay and better jobs if they would stay.
   In a lawsuit filed in October in the New York Supreme Court,
Chicago-based Andersen accused Saatchi and ICG of raiding Andersen
personnel, interfering with Andersen clients and misappropriating
Andersen's confidential and proprietary technology and trade secrets.
   Last week, Andersen amended its lawsuit to include 14 additional
defendants, including Maurice Saatchi, chairman of Saatchi &amp;
Saatchi, the world's largest advertising holding company.
   The amended complaints allege that Maurice Saatchi and former
Andersen personnel now with ICG are participating in various
improper activities to injure Andersen's consulting practice.
   In a lawsuit filed in December, seven former employees of
Andersen, including the six at ICG, charged that Andersen owes them
income, retirement benefits and their capital contributions to
Andersen. The group is seeking a court-supervised accounting to
establish the exact amounts owed them.
</TEXT>
