<FIRST>r f BC-Masco-Universal     03-14 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Masco-Universal,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Masco Corp. Buying Furniture Maker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAYLOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masco Corp., moving to expand its home
furnishings business, will acquire Universal Furniture Ltd. in a
deal approaching $500 million, the companies say.
   Masco and the High Point, N.C.-based furniture manufacturer
announced Monday that both sides had agreed to the merger.
   Masco, which reported $2.4 billion in 1988 sales of furniture,
home furnishings and home improvement products, will give Universal
shareholders 0.95 of a Masco share for each Universal share held,
the companies said.
   Based on Monday's closing price of Masco's stock, the transaction
would have a total value of $484.5 million.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading Monday, Masco shares
closed at $25.50, off 25 cents. Universal closed at $22.75, up
$2.25, in national over-the-counter trading.
   The companies said the agreement had been approved by their
boards and they expected to complete the transaction in three to
four months, subject to approval by regulatory agencies and
Universal shareholders.
   Masco entered the U.S. furniture business three years ago when it
acquired Henredon and Drexel Heritage. Since then, the company has
bought other furniture and home accessory makers and the acquisition
of Universal is its largest home furnishings purchase to date.
   Universal, a leading manufacturer of popular priced furniture and
the largest supplier of dining room furniture in the United States,
has 12,500 employees and reported sales of $472 million in 1988.
</TEXT>
