<HEAD>Soybeans Up; Wheat, Corn Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened slightly higher, but
wheat and corn mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Most of the activity was in the wheat pit, where a round of
profit-taking followed several sessions of rising prices and
life-of-contract highs prompted by the unusually dry weather
recently in the Plains.
   But the profit-taking, coupled with the chance for rain this
weekend, put wheat under pressure at the opening bell. And traders
warned if it continued lower, a spillover effect may bring the beans
and corn down as well.
   ``Even though you've got a bullish (weather) forecast, the market
takes a break once in a while to recover profits,'' said one trader.
``That's what we might be looking at today.''
   At the opening, wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.34{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to \ cent higher, with March at $2.77\; oats were \ cent lower
to { cent higher, with March at $2.10 a bushel; and soybeans were {
cent to 4 cents higher, with March at $7.69.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mostly mixed at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .25 cent lower, with April at 77.95
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .35 cent higher,
with March at 81.25 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent lower to .20
cent higher, with April at 43.80 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .35 cent higher, with March at 38.02 cents
a pound.
