<DOCNO> AP890314-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1303EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Fruit-CyanideReax 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fruit-Cyanide Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grapes, Other Chilean Fruit Disappear From Store Shelves After FDA
Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fruit-Cyanide, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th graf pvs, `In New ...' to UPDATE
with New York wholesale market imposing `quarantine' on Chilean produce.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarket chains and small grocers alike pulled grapes and
other fruit from Chile off the shelves after receiving a warning
from the Food and Drug Administration.
   The FDA, in one of the largest actions of its kind, issued the
warning against eating the fruit on Monday after traces of cyanide
were found in seedless red grapes shipped from the South American
country to Philadelphia.
   The cyanide was confirmed in testing ordered after an anonymous
threat to poison Chilean fruit was telephoned to the U.S. Embassy in
the Chilean capital of Santiago.
   Almost immediately, grocers began began destroying their Chilean
produce or putting it into cold storage until the FDA decides it is
safe to eat.
   The North Carolina-based Food Lion Stores Inc. chain is removing
fruit from Chile from its 581 stores in eight states, said
spokeswoman Dana Clark.
   ``All fruits from Chile will be pulled today and we will follow
the recommendation from the FDA on restocking,'' said Mike Mozingo,
a spokesman for the chain, which has stores in Florida, Georgia,
Tennessee, Maryland, South Carolina, Virginia and Delaware in
addition to North Carolina.
   Larry Rockafield, night manager at Larry's Market north of
Seattle, said 600 pounds of grapes and peaches had been removed to a
cooler for storage with 1,000 pounds of other Chilean fruit that is
being kept off the shelves for now.
   Virtually all the fresh grapes sold in the United States at this
time of year come from Chile, and grapes amount to about two-thirds
of the Chilean fruit sold in the United States, FDA officials said
in Washington.
   Other Chilean fruit sold in the United States at this time of
year includes peaches, blueberries, blackberries, seedless
watermelon, cantaloupe, honeydew melons, raspberries, nectarines,
quince, Granny Smith green apples, cactus pears, pears and plums,
said Sue Hutchcroft, an FDA spokeswoman in Seattle.
   ``We haven't heard from the FDA, but we will be removing all
grapes from display and making refunds for those that were
purchased,'' said John Rhodes, a spokesman for Iowa-based Hy-Vee
Food Stores Inc., which operates 150 stores in seven Midwest states.
Rhodes said the Food Marketing Institute in Washington notified the
company Monday night.
   Ron Morgan, assistant manager at a Des Moines Super Valu store,
said employees removed all grapes regardless of origin. ``I think
ours come from California,'' Morgan said. ``But we're pulling them
off until we're sure.''
   In New York City, health inspectors would not be checking with
stores to make sure the fruit had been removed unless requested to
do so by the FDA, said Marvin Bogner, a spokesman for the city
Department of Health.
   The Hunts Point Market in the Bronx, a major produce distribution
point for area grocers, has imposed ``an airtight quarantine'' on
all produce from Chile, said Tom Kovacevich, chairman of the New
York Produce Trade Association.
   He said the organization had asked the FDA to clarify the problem
and identify what produce from Chile was affected.
   In Birmingham, Ala., Bruno's spokeswoman Beth Dunnaway says that
chain with over 200 stores in the Southeast also is complying. ``We
removed peaches, plums, necatrines, raspberries, and three varieties
of grapes _ red, white and blue,'' she said.
   Steve Sirles, director of produce sales for Richmond, Va.-based
Ukrop's Super Markets, said the Chilean grapes, peaches, plums,
nectarines and pears pulled Monday night from its 17 stores ``leaves
us with nothing. There's no alternative sources.''
   ``You hate to play in the hands of these people (possible
hoaxers), but you have to alert the public,'' said Bill Schroter,
spokesman for Publix supermarkets, Florida's second-largest chain.
</TEXT>
