<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede MIAMI</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pilots Ask That Trustee Run Eastern In Lorenzo's Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with pilots asking for trustee's appointment,
judge agreeing to injunction, pilots union agreeing to pay benefits and
support Eastern pilots. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association today asked a bankruptcy judge to
appoint a trustee to run Eastern Airlines in place of Frank Lorenzo,
charging that the chairman of parent Texas Air Corp. is trying to
strip the airline's assets.
   In other developments in the 11-day-old Machinists strike:
   _ALPA announced in Washington today a $9 million benefits package
for Eastern pilots whose refusal to cross Machinists' picket lines
brought the nation's seventh-largest airline to its knees.
   _The pilots union said members would refuse to fly Eastern planes
or routes that are sold to other airlines unless strike-supporting
Eastern pilots are hired with them.
   _The 8,500-member Machinists union late Monday asked U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland to order Eastern to free strikers'
paychecks from the week before the walkout. The union contends
Eastern is withholding about $9 million in pay and $1 million in
medical claims. A March 23 hearing was scheduled.
   _A federal judge in New York said he would issue an injunction
barring metropolitan-area commuter railroad workers from honoring
Eastern picket lines. U.S. District Judge Robert P. Patterson Jr.,
who signed the order Monday, had issued a temporary restraining
order March 5 against such sympathy strikes.
   _Workers at other airlines were free to honor picket lines by
Eastern strikers as a temporary injunction expired today, but a
spokesman for the Machinists union said he knew of no plans to do
so. Four airlines _ United, USAir, Piedmont and TWA _ had sought an
extension of the injunction against picketing.
   In New York today, the pilots charged that Lorenzo has stripped
Eastern of its assets to support Texas Air and Eastern's sister
carrier, Continental Airlines, and should be barred from running
Eastern during bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``Lorenzo's stripping of Eastern's valuable assets constitutes at
a minimum gross mismanagement and incompetence,'' the union said.
``Either a sophisticated asset stripping is under way or management
is incompetent.
   ``In either event, entrusting Texas Air-controlled management
with reorganizing under Chapter 11 would harm the estate, its
creditors, preferred shareholders and employees.''
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent said a trustee would be unnecessary
because Eastern already has asked the judge to appoint an examiner
to review all transactions between Eastern and the affiliated
airlines during bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``With that protection for debtors and creditors, there doesn't
seem to be a need for a trustee,'' he said.
   Eastern, meanwhile, has boosted its strike-depleted daily
schedule to more than 100 flights and imposed wage cuts more severe
than its proposals that prompted the Machinists strike.
   The Miami-based carrier was scheduled to unveil plans today to
assist travelers who purchased tickets before last week's bankruptcy
filing. The compensation may include vouchers for future Eastern
travel or tickets on other airlines, Eastern said.
   An attorney for the airline also said Eastern would seek court
approval this week for the $365 million sale of its Northeast
shuttle to developer Donald Trump.
   Representatives of Eastern's pilots and Machinists unions said
they would challenge the deal. A Machinists official also said the
union was working on its own bankruptcy reorganization plan, which
could include a buyout of Eastern.
   With service restored between Miami and New York, Montreal and
San Juan, Puerto Rico, Eastern reported 104 domestic and Latin
American flights Monday.
   Eastern has said it hopes to build its schedule to 140 flights
before the weekend, a fraction of its pre-strike level of 1,040
flights a day. The airline has said about 200 of its 3,600 pilots
are crossing picket lines.
   The pilots union ridiculed the company's service plans. ``We
believe they will be significantly hampered in ever reaching these
stated goals because they don't have the pilots,'' Eastern pilots
spokesman Ron Cole said in Miami.
   Henry Duffy, pilots union president, said member pilots from 47
airlines would be assessed an average of $300 a month to support the
Eastern pilots and the union would draw from its $37 million strike
fund as the money is collected.
   ``All 41,000 pilots will reach deep into their pockets to help
the Eastern pilots who are reaching deep within themselves to cope
with the personal and professional risks of their action,'' Duffy
said.
   The wage cuts Eastern imposed Monday will reduce the wages of any
Machinists who cross picket lines and provide still lower pay to any
workers hired to replace strikers, officials said.
   ``This package would make Eastern the lowest-paid in the industry
(compared with major carriers),'' said Wally Haber, a general
chairman for the Machinists union. ``I think it's obvious they don't
want anybody to come back to work.''
   Eastern had sought $125 million in concessions from the
Machinists before the strike to stem losses the airline estimates
have quadrupled to $4 million a day since the strike began.
</TEXT>
