<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Close Higher After Budget Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose sharply Tuesday, strengthened by what
market investors welcomed as an inflation-fighting budget plan from
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
   The market had been expecting Lawson to present a budget
comprised of relatively modest tax cuts. His plan was more fiscally
cautious than economists had forecast.
   Dealers noted that Lawson had left unchanged at 25 percent the
standard rate of tax, indicating restraint on the part of the
chancellor from further boosting consumer spending. The market had
widely expected a drop in the rate to 24 percent.
   Total taxes announced by Lawson will reduce revenue in fiscal
1990 by less than 2 billion pounds, the chancellor said. This
compares with expectations of a total cost of between 2 billion and
3 billion pounds.
   At the close the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 22.4 points, or 1.05 percent, at 2,125.4.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was up 21.7 points at
1,761.1.
   The Financial Times 500-share index closed at 1,211.20, up 10.15.
   Volume totaled 587.1 million shares, up from 496.0 million shares
Monday.
</TEXT>
