<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CraySupercomputers     03-14 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cray Supercomputers,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cray Expands Supercomputer Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc. has expanded its latest
line of supercomputers to include 19 machines priced from $5 million
to $23.7 million each, the company announced Tuesday.
   The most powerful version of the Cray Y-MP computers will be able
to perform up to 2.7 billion calculations per second. The Cray 3,
which is still on the drawing boards and is based on unproven chip
technology, could reach speeds of 16 billion calculations per second.
   Cray is the world's biggest maker of supercomputers, which are
used for high-powered scientific and engineering work. Its rivals
include Control Data Corp. and Japan's Fujitsu Ltd. and Hitachi Ltd.
   The first Cray Y-MP model was introduced in February 1988, an
improvement over the Cray X-MP line. The largest Y-MP model, with
eight processors, will be about three times more powerful than the
largest X-MP and about 30 times more powerful than the Cray-1 system
introduced in 1976, said Marcelo Gumucio, president and chief
operating officer of Cray Research.
   He said the new product line will provide Cray customers with the
potential for convenient upgrades. Some are already available, but
the versions with the maximum memory won't be available until the
second quarter of 1990, the company said.
</TEXT>
