<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf, `The Dow ...' to change to 2 p.m. sted 1 p.m.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rebounded in featureless trading
today, as investors awaited Wednesday's merchandise trade deficit
report.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 5.71 points at
2,311.96 at 2 p.m. EST. The blue-chip indicator had risen 3.39
points an hour after the opening bell but slid throughout the
morning.
   Advancing issues barely outpaced decliners on the New York Stock
Exchange, with 673 issues up, 657 down and 568 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 99.8 million shares.
   Stocks got an early boost as they tracked a rally in the bond
market following release of February retail sales figures.
   The government reported that retail sales last month declined 0.4
percent from January. That signaled good news for the bond market
because it suggested an easing of consumer spending and reduced
worries about inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income
securities such as notes and bonds.
   By mid-morning, the enthusiasm fizzled and the stock market
drifted lower in the face of a weakening dollar and as institutional
investors turned their attention to Wednesday's government report on
the merchandise trade deficit for January.
   ``Institutional investors are sitting on the sidelines to watch
for tomorrow's trade figures,'' said Philip Puccio, senior vice
president at Dillon, Read &amp; Co.
   Volume, which was light at the opening, remained lackluster as
the trading day progressed.
   ``Volume is light because of the number of economic figures due
out this week,'' said John Burnett, senior vice president of
Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette. ``The market is acting like the
numbers are going to be good but it's a skittish market.''
   Some economists have predicted that the U.S. trade deficit for
January will narrow from $10.23 billion in December to about $9.7
billion.
   But investors also are awaiting other information on the
economy's health following last Friday's report showing unemployment
fell to a 15-year low in February. That report sent inflationary
shivers through the market as investors reasoned that strains on the
capacity of the labor force might stir inflation and result in
higher interest rates.
   Reports on housing sales, industrial production and wholesale
prices are due out later in the week.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.08 at 166.08.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index advanced
0.03 to 330.57.
   Among actively traded issues on the NYSE, Citicorp was up \ at
26}, Philip Morris advanced 1\ at 120 and Generaly Electric gained [
to 45}.
   IBM was down [ at 118}, Ford Motor had lost ] to 50] and At&amp;T was
unchanged at 31|.
</TEXT>
