<FIRST>r f AM-EEC-USFarm     03-14 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EEC-US Farm,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Agriculture Chief Sharply Criticizes U.S. in Farm Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top European agriculture official
Tuesday rebuked the United States for pressing Europeans to make
sharp changes in their farm policies while failing to do likewise at
home.
   Ray MacSharry, agriculture chief for the 12-nation European
Economic Community, urged the United States to recognize in trade
negotiations the measures adopted by the trading bloc to curb
production and farm subsidies.
   ``Reductions were not achieved without considerable effort on our
part and sacrifice by the farming community...'' he said in a speech
to the International Chamber of Commerce in Brussels. ``Others
should follow our lead instead of stepping in to profit from our
efforts.''
   He also said, ``We should ensure that the sacrifices of one
negotiating party are not stripped of their value by the opportunism
of another.''
   MacSharry appeared to be trying to put the United States on the
defensive in a dispute between the two sides over an American demand
for sharp cuts in European farm subsidies. The fight has stalled the
latest round of international trade negotiations.
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter and U.S. Trade
Representative Carla Hills met over the weekend with MacSharry and
Frans Andriessen, the EEC's top trade official, to try to resolve
the issue.
   The international trade talks, sponsored by the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade, resume April 5 in Geneva.
   MacSharry said he told Yeutter and Mrs. Hills: ``We must get
credit for our reductions in support.''
   Last year European leaders limited the maxium annual amount spent
on price guarantees over five years. U.S. officials contend the
measures were not enough to fix a fundamentally flawed system and
want more long-term changes.
   MacSharry reiterated the EEC's position that it ``cannot
subscribe to revolutionary changes of its policy.''
   ``We...are asked not only to freeze but also to reduce
agricultural support,'' he said. ``My reaction to this is that the
reductions we have achieved already in some of our suprlus products
have been, to put it mildly, impressive.''
   He said quotas imposed in 1984 have cut milk production by 11
million metric tons and meant the reduction of 3.6 million head of
dairy cattle in 1986-88.
   As a result, he said the EEC has contributed to stabilizing a
sector marked by overproduction and low world prices.
   ``It is, therefore, to say the least, unfortunate that, in 1988,
increased production in the United States, Canada and Australia
alone has offset reductions achieved in the community,'' he said.
   The EEC provides costly subsidies to farmers through guaranteed
prices for many crops. It also gives exporters help so more
expensive European farm prdoucts can compete with lower prices on
the world market.
   The United States complains the export subsidies have helped the
community increase its share of the world market. It has fought back
with its own Export Enhancement Program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
