<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0167</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Volume was light and the absence of fresh news left most of the
markets trading in narrow ranges. An early bout of profit-taking
pressured wheat and it never rebounded very far, despite several
recent sessions of rising prices prompted by the unusually dry
weather.
   Although the 30-day forecast from the National Weather Service
called for drier-than-normal conditions in winter wheat regions,
some predictions of rain this weekend dampened most traders' buying
moods.
   On the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 1} cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.36{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $2.78{; oats were \
cent lower to { cent higher, with March at $2.09{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher, with March at $7.69.
