<FIRST>r f AM-PoultryLosses     03-14 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poultry Losses,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oklahoma Snowstorm Killed 4 Million Chickens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The snow and ice storm earlier this month
caused as much as $100 million in losses in three states and
probably will force up chicken prices this year across the country,
officials said Tuesday.
   The storm, which officials have called one of the worst blows to
the poultry industry on record, destroyed nearly 600 chicken houses
in Oklahoma, Arkansas and Missouri, said Bill Roenigk of the
National Broiler Council in Washington.
   Roenigk said one estimate put total damage in the three states at
$100 million.
   A report from Bart Brorsen, executive director of the Oklahoma
Agriculture Stabilization and Conservation Service, said the storm
caused $21.8 million in damage to equipment and buildings in the
state's poultry industry, mostly in 10 eastern counties.
   The report did not put a price on the 3.9 million chickens or
1,201 head of livestock reported lost.
   Gov. Henry Bellmon has asked Secretary of Agriculture Clayton
Yeutter to designate 16 counties as disaster areas.
   Roenigk, in a telephone interview, said the damage to poultry
will cause the national retail price of whole broiler chickens to
increase 2 to 4 cents a pound. The average price for whole broilers
in 1988 was 85 cents, he said.
   Roenigk said many poultry farmers were insured for wind and fire
damage, but not snow and ice.
</TEXT>
