<FIRST>r f AM-Fruit-Cyanide-Growers 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit-Cyanide-Growers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Growers Emphasize Fruit Safety In Wake Of Chilean Scare</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts thruout to UPDATE with comments from pear group and
editing. ADDs byline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fruit-Cyanide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. fruit growers and distributors tried to reassure consumers
Tuesday that their products were safe as grocers nationwide stopped
selling Chilean grapes and other produce from that country because
of an apparent cyanide poisoning attempt.
   Meanwhile, industry spokesmen said retailers and wholesalers
hoped to disassociate their products from those imported from Chile
by putting up ``Produced in the U.S.A.'' signs.
   ``We want to make it clear that this Chilean thing is a radical
act that has nothing to do with growers in California and it's not a
pesticide-related incident,'' said Marilyn Watkins, spokeswoman for
Sacramento, Calif.-based Blue Anchor Inc., one of the nation's
largest fruit distributors.
   The Food and Drug Administration urged Tuesday that all fruit
from Chile be removed from U.S. markets after traces of cyanide were
found in seedless red grapes shipped to Philadelphia from the South
American country. It also asked Americans to discard all fruit
unless they know it isn't from Chile.
   The cyanide poison was confirmed in testing ordered after an
anonymous threat to poison Chilean fruit was telephoned to th apples, cactus
pears, pears
and plums.
   However, industry experts say most of the winter pears on the
stands are from the Northwest.
   ``I hope this (scare) doesn't affect the remainder of our
product,'' said Maggie Andre, a spokeswoman for the Portland,
Ore.-based Oregon Washington California Pear Bureau.
   She said all anjou pears are domestically produced, while part of
the bosc variety of pears is grown in the United States and part in
Chile. None of the bartlett pears are grown domestically.
   Andre said retailers and wholesalers nationwide ``are indicating
they're going to put signs up on all of their produce as saying,
`Produced in the U.S.A.'''
</TEXT>
