<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0337</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were mostly unchanged in lackluster
trading today after a seesaw session in which investors were
reluctant to make commitments ahead of Wednesday's merchandise trade
deficit report.
   The market opened relatively strong on the heels of a bond market
rally following an unexpected 0.4 percent drop in retail sales last
month.
   ``The consensus was looking for flat to up 0.4 percent and that
helped relieve concern that the economy is overheating,'' said
Alfred E. Goldman, vice president for A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
   The report stimulated speculation that consumer spending has
eased and that inflation is beginning to subside.
   But by mid-morning, the enthusiasm fizzled and the stock market
drifted lower in the face of a weakening dollar, which suggested the
possibility of higher inflation, further credit-tightening by the
Federal Reserve and higher interest rates.
   After staging a brief rally around midday, the market began
drifting with little apparent direction.
   Volume remained light with institutional investors taking to the
sidelines to await the U.S. merchandise trade deficit report for
January, analysts said. The report is scheduled to be released on
Wednesday.
   ``Basically, after some upward stimulation and feeling that maybe
the economy is slowing the market has gone back into hybernation to
await the trade figures,'' Goldman said.
   Some economists have forecast a narrowing of the U.S. merchandise
trade deficit in January to about $9.7 billion from $10.23 billion
in December.
   In addition, investors were awaiting reports later in the week on
housing sales, industrial production and wholesale prices to
determine whether the Federal Reserve's tight credit policy is
working.
   Last Friday's data showing unemployment fell to a 15-year low in
February sent inflationary shivers through the market as investors
reasoned that strains on the capacity of the labor force might stir
inflation and result in higher interest rates. The market bounced
back from a brief sell-off but volume has remained light.
