<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilots Seek Trustee To Run Eastern; Judge Approves Ticketholder Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6 grafs for 10th graf pvs, In disputing... to UPDATE with
details of Machinists filing; Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Texas Air...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots asked a federal judge
Tuesday to appoint a trustee to run the carrier, alleging that Frank
Lorenzo, chairman of parent Texas Air Corp., was stripping Eastern's
assets to bolster affiliated carriers.
   The Air Line Pilots Association stated in papers filed in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court that Lorenzo systematically has funneled Eastern
assets to Texas Air and Continental Airlines in a plan dating to the
1986 acquisition of Eastern.
   In other deveopments in Eastern's Chapter 11 proceedings, U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland approved Eastern's plan to
compensate holders of unused tickets while striking Machinists asked
the judge to order payment of $10 million in back wages and medical
claims.
   Lifland set an April 7 hearing on the trustee motion.
   ``Lorenzo's stripping of Eastern's valuable assets constitutes at
a minimum gross mismanagement and incompetence,'' Farrell
Kupersmith, a financial adviser to the pilots, stated in court
documents. ``Either a sophisticated asset stripping is under way or
management is incompetent.
   ``In either event, entrusting Texas Air-controlled management
with reorganizing under Chapter 11 would harm the estate, its
creditors, preferred shareholders and employees.''
   Losing about $4 million a day during a walkout by mechanics,
pilots and flight attendants that began March 4, Eastern sought
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy law
last Thursday. Any substantial corporate changes by Eastern now are
subject to approval by Lifland.
   Union officials and some industry analysts have maintained that
Lorenzo plans to sell off much of Eastern's $4.5 billion in assets.
Under one scenario, he would cut the airline down and merge it with
Continenal.
   Lorenzo has said he intends to run a scaled-down Eastern
separately and denies he is stripping Eastern's assets to funnel
money into Texas Air or Continental.
   But the court motion cites several examples of asset transfers
the union says weakened Eastern, including:
   _Transfer of a national computerized reservation system to Texas
Air for $100 million shortly after Texas Air bought the ailing
carrier. The motion says Eastern recently valued the system at $750
million.
   _A $40 million loan to Continental last spring at a time when
Eastern applied for a $105 million pension contribution waiver.
   _A $22 million payment to Continental for strike-related services
in December 1987 and another $19 million payment last fall for
similar services that have not been used.
   _Eastern's $11 million sale to Continental of 11 Newark
International Airport gates allegedly worth twice as much.
   _The pending sale of the Northeast shuttle to Donald Trump for
$365 million, which the pilots claim will result in a $30 million to
$40 million reduction in operating cash flow for Eastern.
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent said a trustee would be unnecessary
because Eastern already has asked the judge to appoint an examiner
to review all transactions between Eastern and the affiliated
airlines during bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``With that protection for debtors and creditors, there doesn't
seem to be a need for a trustee,'' he said.
   Eastern President Phil Bakes said Eastern requested an examiner
to ``dispel the misconceptions being promoted by its unions that the
affiliated transactions are somehow not necessarily in the best
interest of Eastern.''
   Separately, Lifland approved Eastern's plan to reimburse
customers with unused tickets, which are worth an estimated $200
million.
   Under the plan, passengers would receive a replacement ticket
when Eastern begins flying the canceled route, plus a companion
ticket at a 50 percent discount. Alternatively, the airline would
allow passengers to transfer 25 percent of the value of the old
ticket on each of four new ones.
   Also Tuesday, Lifland set a March 23 hearing on a Machinists
request to order Eastern to release pre-strike paychecks. The motion
says Eastern is unfairly withholding about $9 million in pay and $1
million in medical claims, said Robert Clayman, an attorney for the
union.
   The back pay covers Feb. 27 to March 5. Clayman said paychecks
issued last Wednesday _ a day before Eastern sought bankruptcy
protection _ were not honored and no other checks were issued.
   ``In light of the fact that active employees have been paid for
work performed prior to the bankruptcy, the IAM employees should be
treated in the same manner,'' he said. ``Eastern received the
benefit of that labor and now they're not paying for it.''
</TEXT>
