<FIRST>r f AM-ColdwellBanker     03-14 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coldwell Banker,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investor Group Nears Purchase of Coldwell Banker's Commercial Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group that includes Coldwell Banker
Commercial Group management is nearing purchase of the unit from
parent Sears, Roebuck and Co. for about $300 million, a source close
to the negotiations said Tuesday.
   In announcing restructuring plans last Oct. 31, the retailing
giant said it intended to sell Coldwell Banker's commercial unit,
while retaining ownership of the residential unit.
   ``We can confirm Sears is in the process of selling the
commercial unit,'' company spokesman Doug Fairweather said Tuesday.
   ``It's been part of the plan all along to sell off some parts and
strengthen that part of our business that focuses on the consumer,''
he said, but declined to elaborate further.
   Sears announced Monday that it was reducing the number of
in-store Dean Witter Reynolds financial-services outlets from about
300 to about 150, and converting virtually all Coldwell Banker
outlets into marketing and referral booths.
   The investment banker in the Coldwell Banker deal is
Washington-based Carlyle Group, whose co-chairman is former
Secretary of Defense Frank Carlucci. Carlucci also served previously
as chairman of Sears' exporting arm, Sears World Inc., from 1983 to
1986.
   The Hillman family of Pittsburgh also is to be involved in
ownership of the new unit, along with current top Coldwell Banker
Commercial staff led by the unit's president Gary Beban, said the
source close to the negotiations, who declined to be identified.
Beban is a former professional football player.
   Coldwell Banker Commercial group, which operates 99 offices
around the county and employs about 5,200 people, accounted for
revenues of $460 million last year.
</TEXT>
