<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-14 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended weaker against most key
currencies in quiet trading Tuesday following the release of what
foreign exchange dealers called disappointing U.S. retail sales
figures.
   Gold prices strengthened. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid of $395.50 a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EST, up
$2.50 from Monday's late bid.
   Earl I. Johnson, a currency dealer at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in
Chicago, said the dollar was depressed by a Commerce Department
report showing February retail sales had fallen 0.4 percent.
   ``It was slightly disappointing,'' Johnson said. ``The market had
expected sales to go up 0.5 percent.''
   Johnson said the decline lessened the possibility of higher
interest rates, which often helps firm the dollar.
   Dealers said domestic trading was quiet in advance of Wednesday's
release of the January merchandise trade report.
   Overseas, traders said the British pound gained from the dollar's
weakness. Sterling also was buoyed by the national budget for the
1989-1990 fiscal year announced to the House of Commons by
Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
   In London, one pound cost $1.7170, more expensive for buyers than
Monday's late $1.7125. Sterling fetched $1.7280 in New York, up from
$1.71295.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar rose to 129.92 Japanese yen from
129.57 late Monday. The dollar traded at 129.85 yen in London, and
at 129.79 yen in New York, down from 130.175.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's late
rates, included: 1.86075 West German marks, down from 1.8675; 1.5930
Swiss francs, down from 1.5970; 1.19385 Canadian dollars, down from
1.19815; 6.3065 French francs, down from 6.3252; and 1,365.75
Italian lire, down from 1,369.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe included: 1.8630 West German marks,
down from 1.8669; 1.5935 Swiss francs, down from 1.5965; 6.3125
French francs, down from 6.3230; 2.1010 Dutch guilders, down from
2.1040; 1,366.12 Italian lire, down from 1,367.40; 1.1970 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1981.
   Traders said gold prices rose because of internal market
influences and firmer prices for oil. The gold market historically
has tracked energy prices because of their impact on inflation.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $396.20 a troy ounce, up from Monday's $394.40.
   Gold settled in London at a bid $395.75 an ounce, up from
$392.25. The closing price in Zurich was $395.25 an ounce, up from
$392.75.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $395.37 an ounce, up
from $394.85.
   Silver prices also gained ground. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery settled at $6.176 a troy ounce, up from
$6.078 Monday. Silver rose in London to $6.17 an ounce from $6.02.
</TEXT>
