<FIRST>r f AM-DishwasherRecall     03-14 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dishwasher Recall,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dishwasher Switch Can Cause Fire, Whirlpool Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp. is making a third
attempt to reach owners of dishwashers with pushbutton selector
switches that can cause fires, the company said Monday.
   Whirlpool said 75,000 undercounter dishwashers sold nationwide
from 1986 until July 1988 were made with a switch that could arc
after exposure to moisture and start a fire.
   Forty fires have been reported. No one was seriously injured in
the blazes, but two people were treated for smoke inhalation,
Whirlpool spokeswoman Joy Schrage said.
   After two alerts in cooperation with the U.S. Consumer Product
Safety Commission, in July and August 1988, the switches have been
replaced on 56,000 of the machines. Owners of the remaining 18,000
have not been heard from, Schrage said.
   The dishwasher model numbers are on the right front edge of the
tub. The affected models are DU7400XS-0, DU7600S-0, DU7800XS-0,
DU9000XR-0 and DU9000XR-1, the company said.
   Whirlpool said owners should not use the machine, should leave
the door unlatched and call 1-800-541-5746 to arrange for free
repair.
</TEXT>
