<DOCNO> AP890314-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 0002EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ShipSale     03-14 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ship Sale,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rouge Steel To Sell Ore Carriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rouge Steel Co. will sell its three Great Lakes
ore freighters, ending its 65-year involvement in the steamship
business, the Ford Motor Co. subsidiary said Monday.
   Rouge Steel said it had agreed to sell the William Clay Ford, the
Benson Ford and the out-of-service Henry Ford II for an undisclosed
price to Lakes Shipping Co. Inc., an affiliate of Interlake
Steamship Co. of Cleveland.
   The steel company will then negotiate a contract with Interlake
Steamship for transportation of ore, spokesman Bill Peacock said.
   Rouge Steel began producing steel in 1919, began operating its
own ore freighters in 1924 and had as many as five freighters in the
1950s, Peacock said. The company has 4,000 employees and sells about
40 percent of its steel to Ford Motor Co.
   Rouge Steel has experienced the same slackening of demand that
has hit the rest of the steel industry, and in the past two years it
sold the freighter Ernest R. Breech and mothballed the Henry Ford II.
   With two ships operating, the company was too vulnerable to any
problem with either one, and elected to contract for ore
transportation, Peacock said.
</TEXT>
