<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-14 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Continue Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices climbed further in light
trading Tuesday amid more signs that OPEC members are honoring
production quotas.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, rose 26 cents
to settle at $19.29 a barrel. On Monday, the April contract picked
up 53 cents, closing above $19 a barrel for the first time since
Jan. 19.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also advanced Tuesday.
The April contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.34 cent to settle at
53.50 cents a gallon, while heating oil edged up 0.05 cent to close
at 52.40 cents a gallon.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior broker with E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., partly attributed the gains to news that Saudi Arabia
was cutting back on crude shipments to Japan by 45,000 barrels a day.
   The report sparked buying on Far East oil markets, which in turn
influenced prices in Europe and New York, Lebow said.
   Traders interpreted the development as further evidence the
Saudis, the largest producers in the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, were abiding by their 4.5 million-barrel daily
quota for crude output, Lebow said.
   OPEC members set an overall ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day
late last year. Analysts have said the cartel appeared to be holding
to its quota.
   Lebow said some buying Tuesday came on momentum from gains a day
earlier, which were partly attributed to a fire that forced the
closing of seven Norwegian crude oil fields in the North Sea.
   The seven fields produce an average of 250,000 barrels a day of
crude oil and about 1 billion cubic feet of gas.
</TEXT>
