<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 1835EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls-Congress     03-14 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Congress,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls-Deposits, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-S&amp;L-Rescues listed on news digest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee,
as an alternative to President Bush's proposal, suggested Tuesday
the government spend ``increments of $10 billion'' over the next few
months to close insolvent savings and loan institutions.
   Sen. Don Riegle, D-Mich., asked congressional auditors to work up
numbers on the possible effects of putting the bulk of the
$100-billion-plus bailout of the S&amp;L industry on the fiscal 1989
budget instead of dragging it out over 30 years through the
elaborate off-budget financing scheme proposed by Bush.
   Riegle complained that the driving force behind Bush's proposal
was a desire to prevent the S&amp;L crisis from having an impact on the
annual deficit-reduction targets in the 1985 Gramm-Rudman law, which
requires a balanced federal budget by 1993.
   The Bush administration already has conceded that the government
will exceed the $136 billion target deficit for fiscal 1989, which
ends Sept. 30, by $35 billion.
   But the administration has been adamant in insisting that the
fiscal 1990 target defict of $100 billion be met, even if it's done
by stretching the taxpayer share of the S&amp;L bailout costs over 30
years at an estimated extra cost to them of $3 billion to $6 billion.
   ``This may be another way to work with the Gramm-Rudman
restraints and at the same time save the taxpayers an awfully lot of
money,'' Riegle said.
   It also would likely swell the projected fiscal 1989 deficit of
$170 billion _ which already is above the $155 billion deficit last
year _ back to the $200-billion-plus annual deficits of the mid
1980s as well as the total federal debt, which now exceeds $2.6
trillion.
   Riegle said his proposal, being pushed in the House by a member
of its banking committee, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., would
encourage the government to liquidate more insolvent S&amp;Ls
immediately rather than attempt to keep their doors open through
subsidized mergers.
   He described it as a ``cleaner'' and, in the long run, less
expensive, alternative. That view was expressed last week by William
S. Niskanean, a former economic adviser to then-President Reagan.
   ``Then we wouldn't be forced to make these mergers, which are
very expensive,'' Riegle said.
   That view was bolstered Tuesday by the congressional General
Accounting Office, which said it would have been cheaper in a third
of the government's 1988 spree of S&amp;L sales to have shut the
institutions and pay off depositors rather than sell the thrifts to
new owners.
   Last year government regulators spent about $37 billion closing,
selling or shoring up 222 insolvent thrifts _ $28.4 billion of it on
subisidies to the new owners of 179 of the them.
   Comptroller General and GAO chief Charles A. Bowsher told the
Senate Banking Committee that the the cash cost of those deals,
including some $7 billion to $8 billion in tax breaks, will total at
least $62 billion over the next few years and could go higher if
their condition worsens.
   ``Most of these (assistance) contracts are for up to 10 years,''
he said. ``That's what worries everyone.''
   In nine of 12 government-subsidized mergers that the GAO examined
in detail, the new owners will be able to use the guarantees against
losses and tax breaks to recoup the money they invested in an
average of three years, Bowsher said.
   While generally endorsing Bush's S&amp;L plan, Bowsher said it
represents the first time that the government would be making and
``open-ended'' commitment of funds with no cap on what eventually
might have to be spent. Some experts have put that amount in excess
of $200 billion over the next 10 years.
   Republicans defended the handling of last year's S&amp;L sales by the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board and its chairman, M. Danny Wall, who
would retain his post in the Bush plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
