<FIRST>u f AM-LincolnSavings-Offer     03-14 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lincoln Savings-Offer,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Executives Offer To Buy Lincoln Savings and Loan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of American Continental Corp. executives,
including a former congressman from California, has offered to buy
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, one of the nation's largest
thrifts.
   Lincoln, a 29-branch, Irvine, Calif.-based thrift which lost
about $36 million in the first nine months of 1988, is the principal
subsidiary of American Continental.
   Under two purchase plans, the Phoenix developer would sell
Lincoln but buy back a resort and a hotel here, plus Lincoln's 20
percent interest in General Oriental Investments Ltd., a
London-based holding company.
   Former Rep. John Rousselot, R-Calif., hired last summer to find a
buyer for Lincoln, and three other American Continental executives
form the new group of would-be investors.
   Rousselot said he met Monday with the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board in Washington to discuss the offer of about $289 million, made
Friday.
   The Rousselot group's offer is the third made for the $6 billion
thrift in a year, leading to industry speculation that American
Continental was trying to buy time with federal regulators critical
of Lincoln's risky investments in high-yield bonds and undeveloped
property.
   ``If you can say to the regulators, `We're doing something or
trying to sell the institution,' that gives you a reason to stall
all regulatory action,'' said Bert Ely, a thrift analyst in
Alexandria, Va.
   Rousselot denied the allegation, saying Charles Keating, American
Continental's chairman, is ready to sell.
   ``He wants out of the savings and loan business, like today if we
could arrange it,'' Rousselot said.
   He said his group's offer was definitive and could close by the
end of the month.
   Other partners are American Continental lawyers Ronald Stoll and
David Thompson and Jack Atchison, former partner in an accounting
firm who joined the company last spring as a vice president.
</TEXT>
