<FIRST>u f AM-HollyFarms     03-14 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Calls shareholder Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. will hold a shareholders'
meeting April 14 to consider ConAgra Inc.'s offer to buy the rival
poultry processor in a $1 billion stock swap.
   Approval of the ConAgra bid would block attempts by another
poultry company, Tyson Foods Inc., of Springdale, Ark., to take over
Holly Farms for $1.1 billion. Tyson has offered Holly Farms
shareholders $60 a share in cash and pledged to pay $63.50 a share
if Holly Farms management cooperates with a buyout.
   Holly Farms set its shareholders' meeting for 10 a.m. CST at the
Marriott Hotel here.
   However, Tyson has asked a state court in Delaware _ where Holly
Farms is incorporated _ to bar the meeting. Tyson also asked the
court to nullify the ConAgra-Holly Farms deal or to hold a hearing
on the appropriateness of the proposal, which provides for ConAgra
to buy certain Holly Farms assets even if their merger falls through.
   Jim Blair, a lawyer for Tyson, declined comment Tuesday on Holly
Farm's announcement.
   Tyson has been trying since last October to buy Holly Farms.
Doing so would allow Tyson to maintain its standing as the largest
poultry processor in the country.
   The proposed ConAgra-Holly Farms merger calls of a swap of 1.875
to 2 shares of ConAgra stock for each of Holly Farms' 18.1 million
outstanding shares.
   Based on expected market prices, the ConAgra bid amounts to about
$59 a share for Holly Farms stock, said Napoleon Overton, an analyst
with Morgan Keegan &amp; Co. of Memphis.
   ``It's still my opinion that Tyson will probably end up with
Holly Farms because they have an all-cash offer and they're willing
to pay more than ConAgra has so far offered,'' Overton said.
   Throughout Tyson's takeover attempt, ConAgra has declined to
discuss any increase in its bid, but Overton said an increase still
is possible.
   ``If they go to court and the judge determines that Holly Farms
is not bound by the terms of that merger agreement and the
asset-option lockup is invalid, then and only then would ConAgra
have any incentive to raise its current bid,'' he said.
</TEXT>
