<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-14 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Gain Again Amid Reports Saudis Cut Supplies to Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures gained for the second straight session Tuesday
after reports that one major oil producer, Saudi Arabia, cut
supplies to the Japanese by 30 percent, and another, Qatar, had
halted production of 150,000 barrels a day while performing
maintenance on its facilities.
   On other markets, silver rose strongly; cocoa prices climbed amid
concerns a labor stoppage in Brazil could affect supplies; and grain
and soybean prices were mixed.
   Crude oil futures settled 14 cents lower to 26 cents higher on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, with the contract for delivery in
April at $19.29. Heationg oil was .01 cent to .34 cent higher, with
April at 52.40 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .10 cent to
.63 cent higher, with April at 53.50 cents a gallon.
   The 26-cent climb in the spot month followed a 53-cent jump
Monday that left crude oil prices at a 16-month high.
   ``The market was up on a confluence of factors,'' said Nauman
Barakat, vice president for energy investments at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., New York. ``But very important was the Saudis
cutting back the Japanese.
   ``The 30 percent was significantly larger than the Japanese
anticipated and about twice the cuts they absorbed in the first
quarter,'' he added.
   Barakat and other analysts pointed to indications that worldwide
supplies were tightening; confirmation Monday that non-OPEC
producers would go ahead with unilateral cuts of almost 300,000
barrels a day; better compliance with assigned quotas some OPEC
producers, notably the Saudis; and a temporary shutdown of some
facilities in Qatar.
   Additionally, a weekly estimate by the American Petroleum
Institute issued after the close of business Tuesday showed a
reduction in stocks from the previous weeks.
   ``We've got both fundamental and technical support for an
uptrend,'' said Barakat.
   Some traders viewed the rise in oil prices as another piece in
the inflationary puzzle, and the precious metals benefited from that
support as well as concerns that recent political rumblings in South
Africa may eventually affect supplies of platinum.
   Platinum climbed $6.90 to $7.10 on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, with March at $549.30 a troy ounce. Gold was $1.50 to
$1.90 higher at the Comex, with March at $396.20 a troy ounce; and
silver was 9.5 cents to 12.4 cents higher, with March at $6.176 a
troy ounce.
   ``Silver's made the best bounce off the recent lows, but it's
still quite cheap relative to the other metals and it's drawing most
of the speculative interest,'' said Steve Chronowitz, director of
futures research for Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co., New York.
   But another analyst called the trend worrisome.
   ``If silver is taking the lead ... we could see trouble because
there are already considerable supplies,'' said Rich Levine, a
precious metals analyst at Elders Futures Inc., New York. ``Gold and
platinum already seem to be losing energy at these prices and if
silver breaks _ and my hunch is it will _ it could mean we've seen a
top for gold and platinum as well.''
   Cocoa prices rallied sharply as a widespread strike by Brazil's
labor unions affected shipments out of South America, as well as
news that sometimes-quarrelsome cocoa producers were making progress
in talks aimed at establishing supply levels.
   Volume was on light on the Chicago Board of Trade and the absence
of fresh news left the grain and soybean markets trading in very
narrow ranges.
   An early bout of profit-taking pressured wheat at the opening
bell and it never recovered, despite several recent sessions of
rising prices prompted by the unusually dry weather recently in the
Plains.
   Wheat was 2 cents lower to 3 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in March at $4.36{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1\
cents higher, with March at $2.78\; oats were \ cent lower to { cent
higher, with March at $2.09{ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent
lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.69.
   Livestock futures were mostly lower and prok future mixed at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent to .70 cent lower, with April at 77.42
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .17 cent lower to .05 cent higher,
with March at 81.15 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent lower to .13
cent higher, with April at 43.75 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .20 cent lower to .22 cent higher, with March at 38.25
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
