<HEAD>Domestic Auto Sales Slump In Early March</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs, bgng Chrysler sold... to CORRECT year to
date decline to 21.4 percent sted 20.9 percent, reflecting change made
by Chrysler. Picks up 12th graf, Chrysler's light...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales were down by 14.8
percent in early March from the same period last year as U.S.-based
automakers continued their slow 1989 sales start, the companies said
Tuesday.
   Automakers said they sold vehicles at an average daily rate of
31,090 during the March 1-10 period this year, compared with a daily
rate of 36,493 a year earlier.
   Car sales were down by 18.5 percent during the early March period
compared with last year and truck sales were down 8 percent. Each of
the Big Three reported declines in domestic car sales rates, with
Chrysler Corp. sales dropping 35.9 percent, Ford Motor Co. falling
21.4 percent and General Motors Corp. declining 13.4 percent.
   Analysts speculated that sales were dampened by comparison with
strong results in the year-earlier period and by rising interest
rates that may finally be slowing consumer spending.
   ``That has to cut into the family's disposable income and maybe
they're thinking maybe let the old buggy do longer,'' said analyst
Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. of New York.
   Interest rates have been rising in recent months, partly because
of a credit squeeze engineered by the Federal Reserve to slow
economic activity and thus curb inflation. The prime lending rate _
the bank lending rate used as a benchmark for many types of consumer
loans _ is 11.5 percent, compared with 8.5 percent a year earlier.
   Analysts said automakers were waiting for traditionally good
early spring buying to start. March and April sales traditionally
have reduced automakers' inventories, which are hovering around the
80-day level.
   According to Ward's Automotive Reports, the combined inventory
among the U.S.-based automakers is at its highest level in 19 months.
   Each of the Big Three recently boosted incentive offers in an
effort to stimulate sales and GM temporarily has halted production
at two plants to reduce inventory.
   For the year through March 10, car and light truck sales by the
U.S.-based makers were down 6.9 percent from last year's pace,
falling to a daily rate of 33,838 vehicles from 36,330 last year.
Car sales were down 9.7 percent and truck sales were down by 1.7
percent.
   Chrysler sold cars at a daily rate of 2,471 in early March this
year, down from the 3,852 daily rate in the year-earlier period.
Chrysler's car sales were down 21.4 percent on a year-to-year
comparison.
   Chrysler's light trucks sales were 8.5 percent lower for the
period and up 3.5 percent for the year.
   Ford said its car sales during early March fell to a daily rate
of 6,012 in 1989 from a 7,651 rate during the period last year. For
the year, Ford's car sales were 3.3 percent lower than last year's
rate.
   Ford truck sales were down 20.6 percent in early March from the
same period last year and were off 3.5 percent for the year to date.
   GM said its car sales dropped to a daily rate of 9,175 during the
March 1-10 period this year from the 10,597 rate in early March last
year. GM's car sales for the year ran 14.4 percent behind last
year's pace.
   Light truck sales by GM were up 5.6 percent during early March
and for the year the pace was 5.8 percent behind last year's sales
rate.
</TEXT>
