<FIRST>u f AM-EasternPilots-Glance 1stLd-Writethru   03-14 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern Pilots-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Pilots Earn $21,600 to $167,000 a Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Pilots Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS final graf to ADD average seniority; No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the higher seniority levels, U.S. airline
pilots earn salaries that make them an elite among unionized
employees.
   The nation's 60,000 or so commercial pilots earn an average of
$82,500 a year plus benefits and have starting salaries averaging
around $21,600, according to Future Aviation Professionals of
America in Atlanta.
   Salaries are determined mainly by seniority and the size of
aircraft flown. Pilots typically start out as flight engineers,
regulating fuel levels and performing other functions in the cockpit
but not actually flying planes. They progress to become copilots of
smaller aircraft, then co-pilots of bigger planes, followed by
captains of smaller planes and finally captains of larger craft.
   Under this system, widely used smaller aircraft include Boeing
727s and 737s, as well as DC9s and MD80s made by McDonnell Douglas
Corp. Bigger commercial planes include Boeing 747s and 767s,
McDonnell Douglas DC10s and Lockheed Corp.'s L1011-Tristar.
   Senior captains earn an average $133,000 a year, with the maximum
pay for that category reaching $167,000 plus substantial benefits,
according to FAPA, an aviation career information service.
   The 10,000 to 12,000 pilots who fly corporate jets, by contrast,
start at around $24,000 and earn an average $44,000 a year.
   Many pilots still get their training in the military, but others
attend special flight schools or professional schools.
   Piloting remains a predominantly white male profession. Only
about 1 percent of U.S. airline pilots are women, while fewer than 1
percent are minorities.
   The average age of U.S. pilots is in the range of 33 to 36 years
and average seniority is 15 years of service, according to Future
Aviation Professionals of America.
</TEXT>
