<FIRST>u f AM-Chile-Fruit 1stLd-Writethru f0262 03-14 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Fruit, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0262,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile Tightens Security in Fruit Exporting Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6, `He said...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE with packing
house identified, exporters suspending operations. Pick up 7th pvs, `Authorities
in...' SUBS 19th pvs, `But after...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with possible
motive. Pick up 20th pvs, `Chile is...' Minor editing to trim. Also moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government tightened security on the
handling of fruit exports Tuesday and began a criminal investigation
into the cyanide-tainting of grapes exported to the United States.
   In a nationally broadcast address, Interior Minister Carlos
Caceres vowed that Chile would remain ``a dependable fruit supplier
to the world.''
   He called the contamination a case of communist sabotage.
Communist Party spokesmen denied any involvement.
   The agriculture minister, Jaime de la Sotta, said he would fly to
Washington to discuss the situation with U.S. officials.
   De la Sotta said investigators had identified the packing house
and vineyard that was the source of the tainted grapes. He refused
to identify them.
   But the president of the exporters, Enrique Bruzzone, said the
tainted grapes came from a vineyard and packing house owned by Julia
Saavedra in the Curacavi area, just northwest of Santiago. He said
Ms. Saavedra is an established grower and exporter.
   Bruzzone said members of the exporters association voluntarily
suspended all packing and shipping operations for 72 hours Tuesdat
night to check all the fruit they had in storage. Grape picking was
also reported idled at most fields.
   Earlier, de la Sotta said the government might temporarily stop
all fruit operations and exports.
   Authorities in the United States, Canada and Japan ordered all
Chilean fruit removed from supermarkets and urged consumers not to
eat any fruit they had already purchased.
   Dutch officials said they were testing Chilean grapes, and
Italian officials said they planned to do the same. In West Germany,
the Health Ministry said tighter controls were put on incoming
Chilean produce.
   Authorities in the port of Valparaiso, 75 miles northwest of
Santiago, said loading of U.S.-bound grapes in one Chilean ship was
halted Tuesday.
   But two other ships, of Japanese registry, were being loaded with
600,000 crates to be sent to Philadelphia and Tampa, Fla.,
authorities saied.
   Fruit exporters and growers said the United States may have
overreacted in removing fruit from stores, but they also announced
plans to redouble security in the exporting process. Chemical tests
were increased.
   The U.S decision ``seems logical from the point of view of the
concern over the population's health,'' the exporters and growers
said. They added, however, that it was exaggerated considering the
``huge social and economic impact it has on our country.''
   Nearly 65 percent of Chile's fruit exports _ grapes, melons,
apples and peaches _ go to the United States.
   Export earnings this year had been expected to exceed $850
million, representing more than 10 percent of all export earnings.
Last year's export earnings totaled $581 million.
   De la Sotta said the cyanide found in two clusters of grapes in
Philadelphia on March 2 amounted to 0.52 parts per million. U.S.
officials said a child would have to eat 2,000 grapes to ingest a
fatal dose.
   ``We have increased security in order to ensure that all fruits
leaving our country is totally safe,'' De la Sotta said.
   Caceres said that security was being reinforced ``from the fields
to the port of destination.''
   The U.S. and Japanese embassies in Santiago received anonymous
telephone calls earlier this month saying fruit exports would be
poisoned. An investigation turned up nothing, authorities said.
   A Bush administration source knowledgeable about the
investigation said ``the first message did suggest they were trying
to call attention to the poverty in Chile.'' The source spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   After confirming cyanide in the Philadelphia samples, the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration on Monday urged that the fruit be
removed from stores. The FDA said Tuesday that it had stepped up
tests on Chilean fruit.
   Chile is at the height of the harvesting season and De la Sotta
said it expected to export 102 million to 103 million crates this
season.
   He said about 47 million crates had been shipped. Another 17
milliom are in warehouses awaiting shipment or en route to various
countries.
   Adm. Jose Merino, navy commander and head of the law-making
military junta, blamed the United States, as well as the communists,
for the incident.
   ``This is yet another roguish act of the United States,'' said
Merino, a frequent critic of the United States. ``Americans think
were are all banana republics. Chile is not a banana republic.''
   Merino said Chile should seek alternative markets for its fruit.
   Chile has been under right-wing military rule since September
1973, when the armed forces ousted the elected government of Marxist
President Salvador Allende. The coup was led by Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, the current president.
</TEXT>
