<SECOND>AM-Sears-Sprint,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears To Be One Of Sprint's Largest Customers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. will become one of
US Sprint's largest customers under an agreement in which Sprint
will provide long-distance connections between about 20,000 Sears
locations nationwide, Sprint said Tuesday.
   Specific terms of the contract were not disclosed, but Sprint
described it as a ``multimillion-dollar communications services''
agreement that ``significantly extends and enhances an agreement
previously reached between Sears and US Sprint in 1988 and makes
(Sears) one of US Sprint's largest users.''
   ``Most US Sprint products and services are covered under the
agreement,'' the company said.
   Selby Shaver, senior vice president of data center operations and
voice telecommunications for Sears Technology Services, said US
Sprint will carry most of Sears' long-distance traffic.
   US Sprint President William Esrey called the agreement ``a
significant milestone in US Sprint history.''
   ``We consider the Sears account to be a strong endorsement of our
company,'' Esrey said.
   US Sprint, based in Kansas City, Mo., provides long-distance
domestic and international voice, data and video-conferencing
services and products. Some of its major customers include General
Electric Co., Westinghouse Electric Corp. and Nynex Corp.
   Sprint's long-distance revenues in 1988 totaled $3.4 billion, up
27 percent from $2.67 billion in 1987. But it had an operating loss
of $409 million for the year, in part due to a $195 million charge
for a restructuring.
   Sprint is a joint venture between United Telecommunications Inc.
of Kansas City, Mo., and GTE Corp., with United Telecommunications
holding the controlling share.
   Sears Technology Services is a wholly owned subsidiary of
Chicago-based Sears, whose businesses include the Sears Merchandise
Group, Allstate Insurance Co., Coldwell Banker and the Dean Witter
Financial Services Group.
</TEXT>
