<FIRST>r f AM-InsiderTrading     03-14 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Convicted In Waldbaum Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stockbroker was convicted of fraud and perjury
charges Tuesday for a $250,000 scheme to buy Waldbaum Inc. stock
with inside information that A&amp;P was going to buy the supermarket
chain.
   Chestman, a stockbroker and first vice president of Gruntal &amp;
Co., was convicted on all counts by a federal court jury in its
second day of deliberations.
   He was charged with buying 11,000 shares of Waldbaum on Nov. 26,
1986, just before the public announcement of the sale to A&amp;P and
just after being told about the deal by one of his clients, a
relative by marriage of Waldbaum's president, Ira Waldbaum.
   Chestman also was charged with lying to the Securities and
Exchange Commission about receiving inside information from the
client, Keith Loeb.
   Loeb, who testified for the government in a plea bargain through
which he avoided criminal prosecution, paid about $50,000 in fines
and disgorged profits to settle an SEC civil action.
   Chestman, 41, of the Long Island community of Lawrence, faces a
maximum penalty of five years in prison on each of the 31 counts of
which he was convicted: 20 counts of securities fraud, 10 counts of
mail fraud and one count of perjury.
   He also faces a maximum fine of about $500,000 _ twice his
illegal profits _ when he is sentenced April 25 by U.S. District
Judge John M. Walker Jr.
   Chestman, who is on unpaid leave from Gruntal, remains free on
bail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
