<FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-HertzSettlement     03-14 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hertz Settlement,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hertz Agrees to Settle Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hertz Corp. agreed to pay $72,980 in civil
penalties and costs Tuesday to settle a lawsuit filed by the
district attorney's office after one of its prosecutors tried to
rent a car at a special rate and found it unavailable.
   Deputy District Attorney Steven Suzukawa launched the Consumer
Protection Division investigation after he telephoned Hertz in
October 1987 to inquire about low weekend rental rates he had seen
advertised in Sports Illustrated magazine, according to a summary of
the case issued by district attorney spokesman Al Albergate.
   Suzukawa was told that the special rates were not available in
California, although the ad failed to state that.
   Hertz revised its ad as soon as it was notified, Albergate said,
and cooperated in negotiating a settlement of the case. He said the
company also has been seeking ``clearer guidelines for advertising
pertaining to the car rental business.''
   The final settlement includes an injunction prohibiting Hertz
from advertising rates on cars when the rates are not generally
available and requiring Hertz to have a supply of advertised cars
sufficient to meet a reasonable demand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
